[PlyCount "6"]

{I am very happy to present to you my new course, The Smyslov Ruy Lopez!} 1. e4 e5 {When choosing the topic, I was looking for a reliable weapon for Black to add to my repertoire when playing vs 1.e4.  While I’ve been playing all sorts of Sicilians throughout my career, I have added the 1...e5 as well some years ago. I am quite an aggressive player and I was happy to play against the Scotch or against the Italian, where Black can choose from various systems, positional or more tactical ones. However, I was struggling against the Ruy Lopez, as the positions one gets are quite far from being nice for an aggressive player.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 {This is when I thought about 3...g6. I remembered seeing some nice games of Grandmasters Shahriyar Mamedyarov and Kateryna Lagno and I decided to check it out.  After extensive research, I now believe that the Smyslov Ruy Lopez is not only great as a surprise weapon but it can be also used on a regular basis, as the arising positions are strategically sound and lead to very complex, interesting battles. I think that players who are new to 1...e5 and want to add it to their repertoire might find this a very good solution, as the lines they have to remember are not that many and the structures you will learn will be very useful, as one encounters them when playing other systems of the Ruy Lopez as well, so it will make it easier to later add new Ruy Lopez systems to your repertoire.   There are quite some novelties I discovered and presented in the course, so I believe that players of any level will benefit from studying the material. I definitely plan on using them in my games!  Some sources suggest this system to be called the Fianchetto Ruy Lopez, but I used to think of it as the Modern Ruy Lopez! Why Modern? Because of the early g6 move. While researching the history of the line, I came to know that the actual name it has is the Smyslov line, named after the World Champion Vasily Smyslov. If one's a bit familiar with the long Ruy Lopez systems (Breyer, Chigorin, Zaitsev...), one might know that after completing the development with Be7 and 0-0, one of the most common plans Black has is to improve the position of the e7- Bishop by fianchettoing it (playing Re8, Bf8, g6, Bg7).   To me, the whole idea of the 3...g6, or (as we will refer to it) The Smyslov Ruy Lopez is to save time and place the dark squared bishop immediately on g7! It sounds very good of course, saving so many tempi, but there are some drawbacks. Instead of spending just one move on developing the dark squared bishop (by playing Be7 or Bc5) we spend two moves (g6, Bg7) and White might try to punish us for doing so.  Well, here comes the thing I like the most about our Smyslov system: when White tries to punish Black immediately for 'losing' time, by playing the principled 4.d4, with precise play, Black is doing perfectly fine! The best way for White to react is actually the slow plan, 0-0, c3, d3, h3, Re1, Nd2-f1-g3, where White will keep a little edge. But let's agree that this is somewhat counterintuitive, as the logic suggests to us that Black should be fine there since we've saved a few tempi, right? I believe this paradox is the main reason White's score is not that impressive against this system, only 51.6%, compared to 55.9% after 3...a6 and 58.8% after 3...Nf6.  According to my database, 3...g6 was first played in 1863 by the Danish player Martin Severin From. In 1883 it was taken over by the World Champion William Steinitz who won a few very nice games with it! The next World Champion to popularize this move was Vassily Smyslov, who played it from time to time during his whole career. Later on, the line was actually named in his honor. These days, 3...g6 is an often guest in Top GM's games. World Champion Magnus Carlsen has given it a few tries, but the one who has the most games played recently in it is GM Shakhriyar Mamedyarov who is known to have an uncompromised and spectacular style of play.   One might wonder, why choose the Smyslov Ruy Lopez instead of the Cozio one 3...Nge7? (Well, even though the two might look similar in a way and they might sometimes even transpose, there are a few important differences. By playing 3...g6 instead of 3...Nge7, Black stays flexible, keeping the option of developing the Knight to f6, which is often much better placed there than on e7, as it puts pressure on the e4-pawn and avoids positions with superfluous Knights (two pieces which fight for the same squares, in the Cozio line, the e7 and c6 Knights). I believe this is an important advantage of choosing the Smyslov line. Another one is avoiding the lines arising after 3...Nge7 4.c3 d5 5.Nxe5 (recommended by Erwin l’Ami in his course on the Cozio), as they tend to lead to very dangerous structures strategically wise (with doubled c-pawns) which require high precision from Black and are quite difficult to handle.  By studying the Smyslov Ruy Lopez, one will not only learn the theory but also get the feeling of how to play in a number of structures. Remembering things move by move is important, however, one can’t always rely on their memory only.   That’s why my approach to openings is to build a system based on ideas, this makes things much easier. If one has a bad day and can’t remember how to play at 13.Bg5 for example, they might instead remember a funny, but very useful concept of “A Bishop on top of a diagonal”, which appears quite often in the course. You will know that the way to fight against those Bishops is to start a hunt on them.  I am very optimistic about the Smyslov Ruy Lopez, which I think is a great addition to one’s repertoire as it gets us rich positions, where the player who knows better the plans and the ideas will have the upper hand!} *

