1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 {A move of rich history, preferred by many GMs and even World Champions! It has become very fashionable lately, one of its most prominent experts being GM Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, who has played it extensively.   I am very optimistic about the Smyslov Ruy Lopez, which I think is great not only as a surprise weapon but also as one to be used on a regular basis, as it gets us rich positions, where the player who knows better the plans and the ideas will have the upper hand!} 4. d4 {[%csl Re5,Gf8][%cal Gf8g7,Gf8e7,Gf8c5,Ga7a6] One of the most critical lines where White tries to punish Black immediately for 'losing' time.} exd4 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gc1g5,Gf3d4,Gc2c3,Gb5c6]} 5. Bg5 {[%csl Rd8,Re7,Rf6,Rg7][%cal Gg5d8] Very energic play. White wants to exploit the weakness of the dark squares by forcing Black to trade the dark squared Bishop.} Be7 {[%csl Rh8][%cal Gh2h4,Gg5f4,Gg5e7,Gg5f6,Gf6h8]} ({Forced, as} 5... Nge7 $4 6. Bf6 {runs into}) ({while} 5... f6 {weakens too much the Kingside.}) 6. Bxe7 Qxe7 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gb5c6] White has a choice now, to get back the sacrificed pawn immediately, or to delay it a bit. Let's examine both options!} 7. Bxc6 dxc6 {[%cal Gc8g4] Awakening our light squared Bishop!} 8. Qxd4 {[%csl Rh8][%cal Gd4h8]} Nf6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf6e4] Developing the Knight and attacking e4.} 9. Nc3 {[%cal Ge1g1,Ge1c1] White keeps both castling options opened!} Bg4 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg4f3,Gf3d2,Ge1c1] Asking White an important question: do they want to allow us to spoil their pawn structure by taking on f3 or not?} 10. Nd2 {White keep their pawn structure healthy.} c5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc5d4] Where should the Queen retreat to?} 11. Qe3 O-O-O {[%csl Gg4]} 12. h3 {[%cal Gh3g4]} Bd7 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gd7c6,Gc6e4] Once again, the best position for our Bishop is on c6, from where it both attacks the e4-pawn and covers our King.} *

