1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 {A move of rich history, preferred by many GMs and even World Champions! It has become very fashionable lately, one of its most prominent experts being GM Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, who has played it extensively.   I am very optimistic about the Smyslov Ruy Lopez, which I think is great not only as a surprise weapon but also as one to be used on a regular basis, as it gets us rich positions, where the player who knows better the plans and the ideas will have the upper hand!} 4. Bxc6 $6 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Gc8g4,Ga7a6] A suboptimal move, as it gives up the pair of bishops and only helps Black to develop. Compared to the Exchange Variation of the Ruy Lopez, we even won a tempi, as White took on c6 without us playing a6.} dxc6 {[%csl Rc6,Gc7][%cal Gc8g4,Gf3e5,Gd2d3,Gd3d4,Gc6c5,Gc6d4,Gg8e7,Ge7c6] Opening up the diagonal for our light squared Bishop.} 5. d4 {White wants to get to an endgame with an extra pawn on the Kingside.} exd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Nxd4 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gg7a1] A structure reminding us somewhat of the Berlin endgames. However, there are a few important differences: our Knight is still on g8 (not on f6) and it gives us the additional idea of playing f5; the dark squared Bishop has a nice opened long diagonal.} Bg7 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg7d4] Making White's only active piece, the Knight on d4, to give up its position.} 8. Ne2 f5 {[%csl Rc2,Re4][%cal Gc8f5,Gf5c2] Opening up the position even more for our Bishop pair!} *

