1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 {A move of rich history, preferred by many GMs and even World Champions! It has become very fashionable lately, one of its most prominent experts being GM Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, who has played it extensively.   I am very optimistic about the Smyslov Ruy Lopez, which I think is great not only as a surprise weapon but also as one to be used on a regular basis, as it gets us rich positions, where the player who knows better the plans and the ideas will have the upper hand!} 4. Bxc6 $6 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Gc8g4,Ga7a6] A suboptimal move, as it gives up the pair of bishops and only helps Black to develop. Compared to the Exchange Variation of the Ruy Lopez, we even won a tempi, as White took on c6 without us playing a6.} dxc6 {[%csl Rc6,Gc7][%cal Gg8e7,Ge7c6,Gc6c5,Gc6d4,Gd2d3,Gd2d4,Gf3e5,Gc8g4] Opening up the diagonal for our light squared Bishop.} 5. d3 {[%csl Ga7,Gb7,Gc6,Gc7][%cal Gb7b6,Gc6c5,Ga7a5] This setup reminds us of the Rossolimo, but there is an important difference - here, our c-pawns are on c7 and c6 compared to the Rossolimo, where they are on c5 and c6.   It may seem like a minor difference, but it's actually very important because our dream pawn setup on the Queenside is c5, b6, a5, c7 - all on dark squares- where the pawns protect each over and are very solid, in the same time - keeping the c6 square free for one of our light pieces to take - either the Knight (Ng8-e7-c6), or the Bishop.  In the Rossolimo, because the pawns are 'by default' on c6 and c5 - Black's Queenside is easier to be attacked and the light pieces struggle on more passive positions, as they don't have the important c6 square for their maneuvers. That's the reason why here, Black is doing perfectly fine!} Bg7 {[%csl Re4,Ge5][%cal Gg7e5,Gg8e7,Ge8g8,Gd8d4,Gb1d2,Gb1c3,Gd3e4,Gf3e5] Preparing to finish the development on the Kingside.} 6. Nbd2 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gd2c4,Gc4e5] White tries to bring the Knight to c4, from where it will pressure the e5-pawn.} Ne7 {[%cal Gd2c4]} 7. Nc4 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gc4e5,Gf3e5]} f6 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gf6e5,Gc1e3,Gc2c3] White has succeeded in temporarily closing Black's dark squared Bishop.} 8. Be3 b6 {[%cal Gc6c5,Gd3d4] With the same c5 idea, to control the d4-square.} 9. d4 {While it looks tempting, it's actually Black who will benefit most from opening up the long dark diagonal and the centre, as we are the ones to have the Bishop pair! White's activity is only visually pleasing and it will fade away.} exd4 10. Qxd4 Qxd4 11. Nxd4 Bd7 {[%csl Ga7,Gb6,Gc6,Gc7][%cal Gd7c6,Ge8c8,Gc8b7] Preparing the long castle.} *

