1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 {A move of rich history, preferred by many GMs and even World Champions! It has become very fashionable lately, one of its most prominent experts being GM Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, who has played it extensively.   I am very optimistic about the Smyslov Ruy Lopez, which I think is great not only as a surprise weapon but also as one to be used on a regular basis, as it gets us rich positions, where the player who knows better the plans and the ideas will have the upper hand!} 4. h4 $5 {[%cal Gh4h5] An interesting move, trying to attack Black's Kingside pawn construction immediately!} Nf6 {[%csl Gh5][%cal Gf6h5] Getting ready to capture on h5 with the Knight in case White advances their h-pawn.} 5. d4 exd4 {[%cal Ge4e5,Ge1g1]} 6. e5 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Ge5f6]} Ng4 {[%csl Gc8,Re5,Rf3,Gg4,Rh4][%cal Gh4h5,Ge1g1,Gg4d1,Gg4e5,Gc2c3] A great square for our Knight, since the h-pawn is already on h4, and can't disturb it!} 7. O-O h6 {[%csl Ge5,Gg5][%cal Rf4g5,Gh6g5,Gc1f4,Gd1e2,Ge2e5] Once again, protecting the vital g5-square!} 8. Nxd4 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gd1g4] Getting back the central pawn and attacking the Knight on g4.} Qxh4 {[%csl Rg1,Rh2][%cal Gh4h2,Gd4f3] A 'little' threat- mate on h2!} 9. Bf4 {[%csl Rh2][%cal Gf4h2] Covering the h2-square and preparing to make our Queen go away by playing 10.Bg3.} Bg7 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gg7e5,Ge8g8] Once again, the most natural way to continue the development.} 10. Bg3 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gg3h4]} Qg5 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gg4e5,Gg5e5,Gg7e5,Gc6e5] Playing against the e5-pawn. We might not be able to take it for now, but nothing will stop us from doing so after castling!} 11. Nf3 {[%csl Ge5,Rg5][%cal Gf3g5,Gf3e5]} Qd8 12. Nc3 {[%csl Rc8] White has finished the development and has some compensation for the sacrificed pawn thank to the extra space.} O-O {[%csl Gb5,Gc8][%cal Gd7d6,Gd7c6,Gb5c6,Ga7a6] The King is safe! The next step is to get our light squared Bishop into the game! We can start by playing 13...a6, who knows, maybe White will make our task easier by taking on c6... If they retreat instead, we can sacrifice the pawn back by playing 14...d6, but open our light squared Bishop, granting us a balanced position.} *

