1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 {A move of rich history, preferred by many GMs and even World Champions! It has become very fashionable lately, one of its most prominent experts being GM Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, who has played it extensively.   I am very optimistic about the Smyslov Ruy Lopez, which I think is great not only as a surprise weapon but also as one to be used on a regular basis, as it gets us rich positions, where the player who knows better the plans and the ideas will have the upper hand!} 4. d3 {A quieter, positional approach, aiming for a long-term strategical battle. I find it harmless for Black and I believe we can even get ambitious in this line!} Bg7 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gc2c3,Gb1c3]} 5. Nc3 {[%csl Gd3,Ge1,Ge4,Rf6][%cal Gg8e7,Gg8f6,Gf6e4] The position resulting from this move order may easily transpose to the 5.0-0 line, so you might ask yourself why to examine it separately... The answer is simple, it is a little positional trap that White has set up using this move order. The most natural reply 5...Nge7 would now be an inaccuracy, as White has not yet castled and will be able to play h4-h5, as our Knight has also committed already to the e7-square and can not go to f6 in order to prevent h5.} h6 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gh6g5,Ga7a6] A useful waiting move, which was part of our plan anyway! We prevent a potential Bg5 and keep out Knight on g8 until White decides to castle.  Now after 6.h4 Black can play 6...a6 first, asking the 'eternal question' and if White takes on c6, then 7.Bxc6 dxc6, opening up the light squared Bishop which will have a very nice square on g4, while if 7.Bc4, Black cand continue with 7...Nf6, stopping h5.} 6. O-O Nge7 {Now the Knight can safely develop to e7.} 7. Be3 {[%cal Gd3d4] The g5-square is no longer available for the Bishop, so White chooses another plan, one connected with d4.} Nd4 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gd4b5] One of the most efficient strategies in chess is to guess your opponent's plan and then stop it; that's exactly what we do here, not allowing White to play d4.} *

