1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 {A move of rich history, preferred by many GMs and even World Champions! It has become very fashionable lately, one of its most prominent experts being GM Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, who has played it extensively.   I am very optimistic about the Smyslov Ruy Lopez, which I think is great not only as a surprise weapon but also as one to be used on a regular basis, as it gets us rich positions, where the player who knows better the plans and the ideas will have the upper hand!} 4. d3 {A quieter, positional approach, aiming for a long-term strategical battle. I find it harmless for Black and I believe we can even get ambitious in this line!} Bg7 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gc2c3,Gb1c3]} 5. c3 {Another tricky move order; one might think that it is again an waiting move, trying to lure our Knight to e7 before White has castled in order to then attack with h4-h5. However, it is not the case here, let's see why.} Nge7 6. O-O O-O {[%csl Ge7,Gg7][%cal Gc1g5,Gd3d4,Gf1e1] I like this position for Black a lot, as it is though Black has spared a lot of tempi compared to any of the long Ruy Lopez lines where Black's Knight is on f6 and the Bishop on e7 and then Black spends a lot of moves to bring that Bishop to g7 and then they go away with the Knight to prepare f5!} 7. Re1 {[%csl Re3,Re5,Gf5,Rg3,Rg6][%cal Gg6f5,Ge1e5,Gb1d2,Gd2f1] The 'a la Ruy Lopez' slow approach; White prepares to reroute the Knight from b1 to d2, then f1, while eyeing the e5-pawn at the same time, so that Black can't comfortably play d5.} d6 {[%csl Ge5,Ge7][%cal Gd6e5,Gc8g4,Gf7f5] No problem! We open up our c8-Bishop, consolidate the e5-pawn and prepare another break-through in the centre: f5!} 8. h3 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gh3g4] Prophylaxis against Black's Bg4 idea.} f5 {[%csl Rb1,Rc1,Rc8][%cal Gf8f2] It is now clear that the position is much easier to play for Black as we're ahead with the development (White has 2 light pieces on their initial positions, while we, only one) and we are the first ones to attack the enemy's King!} *

