1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 {A move of rich history, preferred by many GMs and even World Champions! It has become very fashionable lately, one of its most prominent experts being GM Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, who has played it extensively.   I am very optimistic about the Smyslov Ruy Lopez, which I think is great not only as a surprise weapon but also as one to be used on a regular basis, as it gets us rich positions, where the player who knows better the plans and the ideas will have the upper hand!} 4. O-O {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc2c3] Together with 4.c3, this move is one of the most played ones after 3...g6. The ideas are similar to the ones in the 4.c3 line. The difference is that White first brings their King to safety and only then starts to fight for the centre. On the other hand, it allows us some extra time to finish our development as well.} Bg7 5. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4] The idea is clear, prepare 6.d4.} a6 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ga6b5] Asking the b5-Bishop where does it want to retreat to.} 6. Ba4 {The main move.} (6. Bxc6 {An interesting try, giving up the Bishop pair in order to obtain a pawn majority on the Kingside and good control in the centre.} dxc6 {[%cal Gc8g4] Opening up the diagonal for our c8-Bishop.} 7. d4 {There's no time for White to play 7.h3, preventing 7...Bg4 as then, after either 7...Qd3 or 7...c5 White won't be able to play d4 anymore.} exd4 8. cxd4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] White's central pawns look very nice, but they're quite unstable and we have an easy way to attack them.} Bg4 {[%csl Rd4,Rf3][%cal Gg7d4,Gd8d4,Gg4d1] Pinning the f3-Knight, thus attacking the d4-pawn.} 9. Nc3 {White correctly argues that the d4-pawn is untouchable for now as after 9...Bxf3 10.Qxf3 Bxd4 11.Bf4 Black will be behind with the development and very likely to run into big trouble over the d-file.} Qf6 {[%csl Rd4,Rf3][%cal Gg7d4,Gg4d1,Ge8c8] An important move, getting ready to castle long, but in the same time, keeping the pressure over f3 and d4. #1}) (6. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4f7] The Bishop goes immediately to the a2-g8 diagonal, keeping an eye on the f7-pawn.} f5 {We have seen this idea in a slightly different position in the lines with 4.c3. The only difference is that compared to that position, there is an extra move for each side, short castle for White and Bg7 for Black. However the ideas are still the same, we take advantage of the fact that White's Bishop is exposed on c4 and once White take exf5 we can play d5. Let's take the best tried White has one by one and look into them!} 7. d4 {[%cal Ge1e7] Another try to open up the central files against our King.} fxe4 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Ge4f3] Free central pawn alert!} 8. Nxe5 d5 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gd5c4] Closing up the diagonal for White's light squared Bishop as fast as we can to save our King from trouble. #2}) 6... d6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gc8g4,Gd6e5] Consolidating our e5-pawn and opening up the diagonal for the light squared Bishop.} 7. d4 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gd4d5,Ga4e8] The main move, gaining control in the centre and trying to make use of the pin on the a4-e8 diagonal.} (7. h3 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gh3g4] Not allowing Black's Bishop to g4.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf6e4] Developing with a tempo!} 8. Re1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ge1e4]} O-O {The King is safe now and Black is ahead with the development already.} 9. d3 {9.d4 can be met by 9...b5 and then 10.-- Bb7 with positions very similar to the ones resulting after 7.d4 immediately, but with our Bishop much better placed on b7 than on d7.} Re8 {[%cal Gd6d5] The plan is to prepare d5, the first step is to protect the e5-pawn.} 10. Nbd2 h6 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gh6g5] Covering the g5-square is just a useful move so that after playing d5 we'd be able to develop our Bishop to e6 if needed without White's Knight being able to disturb it by Ng5. #3}) 7... Bd7 {[%cal Gd7a4] Covering up the a4-e8 diagonal thus neutralizing White's pin over it and offering White a choice, to close the centre by means of 8.d5, to take the pressure off by taking on e5, or to maintain the pressure by continuing their development. Let's examine the best tries.} 8. Re1 {The move which was played the most according to my database. White protects the e4-pawn and wants to delay a bit the moment of decision for where their remaining light pieces should move to.} (8. d5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gd5c6] White closes the centre heading to a structure that reminds us of the King's Indian. Our plan will then be to finish our development by castling short and then attacking White's pawn chain by means of either f5 or b5 if White will play c4.} Nce7 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Gd7a4] Having less space, the trades are favorable for us, as it will leave more room for our remaining pieces to manoeuver around.} 9. Bxd7+ {The main move, even though White agrees with the trade of one pair of light pieces, giving Black extra space for the remaining ones, they argue that it will weaken our control over the e6-square and it will be more difficult to play f5 as then White's Knight will be able to jump to g5 and the to e6.} Qxd7 10. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gc4d5,Gb1c3] Consolidating the centre and planning to develop the Knight to c3.} h6 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gh6g5,Gf7f5] The solution to the weakness of our e6-square after we play f5 is quite simple, cover the g5 square first so that White's Knight isn't able to use it.#4}) (8. Bg5 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gg5d8] Asking Black a question, on which square to place the g8-Knight in order to cover the Queen.} Nge7 {We go for this move in order to enable the later ideas with f5 should White close the center with 9.d5.} 9. d5 {Closing up the centre and forcing our Knight to its initial square.} Nb8 {The Knight on b8 is of course not a great piece, so we would love for White to capture on d7 and allow our Knight take that square.} 10. Bc2 {Making it more difficult for Black to develop the b8-Knight.} h6 {However, given that the position has a closed character, time becomes less important and we may slowly finish our development.} 11. Be3 O-O {The idea is still to attack White's pawn chain by means of f5. It will be great it we'll then capture back on f5 with the Bishop, as it would make room for our b8-Knight, enabling the move Nd7. #5}) 8... Nf6 {When allowed, we don't hesitate to bring our Knight to the active f6-square.} 9. Nbd2 O-O {Black is the first one to complete the development. White will have to decide what plan to choose now.} 10. h3 {Prohylaxy against a potential Bg4.} exd4 {A concrete approach, we force White to either give up on the pair of Bishops or to agree on trading the light squared one.} 11. cxd4 Nb4 {There is no time for White to play 12.Bb3, as it will be met by 12...Nd3 with a very unpleasant fork.} 12. Bxd7 Qxd7 {13.-- Nd3 is still a serious threat.} 13. Nf1 c5 {Once again, we do our best to attack White's central pawns.} *

