1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 {A move of rich history, preferred by many GMs and even World Champions! It has become very fashionable lately, one of its most prominent experts being GM Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, who has played it extensively.   I am very optimistic about the Smyslov Ruy Lopez, which I think is great not only as a surprise weapon but also as one to be used on a regular basis, as it gets us rich positions, where the player who knows better the plans and the ideas will have the upper hand!} 4. c3 {The idea of this setup is to prepare d4, force Black to take and then recapture with the c3-pawn in order to get some nice control in the centre. The central pawn structure advantage will grant White more space for their light pieces to maneuver around, as well as prospectives of an attack on the Kingside. Black's counterplay will be linked with combining pawns advance on the Queenside (in order to secure important squares for their light pieces) with attacking White's central pawns (e4 and d4).   After years of playing the Ruy Lopez with both colors, I find that it's easier to go wrong while playing with the White pieces, as the 'visual' advantage of the space tends to make one over-optimistic about their chances. It often leads to getting over-ambitious and pushing too hard which is of course convenient for Black. Therefore, arm yourself with patience and you'll be ready to learn the most important ideas Black has in this structure!} a6 {We want White to decide on which diagonal should their Bishop land.} 5. Bc4 {Is an interesting and logical try, eyeing the f7-pawn with ideas of d4, Ng5 to make it feel even more uncomfortable. However, it allows Black an unexpected move!} f5 {The pawn was weak on f7, why not make it challenge White's centre then? This move goes against the basic chess principles, which say that one needs to finish the development first and only then go for breakthroughs. Despite it, White doesn't have a good way to punish our 'eccentric' move!} 6. d3 {The most logical and solid move.} Bg7 {Continuing our development. An important idea to keep in mind is closing up White's dark squared Bishop by means of f4.} 7. Ng5 {A non-dangerous one move threat.} Nh6 {Covering the f7-square and threatening 8...f4, which would leave White's g5-Knight unprotected.} *

