1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 {A move of rich history, preferred by many GMs and even World Champions! It has become very fashionable lately, one of its most prominent experts being GM Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, who has played it extensively.   I am very optimistic about the Smyslov Ruy Lopez, which I think is great not only as a surprise weapon but also as one to be used on a regular basis, as it gets us rich positions, where the player who knows better the plans and the ideas will have the upper hand!} 4. c3 {The idea of this setup is to prepare d4, force Black to take and then recapture with the c3-pawn in order to get some nice control in the centre. The central pawn structure advantage will grant White more space for their light pieces to maneuver around, as well as prospectives of an attack on the Kingside. Black's counterplay will be linked with combining pawns advance on the Queenside (in order to secure important squares for their light pieces) with attacking White's central pawns (e4 and d4).   After years of playing the Ruy Lopez with both colors, I find that it's easier to go wrong while playing with the White pieces, as the 'visual' advantage of the space tends to make one over-optimistic about their chances. It often leads to getting over-ambitious and pushing too hard which is of course convenient for Black. Therefore, arm yourself with patience and you'll be ready to learn the most important ideas Black has in this structure!} a6 {We want White to decide on which diagonal should their Bishop land.} 5. Ba4 {Avoiding all the 5...f5 drama. It doesn't work now as after 6.d4 fxe4 7.Nxe5 we no longer have the 7...d5 move with tempo (compared to when White had the Bishop on c4).} Bg7 {We go for the most natural developing move.} 6. d4 {Forcing Black to take on d4 as there's no other good way of continuing our development. 6...Nge7 would be met by 7.d5, 6...Nf6 drops the e5-pawn, while 6...d6 allows 7.Bxc6 ruining our pawn structure.} exd4 7. cxd4 b5 {Making sure to be able to play d6 or d5 without worrying about White taking on c6. White now has two options, both of them viable and played extensively.} 8. Bb3 {The most natural move, pressuring the f7-pawn and not allowing Black to play d5.} (8. Bc2 {White argues that they don't need to lose a tempo on playing 8. Bb3, as after an eventual Na5, the Bishop will end up on c2 anyway. However, it allows Black an additional idea!} d6 {The 'classical' approach, one which leads to more complex battles. I would recommend choosing it against opponents you are confident you could outplay. Otherwise 8...d5 is a simpler way to equalize.} 9. h3 {A slow, python-style approach. White wants to prove that their space advantage (thanks to the central d4- and e4-pawns) will be decisive and Black will struggle to find good places for their pieces.} Nf6 {The main idea for Black in this setup is to attack White's central pawns and make one of them move forward. It will either make the pawn that moves weak and a target for us to attack, or it will weaken important central squares.} 10. O-O O-O 11. Nc3 {Both sides do their best to finish the development.} Bb7 {Staying true to our plan of building-up pressure against White's central pawns.} 12. Re1 {Prophylactical move, over-protecting the e4-pawn.} Re8 {Another one bites... the e4-pawn! With the development complete for both sides, White's task is now to come up with a plan. Let's examine the most played and most natural tries. #1}) 8... Nge7 {Continuing the development and preparing to castle short.} 9. O-O O-O {Both sides have brought their Kings to safety and it is now White to choose from a variety of plans.} 10. Nc3 {The most logical try, a natural developing move which was played most.} Na5 {We stay true to our ideas, trying to either win the pair of Bishops or drive White's light-squared Bishop away from controlling the d5-square.} 11. Bc2 d6 {Getting ready to pin White's f3-Knight by bringing the Bishop to g4.} 12. h3 {A useful waiting move that stops our light squared Bishop from developing to g4.} c5 {We are ready now to attack White's central pawns and make them decide whether to close up the centre with 13.d5, simplify the position by taking on c5 or maintain the pressure in the centre. It is always good when we make our opponents face choices, as what might seem a natural decision for us, might be challenging for others. #2} *

