1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 {A move of rich history, preferred by many GMs and even World Champions! It has become very fashionable lately, one of its most prominent experts being GM Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, who has played it extensively.   I am very optimistic about the Smyslov Ruy Lopez, which I think is great not only as a surprise weapon but also as one to be used on a regular basis, as it gets us rich positions, where the player who knows better the plans and the ideas will have the upper hand!} 4. d4 {One of the most critical lines where White tries to punish Black immediately for losing time.} exd4 5. c3 {Sacrificing a pawn to get the initiative.} dxc3 6. Nxc3 h6 {Not allowing White to play Bg5 anymore.} 7. O-O Bg7 {Black is behind with the development but has an extra pawn. If allowed to play Nge7 and then castle short, Black will solve all the opening problems and will just have a healthy extra pawn.} 8. Bd2 {A slightly different approach- White wants to bring first the Knight to d5, then the Bishop to c3 in order to trade Black's best piece- the Bishop on g7.} (8. Be3 {Completing the development and preparing Qd2.} Nge7 9. Qd2 {Not allowing Black to castle, as the pawn on h6 is hanging.} d6 10. Rac1 {White places one of the rooks on the semi-open c-file and asks Black how they plan to conclude the development since our king is stuck in the center for now because of the weakness of the h6 pawn. White places one of the rooks on the semi-opened c-file and asks Black how are they planning to finish the development since our King is stuck in the centre for now because of the weakness of the h6-pawn.} a6 {Step 1, we want to get rid of the unpleasant pin and make White decide where to place the light squared Bishop.} 11. Be2 {The only square where White's Bishop can't be disturbed by Black's forces.} (11. Ba4 Bd7 {Making sure we won't get in trouble because of the pin.} 12. h4 {Preventing a potential g5, after which Black would be able to castle short.} b5 {Another question to White's Bishop.} 13. Bb3 {It is indeed the best diagonal for White's light squared Bishop, but unfortunately, White isn't able to keep it.} Na5 {Winning the pair of Bishops, as if White's Bishop retreats from b3, we'll be able to continue with 14... Nc4, trading the other Bishop.} 14. Nd5 {A double attack; the Knight on a5 and the c7-pawn are hanging.} Nxb3 15. axb3 (15. Nxc7+ {would be a blunder, as after} Qxc7 {Black wins material.}) 15... Nxd5 {Trading pieces is convenient for the part who has extra material.} 16. exd5 Kf8 {Black has the pair of Bishops and an extra pawn. The problem is with the King, which is stuck in the centre for the moment, and the somewhat weak c7-pawn. In order to solve these problems, we will bring the King to h7 and then occupy the e-file with the h8-Rook. We might also need to secure the c7-pawn by playing Rc8. White doesn't have any breakthroughs and the compensation for the sacrificed pawn is good enough only for keeping the game balanced. #1}) (11. Bc4 {Makes the rook on 'c1' look useless.} Be6 {As mentioned before, the trades are favorable for us, as we have an extra pawn.} 12. Nd5 {Trying to get the pair of Bishops.} Bxd5 13. exd5 Ne5 {And yet another trade!} 14. Nxe5 dxe5 {Black has solved all the problems! The e-file is no longer opened, so our King is safe and we also plan on playing 15...Nf5 (both protecting the h6-pawn and wanting to trade our N for the dark squared B), after which short castle will follow! Development completed and an extra pawn, sounds good! #2}) 11... Be6 {Black would love to play d5 if allowed!} 12. Nd5 Ng8 $1 {There are other ways to continue, but I like this move a lot, as it highlights the downside of White's placing the Bishop on e2: the e-file is over-crowded with White pieces now, therefore there's no danger for our King in the centre and we can regroup! The Knight will be much better placed on f6 now, as it will target the e4-pawn and threaten Ng4 as well!} 13. Nf4 Bd7 {We can't allow White to mess with our pawn structure on the Kingside!} 14. Bc4 Nf6 {Black has solved once again the opening problems! We are ready to play g5 and then castle (can't castle right away, as the g6-pawn is hanging). Another idea to keep in mind is Ng4, trying to trade White's dark squared Bishop. #3}) (8. Bf4 $6 {Looks natural, but is already imprecise, as the Bishop will be exposed here to g5.} Nge7 9. Qd2 {White tries to stop Black from castling by targeting the h6-pawn.} d6 {Opening the c8-h3 diagonal for the light squared Bishop and planning to complete the development by playing g5 with tempo, thus protecting the h6-pawn and then short castle will follow. White will struggle to prove the compensation for the sacrificed pawn. #4}) 8... d6 {Black has to simply continue the development - first step - open the c8-h3 diagonal for the light squared Bishop.} 9. Nd5 {The threat is now 10.Ba5 - attacking the c7 pawn. Black has to do something about it, as it would be impossible to defend the pawn if we just ignore the threat.} a6 {The first step - we ask the Bishop the 'eternal' question- 'Where to go?'.} 10. Ba4 Nf6 {Solving the problem of the c7-pawn, now Black is ready to capture the d5-Knight. At the same time, we continue the development.} 11. Ba5 Nxd5 12. exd5 b5 {A typical intermediate move in the Ruy Lopez! Black would be happy to trade the c6-Knight for the a4-Bishop, as it would guarantee us the pair of Bishops in a position with an open character.} 13. Re1+ Ne7 14. Rc1 {White wants to make use of being ahead in the development and sacrifices a piece in order to get the initiative.} bxa4 15. Rxc7 {16.Rcxe7+ is now a very unpleasant threat.} Bd7 {Covering the 7th rank and planning on castling short on the next move. The position is balanced - White still has compensation for the sacrificed piece, but one would need to work very hard in order to prove it - Black's play is much simpler.   After we castle short, we will use the opened b-file and the long dark diagonal to create threats on the Queenside. White's b2 pawn is a clear target. The d5 pawn can also be attacked by the Queen - Qb8-Qb5 would be a good way to do that. #5} *

