1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 {A move of rich history, preferred by many GMs and even World Champions! It has become very fashionable lately, one of its most prominent experts being GM Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, who has played it extensively.   I am very optimistic about the Smyslov Ruy Lopez, which I think is great not only as a surprise weapon but also as one to be used on a regular basis, as it gets us rich positions, where the player who knows better the plans and the ideas will have the upper hand!} 4. d4 {One of the most critical lines where White tries to punish Black immediately for losing time.} exd4 5. Nxd4 {Natural but harmless.} Bg7 {With tempo! The Knight has to either move or to be protected.} 6. Be3 (6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bc4 Nf6 {The best position for the Knight! We are ready to castle now!} 8. e5 {The issue with our previous move can be connected only with e5. If we have a good answer to it, then the Knight always prefers the f6-square to the more passive e7.} Ne4 {With a nice tactical idea.} 9. Qe2 O-O $1 {'Pretending' that the Knight on e4 is not hanging.} 10. Qxe4 d5 $1 {With a fork! #1} 11. Z0 ({White can't take en passant, as it is now White's King who's in trouble in the centre!} 11. exd6 {will be met by} Re8 {winning the Queen.})) 6... Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O {The King is safe!} 8. O-O Ne7 $1 {A typical move, first played by World Champion William Steinitz. The idea is to prepare d5 and to lure White into playing 9.e5, which is actually a mistake.} 9. e5 $2 (9. Qf3 {Connecting the Rooks and trying to fight against d5.} d5 10. Bg5 {Pinning the Knights and attacking both the pawn on d5 and the f6 Knight.} (10. e5 {doesn't work because of} Ng4 {and the e5 pawn is lost.}) 10... Qd6 {The best square for Black's Queen, covering e5 and protecting the Knight on f6 and the d5-pawn.} 11. Rfe1 {Threatening to deliver an unpleasant fork on e5.} dxe4 {Forcing a series of trades.} 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Nf5 $11 {With a nearly symmetrical and equal position. #2}) 9... Nfd5 {With a double attack on the e5 pawn and the Bishop on e3!} 10. Nxd5 Nxd5 11. Bc1 c6 $1 (11... Bxe5 {would be premature, as after} 12. Nf3 {both the Bishop on e5 and the Knight on d5 are hanging.}) 12. Bc4 $2 Nb6 {Harassing White's Bishop. If it retreats on e2, we can safely capture the e5 pawn.} 13. Bb3 c5 {Nice little trick! The Knight is hanging, but when it goes away, we can play 14...c4 and the Bishop on b3 is trapped! #3} *

