1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 {A move of rich history, preferred by many GMs and even World Champions! It has become very fashionable lately, one of its most prominent experts being GM Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, who has played it extensively.   I am very optimistic about the Smyslov Ruy Lopez, which I think is great not only as a surprise weapon but also as one to be used on a regular basis, as it gets us rich positions, where the player who knows better the plans and the ideas will have the upper hand!} 4. d4 {One of the most critical lines where White tries to punish Black immediately for losing time.} exd4 5. Bxc6 $2 {Giving up the pair of Bishops is a bad idea!} dxc6 6. Qxd4 ({White couldn't avoid trading Queens, as after} 6. Nxd4 c5 {the Knight has to go away and 7...Qxd1 will follow.}) 6... Qxd4 7. Nxd4 Bg7 {Now our Bishop on g7 is a 'monster'! It targets the pawn on b2, making it difficult for White to finish their development of the Queenside.} 8. Ne2 f5 $1 {As we have the pair of bishops, we aim for an open position, where the Bishops will have as many diagonals as possible!} 9. Nbc3 fxe4 10. Bf4 (10. Nxe4 {would be met by} Nf6 {first trading the Knights and then developing the light squared Bishop to f5.}) 10... Ne7 11. Bxc7 O-O {The e4-pawn is untouchable, as b2 is hanging. We'll follow with Nf5, Be5, Rad8, with a better position for Black thanks to the very strong pair of Bishops.} *

