1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 {A move of rich history, preferred by many GMs and even World Champions! It has become very fashionable lately, one of its most prominent experts being GM Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, who has played it extensively.   I am very optimistic about the Smyslov Ruy Lopez, which I think is great not only as a surprise weapon but also as one to be used on a regular basis, as it gets us rich positions, where the player who knows better the plans and the ideas will have the upper hand!} 4. d4 {One of the most critical lines where White tries to punish Black immediately for losing time.} exd4 5. Bg5 {Very energic play. White wants to exploit the weakness of the dark squares by forcing Black to trade the dark squared Bishop.} Be7 ({Forced, as} 5... Nge7 $4 {runs into} 6. Bf6) ({while} 5... f6 {weakens too much the Kingside.}) 6. Bf4 {An interesting but not dangerous move. White argues that our Bishops aren't optimally placed on e7 and wants to exploit it.} Nf6 7. e5 (7. O-O O-O {It was possible to capture the e4-pawn, but why take risks when we can first bring the king to safety?} 8. e5 Nh5 9. Bh6 Ng7 10. c3 ({Taking} 10. Nxd4 {would run into} Nxe5 {keeping an extra pawn.}) 10... a6 {A useful inclusion, asking White's Bishop a question.} 11. Ba4 d6 {Time to open up our light squared Bishop!} 12. exd6 Bxd6 {With better chances for Black, as White is forced to either take on d4 with the pawn, after which they'll be left with an isolated pawn structure, or to give up the pair of Bishops by playing 13.Bxc6, which is not a great idea in an open position. #1} 13. Z0 (13. Nxd4 {doesn't work because of} Qh4 {with a double attack on h6 and h2.})) 7... Nd5 8. Bh6 {Not allowing us to castle.} a6 {The 'eternal' question to White's Bishop.} 9. Bc4 Nb6 {One more!} 10. Bb3 d5 {Now we want to play Be6, Qd7 and then castle long, with great prospects for us! #2} 11. Z0 ({Note that White can't get back the pawn, as after} 11. Nxd4 {we can play} Nxe5 {keeping the extra pawn!}) *

