1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 {A move of rich history, preferred by many GMs and even World Champions! It has become very fashionable lately, one of its most prominent experts being GM Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, who has played it extensively.   I am very optimistic about the Smyslov Ruy Lopez, which I think is great not only as a surprise weapon but also as one to be used on a regular basis, as it gets us rich positions, where the player who knows better the plans and the ideas will have the upper hand!} 4. d4 {One of the most critical lines where White tries to punish Black immediately for losing time.} exd4 5. Bg5 {Very energic play. White wants to exploit the weakness of the dark squares by forcing Black to trade the dark squared Bishop.} Be7 ({Forced, as} 5... Nge7 $4 {runs into} 6. Bf6) ({while} 5... f6 {weakens too much the Kingside.}) 6. Bxe7 Qxe7 {White has a choice now, to get back the sacrificed pawn immediately, or to delay it a bit. Let's examine both options!} 7. Bxc6 (7. O-O Nf6 {Continuing the development.} 8. Bxc6 {White wants to get back the sacrifised pawn and get a pawn majority on the Kingside.} (8. Re1 O-O 9. e5 {Energic play - White tries to prove Black has delayed the development for too long!} Nh5 {Covering the f4-square.} 10. c3 ({Now if White takes} 10. Nxd4 {Black can take} Nxe5 {- there's no} 11. f4 {as our Knight covers it. Thus - no reasons to worry about the pin on the e-file and we keep the extra pawn!}) 10... d5 {Returning the extra pawn, but opening up our Bishop!} 11. cxd4 (11. Bxc6 dxc3 $1 {A nice intermediate move! White doesn't have time to retreat from c6, as the after 12...cxb2, the Rook on a1 would be trapped.} 12. Nxc3 bxc6 {White has some compensation for the extra pawn, but it's enough only for equalizing. Black will have good play on the Queenside - Bd7, a5, Rb8, playing on the side where we have more pawns! #1}) 11... Nd8 {No longer allowing White to spoil our pawn structure!} 12. Bf1 c6 {With a balanced, healthy position. The Knight from h5 will go to g7, the other one to e6 and then we'll prepare the c5 break-through (by playing b6, Bb7), in order to create a passed pawn on the d-file. #2}) (8. e5 {White tries to spare tempi by not playing Re1.} Nd5 {Our Knight is now comfortable on d5.} 9. Nbd2 $5 {GM Gajewski's recommendation for White. White finishes the development and aims for the e4-square. For now, the e5-pawn is untouchable, as we'd get in trouble over the e-file.} (9. Re1 {Trying to keep the e5-pawn alive.} Qb4 {With a double attack on the b2-pawn and the b5-Bishop.} 10. a4 {White correctly assesses that we can't capture the b2-pawn for now as our Queen might get in trouble after 11.Ra3.} a6 {Asking the Bishop our favorite question - 'Where to go to'?} 11. Bd3 Nf4 {Continuing the Bishop's hunt!} 12. Ra3 {A nice Rook lift meant to bring one more piece into the game if Black captures on d3 - White will take back with the Rook and then the d4-pawn would be impossible to protect.} (12. Bf1 {would be met by} O-O {followed by Ne6 and d5, with a pawn up. White would have to work very hard to prove any compensation.}) 12... O-O 13. c3 {White wants to open up the position and get as much activity as possible for their pieces in order to prove compensation for the sacrificed pawn.} Qe7 {Once again, we return the extra material (pawn) in order to quickly finish our development.} 14. cxd4 d6 {Our development will be completed on the next move when we bring the Bishop to g4 - that will also increase our pressure on the e5-pawn. Taking on d6 isn't a great option for White as it would leave them with the weak isolated d4-pawn.  If trying to stop 15...Bg4 by playing 15.h3, we can take on e5 and when White captures back with the pawn (either immediately or after first trading Knights) we will play Rd8 - with a very unpleasant pin over the d-file. Altogether, I like Black's prospects more here. #4}) (9. c3 dxc3 {Taking advantage of the fact that White doesn't have time to capture on d5, as 10...cxb2 would follow, winning the Rook on a1.} 10. Nxc3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 {White counts on the fact that Black's dark squares on the Kingside are now weak and castling short would be reckless.} b6 {But Black has another plan- castling long! We want to play 12...Bb7 and then 13...0-0-0. Our King will be very safe on the Queenside and, at the same time, we keep our extra pawn! All reasons to be optimistic! #5}) (9. Bxc6 $2 {Is bad, as it only helps us finish the development.} dxc6 10. Qxd4 {White got the pawn back, but Black no problems at all.} Bf5 {Eyeing the c2-pawn.} 11. Nc3 Nxc3 12. bxc3 (12. Qxc3 {would be met by} O-O-O) 12... O-O {The position is balanced- White has a pawn majority on the Kingside, but the pawn structure on the Queenside is weak. The position is quite open, so our Bishop is doing a fine job. We'll continue with Rad8 and maybe even f6, opening up the position even more. The c2 and c3 pawns will become targets. #6}) 9... O-O {Threratening to take the e5-pawn.} 10. Re1 a6 {Bishop on top of a diagonal alert! We start the hunt on it.} 11. Bxc6 {Gets back the pawn.} (11. Bc4 {Trying to disturb our d5-Knight.} Nf4 12. g3 Ne6 {Our Knight has found a nice square from which it protects our extra d4-pawn.} 13. Ne4 d6 {Undermining the e5-pawn so that White's Knight won't be stable after landing on f6.} 14. exd6 cxd6 {White has compensation for the sacrificed pawn, but it's only good enough for keeping the game balanced. We will finish the development with 15...Bd7 and then look for trades with Ne5. #7}) 11... dxc6 12. Nxd4 {White gets a pawn stucture with a majority on the Kingside and claims to be better.} c5 {Disturbing the nicely placed Knight on d4.} 13. N4f3 b6 {Preparing to develop our Bishop to b7.} 14. Ne4 Bb7 {White's pawn majority is counterbalanced by our strong light squared Bishop on b7. We plan to follow up with 15...Rad8 and then prepare f5. The position is equal. #8}) 8... dxc6 9. Qxd4 {Possible, but not much different than the mainline.} c5 {White's best piece is the centrally placed Queen on 'd4', thus we make it go away to a less optimal position.} 10. Qe3 {Now White's Queen no longer controls the 'd' file, meaning Black can continue the development and prepare castling long.} Bg4 {Now that the Queen doesn't get in the way of our castling long, we can develop the Bishop to g4!} 11. Nc3 (11. Rd1 {runs into} Qxe4) 11... O-O-O {The development is complete! It looks like White has an 'extra pawn', as we have doubled pawns on the c-file, but it is not a big problem for us as we have a clear plan.  The Rook from h8 will come to e8, increasing the pressure against the e4-pawn. The pawn on c5 does a very important job of controlling the d4-square, which would be a great place for our d8 Rook to be in order to attack the e4 pawn one more time, but also to take control over the open d-file. The Knight on f3 is covering d4 for now, but we can solve this problem by trading our Bishop for it anytime we please. If the Knight goes away from f3, the d4 square will be free to take for our Rook! #3}) 7... dxc6 {Awakening our light squared Bishop!} 8. Qxd4 Nf6 {Developing the Knight and attacking e4.} 9. Nc3 {White keeps both castling options opened!} (9. O-O {Possible, but not much different than the mainline.} c5 {Depending on where the Queen retreats, we choose where to develop our Bishop.} 10. Qe3 ({After} 10. Qd3 {we will play} Bd7 {in order to cover the d-file and prepare long castle.}) 10... Bg4 {Now that the Queen doesn't get in the way of our castling long, we can develop the Bishop to g4!} 11. Nc3 (11. Rd1 {runs into} Qxe4) 11... O-O-O {The development is complete! It looks like White has an 'extra pawn', as we have doubled pawns on the c-file, but it is not a big problem for us as we have a clear plan.  The Rook from h8 will come to e8, increasing the pressure against the e4-pawn. The pawn on c5 does a very important job of controlling the d4-square, which would be a great place for our d8 Rook to be in order to attack the e4 pawn one more time, but also to take control over the open d-file. The Knight on f3 is covering d4 for now, but we can solve this problem by trading our Bishop for it anytime we please. If the Knight goes away from f3, the d4 square will be free to take for our Rook!} 12. Nd2 {White wants to make our Bishop on g4 feel useless and also brings the Knight to c4, where it can potentially help White to create threats against our King.} b6 {A useful move - protecting c5 and also getting ready to meet a4 with a5.} 13. a4 {White wants to play a5 and weaken our King.} a5 {Not today!} 14. h3 Bd7 {The Bishop will feel great on c6 from where it will both attack the e4-pawn and protect our King. Rhe8 will follow then, applying some extra pressure on the e4-pawn. It can be increased even more by bringing the other rook to d4! Black has a superior position. #9}) 9... Bg4 {Asking White an important question - do they want to allow us to spoil their pawn structure by taking on f3 or not?} 10. Nd2 {White keep their pawn structure healthy.} (10. O-O-O {White argues that taking on f3 will only open the g-file for them.} Bxf3 11. gxf3 O-O {But there are little light pieces left on the board (just a pair of Knights) and it makes it difficult for White to exploit our somewhat weakened pawn structure on the Kingside.} 12. Qe3 {The Queen would have to move anyway and the e3-square is the best spot for it, keeping an eye on both flanks (eyeing the a7-pawn and sometimes thinking of going to h6).} (12. f4 {A direct try to break through.} a5 {Freeing the Rook from defending the a7-pawn.} 13. f5 Rad8 {White is still many moves away from creating a real threat against our king. At the same time, we are ready to start an attack of our own on the Queenside by playing b5 and then b4. The position is balanced. #10}) 12... Rfe8 {Increasing the pressure on the e4-pawn.} 13. f4 {Black can't capture on e4, as after 14.Rhe1, the Knight would be pinned and after 15.f3 - lost.} a5 {Again, the same idea, taking the pawn away from White's Queen's eyes and preparing to bring the a-Rook to the centre.} 14. e5 Nh5 {The best place for the Knight in this position, as it covers the f6-square and can also be rerouted to f5 via g7.} 15. Ne4 {White's Knight looks nice on e4, but it doesn't create any threats.} Rad8 16. Rde1 {Preparing Ng3 and h4-h5.} (16. Ng3 {will be met by} Ng7 {and we will be ok with repeating the position.}) (16. h4 {will not work, as after} Rxd1+ {White can't capture back with the Rook, as the h4-pawn is hanging.}) 16... f5 {Fixing the structure on the Kingside.} 17. Ng3 ({Taking on f6 isn't dangerous, as after} 17. exf6 Nxf6 {the f2- and f4-pawn will be weak.}) 17... Ng7 {The knight is rerouting towards the centre.} 18. h4 h5 {White can't breakthrough on the Kingside anymore. We will first consolidate by playing Qf7 (eyeing the a2 pawn and over-protecting f5 and h5 in the event of some sacrifices) then continue with Kh7, Ne6 with a perfectly fine position. All the endgames will be better for Black, as the f4-pawn is weak and we'll be able to increase the pressure against it by playing Rd4. #11}) 10... c5 {Where should the Queen retreat to?} 11. Qe3 (11. Qd3 {Not allowing Black to castle long.} Bd7 {Insisting on castling long and bringing the Bishop closer to its best position: c6.} 12. O-O-O O-O-O 13. Qe3 Bc6 {With a few tempi up compared to themainline with 11.Qe3. #12}) 11... O-O-O 12. h3 (12. f3 {Trying to spare tempi and not play h3 at all.} Bd7 {We still stick to the same plan of bringing the Bishop to c6.} 13. O-O-O b6 {A good move, consolidating c5 and not committing our Bishop to the c6 square just yet, as if White will try to bring the Knight from d2 to c4 we can make it feel uncomfortable by playing Be6. We have enough useful moves in order to delay a bit choosing the square our Bishop will land to.} 14. Nc4 (14. h3 Bc6 {Transposingto the mainline. #13}) (14. Rhe1 {White is waiting for us to commit our Bishop to c6 and only then bring the Knight to c4.} Rhe8 {But we don't get convinced to commit so easily! If White continues to stall - we still have a lot of useful moves - Kb7, Nh5 (preparing Ng7 and f5).} 15. Qg5 Nh5 {Why not trade Queens? The problem of White's nice pawn majority on the Kingside will still remain the same- once starting to move - the pawns will become targets for us to attack.} 16. Qxe7 Rxe7 17. Nd5 {Only 'visual' activity which doesn't achieve anything.} Re6 18. g4 Nf6 {We want to trade the active d5-Knight if allowed. Either way, our plan will be connected with attacking White's pawn chain on the Kingside. We can achieve it by playing Bc6, Nd7, Rde8, f5 - all of this if White avoids changing the Knights.} 19. c4 {White wants to take back on d5 with the c-pawn.} Nxd5 20. cxd5 Rf6 {The Rook is very comfortable on the f-file, eyeing the f3-pawn. It can always jump to f4 if attacked by means of 21.e5 or 21.g5. We still want to attack White's pawn chain, this time by playing 21...c6. The position is balanced for now, but White should be very accurate in order not to expand too much and start losing pawns. #14}) 14... Be6 {The Knight can't now keep its good position on c4.} 15. Ne5 {Threatening on a fork from c6.} Kb7 {Our King is happy to help - 16.Nc6 is no longer an issue.} 16. Qg5 {Just a move of false activity. We can get easily rid of the pin over the h4-d8 diagonal.} h6 {The Queen will have to move away, which will leave the e5-Knight quite unstable. We'll follow up with 17...g5, taking control over the dark squares and preparing to bring the Knight to f4 via h5. #15}) 12... Bd7 {Once again, the best position for our Bishop is on c6, from where it both attacks the e4-pawn and covers our King.} 13. O-O-O Bc6 14. f3 {Making sure the e4-pawn is untouchable.} (14. g4 {White takes under control the h5-square, so we won't be able to reroute our Knight via h5-g7-e6-d4.} Rhe8 {Pressuring the e4-pawn.} 15. Rhe1 b6 {Consolidating and preparing Rd4.} 16. Qg3 Rd4 {This square is very important for our Rooks, as it ensured that we'll have control over the d-file, but it also allows us to increase the pressure against the e4-pawn.} 17. f4 Red8 18. e5 Ne8 {The Knight has found an alternative way to reroute to g7!} 19. Ne2 (19. f5 {would be a mistake, as after} Qg5 {the Knight on d2 is very unpleasantly pinned.}) 19... R4d5 {White has no sensible way of improving their position, while Black still does - the Knight can come to g7, the Queen - to d7 - increasing the pressure on d-file even more! It seems that White has over-expanded on the Kingside and will struggle to keep its territory.} 20. Nc3 Rd4 {The best White can achieve is a repetition. #16}) 14... b6 {Our plan is very simple - consolidate, improve, attack! Transposingto the mainline.} 15. Nc4 Nh5 {The Knight was no longer good on f6, as the e4-pawn was untouchable - it was time for it to be rerouted!} 16. g4 (16. Rhe1 {White tries to respect the chess principles and bring the pieces to the centre!} Rhe8 {So do we! Now the useful moves are over for White and they have to decide what to do next.} 17. Qh6 {White gets a bit greedy and wants perhaps to win the h7-pawn.} Rd4 {Making the Knight on c4-uncomfortable.} 18. Ne3 Kb7 {Ignoring the h7-pawn and improving the position of the King.} 19. Qxh7 Rxd1+ 20. Ncxd1 Qf6 {Threatening to win the Queen with 21...Rh8. Black has very good compensation for the pawn. #17}) 16... Ng7 17. f4 (17. h4 {Trying to attack our pawn structure from another side.} f6 {A solid move that covers the dark squares and clears the f7-square for our Queen. #18}) 17... f6 {The same reaction as the earlier variation where White played h4 - consolidating and planning on bringing the Queen to f7!} 18. Rhe1 Ne6 {It is a matter of patience here. In these types of positions, the pawn advances are actually creating only weaknesses and Black's job is to wait/ provoke them.} 19. Nd5 Qf7 {The knight on d5 is unstable. We want to play 20...Nd4 and make it go away. Another useful move to be made is Rhe8, Kb7, waiting for White to over-expand and create irreparable weaknesses. The position is balanced. #19} *

