1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Bxc6 $6 {A suboptimal move, as it gives up the pair of bishops and only helps Black to develop. Compared to the Exchange Variation of the Ruy Lopez, we even won a tempo, as White took on c6 without us playing a6.} dxc6 {Opening up the diagonal for our light squared Bishop.} 5. Nxe5 $2 {Is bad, as we get the pawn back and as a result, the position will have opened even more for our Bishop pair.} Qd4 {A typical reaction, with a double attack.} 6. Nf3 Qxe4+ {Forcing White to trade Queens, as otherwise, White would have to lose the right to castle.} 7. Qe2 Qxe2+ 8. Kxe2 f6 $5 {A very interesting, positional move. We make room for our King on f7 - we know that the King is an important piece in the endgame and, as White has given up the light squared Bishop, our King will be safe there. We will then continue the development with Ne7 and Bd7. We can then start bothering White by playing g5-g4.   The dark squared Bishop can be developed then to d6 (the Knight can move to g6 making room for it), and then the Rooks can come to the central d- and e-files. The pair of Bishops give us a nice advantage.} *

