1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Bxc6 $6 {A suboptimal move, as it gives up the pair of bishops and only helps Black to develop. Compared to the Exchange Variation of the Ruy Lopez, we even won a tempo, as White took on c6 without us playing a6.} dxc6 {Opening up the diagonal for our light squared Bishop.} 5. d4 {White wants to get to an endgame with an extra pawn on the Kingside.} exd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Nxd4 {A structure reminding us somewhat of the Berlin endgames. However, there are a few important differences: our Knight is still on g8 (not on f6) and it gives us the additional idea of playing f5; the dark squared Bishop has a nice opened long diagonal.} Bg7 {Making White's only active piece, the Knight on d4 give up its position.} 8. Ne2 f5 {Opening up the position even more for our Bishop pair!} 9. Nbc3 fxe4 10. Bf4 {White tries to argue that the pawn on e4 is weak and one will be able to get it later, meanwhile attacking the c7 one.} Ne7 {The Knight is placed better on e7 than on f6 because it doesn't get in the way of the dark squared Bishop.} 11. Bxc7 O-O {Black has a superior position thanks to the pair of Bishops. The pawn on e4 is untouchable, as White has problems on the long dark diagonal (the b2-pawn is hanging).} *

