1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Bxc6 $6 {A suboptimal move, as it gives up the pair of bishops and only helps Black to develop. Compared to the Exchange Variation of the Ruy Lopez, we even won a tempo, as White took on c6 without us playing a6.} dxc6 {Opening up the diagonal for our light squared Bishop.} 5. d3 {This setup reminds us of the Rossolimo, but there is an important difference - here, our c-pawns are on c7 and c6 compared to the Rossolimo, where they are on c5 and c6.   It may seem like a minor difference, but it's actually very important because our dream pawn setup on the Queenside is c5, b6, a5, c7 - all on dark squares- where the pawns protect each over and are very solid, in the same time - keeping the c6 square free for one of our light pieces to take - either the Knight (Ng8-e7-c6), or the Bishop.   In the Rossolimo, because the pawns are 'by default' on c6 and c5 - Black's Queenside is easier to be attacked and the light pieces struggle on more passive positions, as they don't have the important c6 square for their maneuvers. That's the reason why here, Black is doing perfectly fine!} Bg7 {Preparing to finish the development on the Kingside.} 6. Nbd2 {White tries to bring the Knight to c4, from where it will pressure the e5-pawn.} (6. Nc3 b6 {An important move; Black is preparing c5, which will stop White from playing d4, fixing the centre.} 7. Be3 c5 {The d4-square is now under Black's control!} 8. a3 {White wants to challenge our control over the d4-square by preparing b4.} Ne7 9. b4 {The c5-pawn is now hanging.} f5 $1 {Ignoring the threat and starting immediately the counterplay on the Kingside!} 10. bxc5 Nc6 {Taking once again control over the d4-square!} 11. Nd5 O-O 12. cxb6 axb6 {We have sacrificed a pawn, but we've got great compensation for it! The a3-pawn is weak and White's light pieces are unstable - we'll challenge the Knight on d5 by playing Be6, while the Bishop on e3 is exposed to f4.} 13. O-O Be6 14. c4 {White tries to consolidate in the centre.} f4 {As the centre is closed, we start the attack on the Kingside!} 15. Bd2 g5 {Planning on playing g4, then Nd4 and c6. All White's pieces will have to retreat, with the black pieces completely dominating! The attack on the kingside will be extremely dangerous and White has no counterplay whatsoever! #1}) 6... Ne7 7. Nc4 f6 {White has succeeded in temporarily closing Black's dark squared Bishop.} 8. Be3 (8. c3 {Preparing d4.} Be6 {Continuing the development and, at the same time, fighting against White's d4 plan, as the Knight on c4 will be hanging.} 9. Qe2 {White insists on playing d4 by protecting the c4-Knight.} Qd7 10. d4 O-O-O {Development completed!} 11. O-O ({The pawn on e5 is untouchable for now, as after} 11. dxe5 Bxc4 {White loses a piece because of the mate on d1.}) 11... exd4 12. Nxd4 (12. cxd4 {would be met by} Bg4 {and White will struggle to hold on to their central hanging pawns.}) 12... f5 {Opening up our dark squared Bishop! #2} 13. Z0 ({The e4-pawn is hanging and White doesn't have time for} 13. exf5 {as after} Bxc4 14. Qxc4 Bxd4 {White will have a weak, isolated pawn on d4.}) (13. Nxe6 {is also not great, as after} Qxe6 {we pin the e4-pawn and White will struggle to protect it!})) 8... b6 {With the same c5 idea, to control the d4-square.} 9. d4 {While it looks tempting, it's actually Black who will benefit most from opening up the long dark diagonal and the centre, as we are the ones to have the pair of Bishops! White's activity is only visually pleasing and it will fade away.} (9. O-O O-O 10. b4 {White tries to stop us from playing c5 from the other side!} Be6 {Development completed! White isn't able to play d4 because of the unstable Knight on c4.} 11. a4 {Starting an attack on the Queenside.} g5 {Our Knight on e7 was struggling, so we find a better position for it - on g6! At the same time, our counterplay should be on the Kingside!} 12. a5 Ng6 {Taking control over the h4-square, so that after we play g4, White wouldn't be able to play Nh4.} 13. axb6 axb6 14. h3 {The only way to try to stop our g4.} Qd7 {Putting some pressure on h3. White will have to take into count a possible piece sacrifice on h3. In the same time, we have connected our Rooks and plan to continue our Kingside attack with h5-g4. #3}) 9... exd4 10. Qxd4 Qxd4 11. Nxd4 Bd7 {Preparing the long castle.} 12. O-O-O O-O-O {Our plan is to play c5, then Nc6 and f5, forcing White's pieces to retreat and opening up the position for our Bishops! Black is better! #4} *

