1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. h4 $5 {An interesting move, trying to attack Black's Kingside pawn construction immediately!} Nf6 {Getting ready to capture on h5 with the Knight in case White advances their h-pawn.} 5. h5 {White sacrifices a pawn to drive our Knight away from the centre and try to play for the initiative.} Nxh5 6. d4 {Energic play.} exd4 {For now, we are pragmatic, taking all the material White kindly offers us.} 7. c3 (7. Bg5 f6 (7... Be7 {would be met by} 8. Bh6 {not allowing us to castle.}) 8. Bc1 Qe7 {Attacking the e4-pawn.} 9. O-O a6 {Asking White's Bishop 'the eternal' question - where to retreat?} 10. Bc4 {Would be the best diagonal for White's light squared Bishop if not...} Ne5 $1 {Continue to hunt the Bishop!} 11. Bb3 d6 {Planning on continuing the development with 12...Be6 and 13...0-0-0. #1} 12. Z0 ({White can't play} 12. Nxd4 {because after} c5 {and 13...c4, the Bishop on b3 will be trapped.})) 7... Bg7 {Time to do something about our development as well!} 8. cxd4 O-O {Our King has successfully made it to safety and we are still a pawn up! We plan on continuing with 9...d5 in order to open up our light squared Bishop. #2} 9. Z0 ({If White tries to stop us by playing} 9. d5 {themselves, we will answer with} Ne5 {as the trades favor the one with more material!}) *

