1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. h4 $5 {An interesting move, trying to attack Black's Kingside pawn construction immediately!} Nf6 {Getting ready to capture on h5 with the Knight in case White advances their h-pawn.} 5. d4 exd4 6. e5 (6. h5 Nxh5 {transposesto 5.h5.}) (6. O-O {White tries to finish the development quickly and try to exploit the fact that our King is still in the centre.} h6 {An important move - taking the g5-square under control!} 7. Nxd4 {Getting back the sacrificed pawn, but giving Black time to finish the development.} (7. c3 dxc3 {A pawn is a pawn!} 8. Nxc3 Bg7 {White has compensation for the sacrificed pawn, but not enough to hope for more than equality. We will castle on the next move and if allowed, continue then with d6 and Bg4. #1} 9. Z0 ({If White plays} 9. e5 {we have} Ng4 {with the same plan.})) 7... Bg7 8. e5 Nh5 {The Knight might look strange here, but it's the optimal square for it because White has weakened the Kingside with h4 and now the pawn is hanging.} 9. g4 $4 {Trying to win a piece.} (9. Nf3 {The h4-pawn needs to be protected.} d6 {Opening up the c8-h3 diagonal for our light-squared Bishop.} 10. exd6 O-O {Bringing the King to safety and tempting White to win a pawn.} 11. Nc3 {White tries to finish the development as well.} (11. dxc7 {isn't good as after} Qxc7 {our pieces are very active. 12...Rd8 followed by 13...Bg4 is a very unpleasant threat. Due to White's Kingside weaknesses (the h4-pawn and the g4-square) Black has very good compensation.}) 11... cxd6 {The d6-pawn is isolated but White doesn't have good ways to attack it. The Knight on h5 covers very well the f4-square, so White's Bishop can't put pressure on our isolated pawn.   At the same time, we want to develop our Bishop to g4, following up with Ne5 ideas: exploiting the pin over the d1-h5 diagonal. The weak h4-pawn is also going to be a target. #2}) 9... Qxh4 {White's King is now in terrible danger! Taking on h5 is not possible because the d4-Knight is hanging for now.} 10. Bxc6 dxc6 {Now White's Knight is safe on d4, but our light squared Bishop is ready to join Black's Queen, making our attack on White's King unstoppable!} 11. gxh5 Bh3 {With just too many threats! The pawn on e5 is hanging, so does the Rook on f1. We want to castle long and pin White's Knight over the d-file... Black is winning. #3}) 6... Ng4 {A great square for our Knight, since White cannot disturb it with h3!} 7. O-O (7. Bg5 Be7 {with a transposition to 4.d4 exd4 5.Bg5 Be7 6.h4}) (7. c3 d6 8. cxd4 (8. exd6 {will be met by} Bxd6) 8... dxe5 {Once again, taking the kindly offered pawn, but on our own terms!} 9. O-O Be7 (9... Bg7 {is also possible, but it feels like from e7 it does more things - attacking the h4-pawn and covering the g5-square.}) 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Qa4 {White gives up the pair of Bishops trying to get back the sacrificed pawn.} exd4 12. Nxd4 (12. Qxc6+ {will be met by} Bd7) 12... Qd6 {Threatening mate on h2. #4} 13. Z0 ({White's best option is to play} 13. Qxc6+ {where after} Qxc6 14. Nxc6 Bxh4 {Black has a superior position thanks to the extra pawn and the pair of Bishops.})) (7. h5 {Now that our Knight is away, White ceases the moment to attack our Kingside pawn structure.} Qe7 {White's King is also still in the centre, and now it's cover - the e5-pawn is attacked.} 8. O-O Qc5 {Disturbing the b5-Bishop and in the same time - protecting d4, while keepig an eye on the e5-pawn.} 9. Bd3 Bg7 {The most natural way to continue the development.} 10. Nbd2 {White has found a good square for the Knight to land on e4 and goes for it.} O-O 11. Ne4 Qb6 {Keeping the Queen to protect the d4-pawn and, in the same time disturb White's development my attacking the b2-pawn and keeping the c1-Bishop at its defence.} 12. Nf6+ {Sacrificing some more material in search for the intiative!} Nxf6 13. exf6 Bxf6 14. Bh6 Qc5 {Bringing the Queen closer to the Kingside. We already have 2 extra pawns, that's why we can afford to sacrifice the exchange in order to solve our King's safety issues.} (14... Bg7 {runs into} 15. Qc1 {and Black's King might get in trouble.}) ({While} 14... Re8 {will be met by} 15. Re1 {where the safety of our King might be again an issue.}) 15. Bxf8 Kxf8 16. hxg6 hxg6 {Our dark squared Bishop does a fine job protecting the King. Now we plan to finish our development by playing d6, Bd7, after which we can start an attack over the h-file by playing Qh5, Kg7, Rh8. The dark squared Bishop and the 2 pawns we have for the Rook are more than enough! #5}) 7... h6 {Once again, protecting the vital g5-square!} 8. Nxd4 {Getting back the central pawn and attacking the Knight on g4.} (8. Bf4 {Protecting the e5-pawn and continuing the development.} Bg7 {Ready to castle!} 9. c3 dxc3 10. Nxc3 O-O {Thanks to the sacrificed pawn, White is ahead in development and has some extra space, but the e5 pawn is hanging, so one has to spend some time on protecting it.} 11. Re1 d6 $1 {It is now time to return the material and create some threats of our own against White's King!} 12. exd6 cxd6 13. Bxd6 Qb6 {Making use of the newly opened diagonal for our Queen! We sacrifice the exchange, but get in return a nice attack over White's King!} 14. Bxf8 Qxf2+ 15. Kh1 Bxf8 {The b2-pawn is hanging and White's King is very exposed. White has now to be precise in order to avoid a collapse.} 16. Re8 {The best defense is the attack! White pins our Bishop to the King, creating the unpleasant threat of 17.Qd6.} Qxb2 {Threatening a nasty fork on f2 and attacking the c3-Knight.} 17. Qd6 {White gives up the Rook, hoping to be the first one to deliver a mate!} Qxa1+ 18. Ng1 Nf2+ 19. Kh2 Ng4+ $11 {White has to play 20.Kh1 and settle for a draw. #6} (19... Ng4+ 20. Kg3 {is bad because of} Qe1+ $1 {where after} 21. Rxe1 Bxd6+ {Black is winning.})) (8. Qe2 {A smart move - both protecting e5 and threatening to play 9.Qe4, where our g4-Knight will be in trouble.} Qe7 {Prophylaxis! Now 9.Qe4 can be met with 9...f5 , taking advantage of the pin over the e-file.} 9. Re1 {Protecting the Queen and reinforcing the threat of Qe4.} ({Now} 9. Qe4 {can be met with} f5 {taking advantage of the pin over the e-file.}) 9... Bg7 {There's not much to be done about saving our Knight, but we can instead sacrifice it and get some nice, healthy pawns for it!} (9... h5 {weakens too much the dark squares and White can use it immediately:} 10. Bg5 Qc5 11. Bf6 {and White is winning.}) 10. Qe4 Ncxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. f4 c6 ({Our Knight is pinned, so we can't save it -} 12... Nc6 {runs into} 13. Bxc6 {- winning a piece.}) 13. Bd3 d6 {Getting ready to recapture on e5 with the pawn.} 14. fxe5 dxe5 {We have 3 pawns for the sacrificed Knight and they are just enough to secure we have nice compensation! We plan on starting to advance them by playing f5, then castle short and continue with the pawn advance! #7}) 8... Qxh4 {A 'little' threat - mate on h2!} 9. Bf4 {Covering the h2-square and preparing to make our Queen go away by playing 10.Bg3.} Bg7 {Once again, the most natural way to continue the development.} 10. Bg3 Qg5 {Playing against the e5-pawn. We might not be able to take it for now, but after castling - nothing will stop us from doing so!} 11. Nf3 Qd8 12. Nc3 {White has finished the development and has some compensation for the sacrificed pawn thank to the extra space.} O-O {The King is safe! The next step is to get our light squared Bishop into the game! We can start by playing 13...a6 - who knows, maybe White will make our task easier by taking on c6...  If they retreat instead, we can sacrifice the pawn back by playing14...d6, but open our light squared Bishop - which will grant us a balanced position. #8} *

