1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. d3 {A quieter, positional approach, aiming for a long-term strategical battle. I find it harmless for Black and I believe we can even get ambitious in this line!} Bg7 5. O-O {Trying to quickly finish the development.} Nge7 {The best place for the Knight! From here, it supports not only the d5 breakthrough but also the f5 one!} 6. Nc3 {Another developing move, keeping an eye on the d5-square.} O-O {Now that Black's development is almost complete, we will be looking to open up the position with either f5 or d5.} 7. Bg5 {Pinning our Knight, thus stopping us from playing d5.} (7. h3 {A prophylactical move, getting ready for Black playing d5 and opening up the Bishop from c8. Bg4 will then not be a threat.} a6 {Asking the Bishop the 'eternal' question!} 8. Bxc6 (8. Bc4 {and 8.Ba4 won't save White's light squared Bishop from being traded, as our reaction in both cases will be} b5 {where after} 9. Bb3 {we'll play} Na5 {and then trade our Knight for the Bishop.}) 8... bxc6 (8... dxc6 {is possible as well, but generally speaking, it is better to bring a pawn closer to the center! The Bishop from c8 will be opened soon anyway. After the d-pawn will move forward, Black wanted to play d5 on the next move!}) 9. d4 {Trying to be the first one to open the center and potentially put some pressure on Black's doubled pawns after recapturing on d4 with the Knight.} exd4 10. Nxd4 {White wants the Black Knight from e7 to be stuck to protecting the c6-pawn if Black will advance with the d-pawn.} d6 (10... d5 {would be premature because of} 11. Bg5 {pinning the e7 Knight, therefore threatening to take the pawn on c6.}) 11. Bg5 {An unpleasant pin, now the c6-pawn is hanging.} f6 {An 'ugly', but highly efficient move! Black solves the problem of the pin on the h4-d8 diagonal and the Bishop on g7 is closed only temporarily - f5 will be coming shortly to solve this problem!} 12. Be3 c5 {And suddenly all of White's active pieces have to retreat!} 13. Nde2 Rb8 {Making use of the semi-opened b-file! The b2-pawn is now hanging!} 14. Rb1 f5 {Opening up the long dark diagonal for the Bishop, which is now eyeing the b2-pawn! 15...fxe4 is a serious threat, as White won't be able to capture back with the Knight, precisely because of the hanging b2-pawn. Taking on f5 is also not a great option, as after 15...Nxf5, White's Bishop on e3 will have no good squares to retreat to. #1}) 7... h6 {Solving the 'pinning' matter!} 8. Bh4 g5 {Forcing White's Bishop on a rather sad position - on g3, where it might get in trouble after an eventual pawn advancement by means of h5-h4 or f5-f4.} 9. Bg3 d6 {Overprotecting e5 and opening up the light squared Bishop.} 10. Bc4 {White tries their best to prevent f5.} Na5 {The problem is that White can't keep the Bishop on the a2-g8 diagonal without allowing us to trade it, meaning that f5 will be coming anyway!} 11. Nd2 c6 {An important chess principle is 'Don't hurry!' and that's exactly what Black is doing. The Bishop on c4 is not going anyway, so we can improve our position. White will now have to deal with the d5 threat as well!} 12. a4 {Making room for the Bishop to retreat to a2.} Nxc4 {In the best moment, just when White was ready to run away from c4.} 13. Nxc4 Ng6 {Again, the 'Don't hurry!' principle. It is very important to have your pieces placed on the best possible squares before going for a breakthrough. The Knight does an important job protecting the e5-pawn! Black's threats are now both 14...d5 and 14...f5 with a better position! #2} *

