1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. d3 {A quieter, positional approach, aiming for a long-term strategical battle. I find it harmless for Black and I believe we can even get ambitious in this line!} Bg7 5. Nc3 {The position resulting from this move order may easily transpose to the 5.0-0 line, so you might ask yourself why to examine it separately...  The answer is simple - it is a little positional trap which White has set up using this move order. The most natural reply 5...Nge7 would now be an inaccuracy as White has not yet castled and will be able to play h4-h5. Our Knight has also committed already to the e7-square and cannot go to f6 in order to prevent h5.} h6 $1 {A useful waiting move, which was part of our plan anyway! We prevent a potential Bg5 and keep our Knight on g8 until White decides to castle.} 6. O-O ({Now after} 6. h4 {Black can play} a6 {first, asking the 'eternal question' and if White takes on c6, then 7...dxc6 - opening up the light squared Bishop which will have a very nice square on g4, while if} 7. Bc4 {- Black can continue with} Nf6 {stopping h5.}) 6... Nge7 {Now the Knight can safely develop to e7.} 7. Be3 {The g5 square is no longer available for the Bishop, so White chooses another plan - one connected with d4.} Nd4 {One of the most efficient strategies in chess is to guess your opponent's plan and then stop it. That's exactly what we do here, not allowing White to play d4.} 8. Bxd4 (8. Bc4 O-O {The problem for White here is that it's not easy to find an alternative plan to the d4 one, while Black has a very easy play and various good plans to choose from - 'Kh7, d6, f5' or 'c6, d5'.} 9. Nd5 {Preparing c3 thus trying to get rid of the d4-Knight and then prepare to play d4.} Nxd5 10. Bxd5 c6 {Black is first opening up the centre by means of 11...d5 if White just retreats with the Bishop.} 11. Bxd4 {An intermediate move, but one which does not cause us any trouble!} exd4 12. Bb3 d5 {Finally opening up our light squared Bishop.} 13. exd5 {White hopes to be able to make use of Black's soon-to-be doubled pawns on the d-file.} cxd5 {We have our pawn structure a bit spoiled, but White doesn't really have the means to exploit it. On the other hand, Black has the pair of Bishops and an extra semi-opened c-file to play for!} 14. Re1 a5 {Threatening to play 15...a4 and trap the Bishop. The long term plan is to develop the Bishop to e6, the Queen will go to d6 - taking control of the important f4- and b4-squares, so that White's Queen can't get there to attack our d4-pawn and then we'll be ready to attack any of the flanks, either by advancing our pawns on the Kingside - f5, g5, Bf6, g4, or by playing Rfc8, Rab8, b5. #1}) 8... exd4 9. Ne2 {Attacking our d4-pawn.} c5 {The only way to protect d4.} 10. c3 {White wants to make Black take on c3 and then capture back bxc3, bringing a pawn closer to the center, arguing that the resulting central pawn majority is a serious achievement.} a6 {Once again, asking White's b5-Bishop the 'eternal' question.} 11. Ba4 b5 {Hunting White's Bishop!} 12. Bb3 dxc3 {We agree to let White have the pawn majority in the centre but in return, we have the Bishop pair and some nice diagonals!} 13. bxc3 O-O 14. d4 {White occupies the centre with their pawn majority. However, let's remember another important chess principle - who does a position with an open character favor? Exactly - the player who has the Bishop pair!} d6 {Protecting c5 and preparing to finish the development by bringing the Bishop to b7. The plan then is to apply pressure on White's central pawns by playing Re8, Nc6, maybe even double on the e-file and try to provoke one of the pawns to move, which will cause irreparable weaknesses in White's position. #2} *

