1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. d3 {A quieter, positional approach, aiming for a long-term strategical battle. I find it harmless for Black and I believe we can even get ambitious in this line!} Bg7 5. c3 {Another tricky move order. One might think that it is again a waiting move, trying to lure our Knight to e7 before White has castled in order to then attack with h4-h5. However, it is not the case here. Let's see why.} Nge7 6. O-O (6. h4 {This is the move we should always have an answer to before committing our g6 Knight to e7, from where it can't control the h5-square, unlike from f6. In this particular position, when White's pawn is already on c3, it is not so dangerous, as White's Knight can't come to c3, and use the soon to be weak Black's light squares.} h6 {Preparing to meet 7.h5 with 7...g5.} 7. h5 g5 {Imagine White's Knight on c3 here instead of the pawn - White would then play Bc4 - enhancing the control over the light squares and making it very difficult for Black to make the d5 or f5 breakthrough work.   The situation is completely different now that there's a pawn on c3, which doesn't stay in the way of us playing d5 (after castling first) in any way! #1}) 6... O-O {I like this position for Black a lot, as it is though Black has spared a lot of tempi compared to any of the long Ruy Lopez lines where Black's Knight is on f6 and the Bishop is on e7. Then, Black spends a lot of moves to bring that Bishop to g7 and they go away with the Knight to prepare f5!} 7. Re1 {The 'a la Ruy Lopez' slow approach - White prepares to reroute the Knight from b1 to d2, then f1, while eyeing the e5-pawn at the same time, so that Black can't comfortably play d5.} (7. Bg5 $6 {We already know how to react to this kind of pins here!} h6 8. Bh4 {Solves the problem of f5 only temporarily.} ({If} 8. Be3 {now, Black will play} f5 {immediately, launching an attack on the Kingside!}) 8... d6 {The 'Don't hurry!' principle, first making sure that all of our pieces participate in the game and only then breaking through!} 9. Nbd2 g5 {Getting rid of the pin!} 10. Bg3 f5 {And here is our breakthrough! 11...f4 is a serious threat - trapping the g3-Bishop and overall Black's position is perfect, all the pieces work harmoniously together.  We may want to increase the tension in the centre even more by playing d5 as well, the Bishop will develop to either e6 or f5 (if White takes on f5) then we will bring the Queen to d7, the Rook from a8 to e8... White will have a difficult time! #2}) (7. d4 $6 {This is basically a loss of tempo, as White used to move with the d-pawn in order to reach the d4-square...} exd4 8. cxd4 d5 {Opening up the diagonal for the light squared Bishop and aiming for a pawn structure where White will have to play with an isolated pawn.} 9. exd5 Nxd5 {The d4 isolated pawn is now the major issue in White's position and Black plans to increase the pressure against it!} 10. Bxc6 {Eliminating one of the pieces which attacks the d4-pawn and spoiling Black's pawn structure.} bxc6 {Black does have a pair of doubled pawns on the c-file, but White also has an isolated d-pawn. Also, Black has now the Bishop pair, which means that Black has the advantage thanks to the open character of the position!} 11. Bg5 Qd6 {Once again, the best square for the Queen - protecting the c-pawns and the e5-square!} 12. Nc3 {White tries to finish the development.} h6 {Asking the Bishop a question! At the same time, Black's plan is very simple - combine finishing the development (the light squared Bishop will come to e6) with the play in the centre and attacking the isolated d4-pawn - one Rook will come to e8, while the other can come to d8! Black's position is preferable! #3}) 7... d6 {No problem! We open up our c8-Bishop, consolidate the e5-pawn and prepare another breakthrough in the centre - f5!} 8. h3 {Prophylaxis against Black's Bg4 idea.} f5 {It is now clear that the position is much easier to play for Black as we're ahead in development (White has 2 light pieces on their initial positions, while we only have one) and we are the first to attack the enemy's King!} 9. Nbd2 {Trying to do something about those development issues.} Kh8 {A good prophylactical move, so that the King will never have to worry about all kinds of diagonal checks.} 10. d4 {Another way of making sure that White's b5-Bishop has a way to retreat. At the same time, White follows one of the most famous chess principles - 'When your opponent attacks on one of the flanks, counter-attack in the centre!'.} (10. a4 {A typical, multi-purpose move - White secures a way for the light squared Bishop to retreat (c4-a2) and tries to gain space on the Queenside.} Be6 {Finishing the development!} 11. b4 a6 {Asking the Bishop a question!} 12. Bc4 Bxc4 13. Nxc4 Qd7 {Once again, the position is very simple to be played for Black - the Rook from a8 will come to e8, the Knight from c6 might go to d8-e6 (in the case White attacks it with b5) and then we'll continue our attack on the Kingside by playing h6, g5, g4! #4}) 10... a6 {Checking where this Bishop wants to retreat.} 11. Bd3 {Consolidating the 'e4' pawn.} fxe4 {The most forcing move - White will have to recapture with a piece.} 12. Bxe4 d5 {Another forcing move - not giving White the chance to 'breath'!} 13. Bc2 e4 {And yet another forcing move - all of White's pieces have to retreat!} 14. Nh2 Nf5 {Black has a significant advantage thanks to the initiative against White's King. We control the semi-opened f-file and almost all of our pieces look towards White's King! The Queen can come to h4 or g5, and the Knight from f5 can go to d6 in order to open up the diagonal for the light squared Bishop, threatening to open-up White's King after sacrifices like Bxh3! #5} *

