1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Nc3 {Aiming for closed-centre structures and a more positional approach.} Bg7 {We just continue our development in the usual way.} 5. d4 $2 {A temporary pawn sacrifice, which doesn't work for White.} Nxd4 6. Nxd4 exd4 7. Ne2 {White plans to get the pawn back on the next move.} c6 {With tempi! The Bishop has to move away!} 8. Bc4 (8. Bd3 {Unfortunately, closes up the d-file for White's Queen. Now Black’s d4-pawn will stay alive.} Ne7 {Continuing the development.} 9. O-O O-O {With a healthy pawn up and a better position - d5 is coming - opening up the last undeveloped light piece - the Bishop from c8. #1}) 8... Nf6 {Attacking the e4-pawn.} 9. Qxd4 {White gets back the sacrificed pawn, but places the Queen under Black's fianchettoed g7-Bishop x-ray.} O-O {Now that Black's King is safe and the g7-Bishop is protected by the King, the f6-Knight wants to jump and create unpleasant threats against White's Queen!} 10. Bg5 (10. e5 Nh5 {The e5-pawn is weak and Black wants to attack it by playing Re8.} 11. g4 {It might seem that Black's Knight is trapped, but is it?} d5 {A nice counter-blow, taking advantage of the fact that White can't capture en-passant because of the pin over the long dark diagonal.} 12. Bd3 c5 {Distracting the Queen from protecting the g4-pawn.} 13. Qxc5 (13. Qa4 {would run into} Bd7 {and the g4-pawn will still fall.}) 13... Bxg4 {With a decisive advantage thanks to being much ahead in development, White's ruined pawn structure and weak King. #2}) 10... Nxe4 {A nice little tactical trick! #3} 11. Z0 ({White loses a pawn as after} 11. Qxe4 {there is} Qxg5) ({and if} 11. Bxd8 {then} Bxd4 12. Be7 Re8 {and White doesn't have time to capture our d4-Bishop and save their own dark squared Bishop at the same time.}) *

