1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Nc3 {Aiming for closed-centre structures and a more positional approach.} Bg7 {We just continue our development in the usual way.} 5. Nd5 {Occupying the beautiful central d5-square. However, White's Knight may be disturbed there.} a6 {Asking the Bishop the 'ethernal' question - where will it go?} 6. Ba4 (6. Be2 {Avoids b5 with tempo, but is quite passive.} Nge7 {The d5-Knight can't remain unchallenged! In the same time, Black continues the development and plans on castling short.} 7. c4 {Insisting on keeping the Knight on d5.} d6 {Opening up the diagonal for the light-squared Bishop.} 8. d3 {Threatening to make an unpleasant pin: 9.Bg5.} h6 {Prophylaxis - covering the g5-square.} 9. O-O O-O {White has a beautiful Knight placed in the centre, but that's about it. Black has a clear plan- starting an attack on the Kingside by playing f5, either immediately or after g5, Ng6. #1}) 6... b5 {Hunting down White's Bishop!} 7. Bb3 Na5 {White has no way to avoid losing the pair of Bishops now.} 8. O-O c6 {Additionaly, Black has cleared the c6-square for the pawn. Now the beautiful Knight from d5 has to leave its active position.} 9. Nc3 Ne7 {Continuing the development. There is no reason to hurry taking on b3, as the Bishop is not going anywhere, we can first finish our development.} 10. Re1 O-O {Black's plan is to prepare an attack on the Kingside by playing d6, h6, Nxb3, f5. Black's position is superior. #2} *

