1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Nc3 {Aiming for closed-centre structures and a more positional approach.} Bg7 {We just continue our development in the usual way.} 5. h4 {An aggressive but typical move against the opponent's fianchettoed Bishop pawn structure. White plans on playing h5, at the same time taking control of the g5-square.} ({1.} 5. O-O Nge7 6. d3 O-O {transposes to 4.d3 Bg7 5.0-0 Nge7 6.Nc3 0-0}) ({2.} 5. d3 h6 {transposes to 4.d3 Bg7 5.Nc3 h6.}) 5... a6 {The 'eternal' question once again.} 6. Bc4 {Eyeing the f7-pawn, 7.Ng5 is now a threat.} (6. Bxc6 {Doesn't work well for White, as it is opening Black's light squared Bishop, which will later comfortably jump to the weakened g4-square.} dxc6 7. h5 {This attack achieves nothing.} Bg4 8. hxg6 fxg6 {Black can now prepare castling long and then use the semi-opened f-file and the pin on the h5-d1 diagonal to their benefit.} 9. d3 Qe7 {Ready to castle!} 10. Qe2 Nf6 {But not before finishing the development of all our light pieces!} 11. Bg5 h6 {Not allowing White even a mere activity.} 12. Be3 O-O-O {Black's development is complete! The plan is simple - use the semi-opened f-file and the pin on the h5-d1 diagonal. White is helpless against Black's plan - Nh5, Rhf8, take on f3 (spoiling White's pawn structure), Nf4. #1}) 6... h6 {Double-prophylactical move, against both Ng5 and 7.h5 - which we can meet with 7...g5 now.} 7. d3 d6 {Highlighting the disadvantage of having moved the h-pawn 2 squares. The g4-square will now be weak forever!} 8. a4 {Stopping a potential b5.} (8. Be3 Nge7 {Simply continuing the development.} 9. h5 g5 {The typical reaction agains White's h5.} 10. Nd5 f5 {We can afford such a move thanks to the closed centre and the impossibility of White to open it right away. f4 and b5 are unpleasant threats.} 11. a4 Nxd5 {Trading White's only active piece.} 12. Bxd5 Ne7 {The Bishop has to retreat, if allowed to take on d5 - we will do so happily, gaining a decisive advantage in the centre.} 13. Bb3 f4 {White loses more and more space, which will make their pieces to struggle finding good places.} 14. Bd2 Bg4 {With quite a peculiar plan on how to bring the King to safety! Black's King will go 'by foot' to g7 via f8, the g7-Bishop can make room for it by moving to f6 first. Black's Queen will be most comfortable on d7. A pawn break in the centre should be prepared then (c6, d5). #2}) 8... Nf6 {Once again highlighting the weakness of the g4-square.} 9. Be3 Bg4 {The same unpleasant pin.} 10. Qd2 {Not allowing Black to castle short as the h6-pawn is hanging.} Qd7 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. Bxd5 f5 {Planning to trap White's e3-Bishop by playing 13.f4. White's pieces have too little space and are too clumsy. #3} *

