1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O {Together with 4.c3, this move is one of the most played ones after 3...g6. The ideas are similar to the ones in the 4.c3 line. The difference is that White first brings their King to safety and only then starts to fight for the centre. On the other hand, it allows us some extra time to finish our development as well.} Bg7 5. Re1 {A slow move that allows us just enough time to come up with a breakthrough in the centre.} Nge7 6. c3 {Preparing d4.} O-O {Our King has reached safety and we are now ready for the action in the centre.} 7. d4 exd4 8. cxd4 d5 {Attacking the centre immediately, as White did not take time to control the d5-square.} 9. exd5 ({There's no time for} 9. e5 {as after} Bg4 {White's d4 pawn will be in trouble.}) 9... Nxd5 {We are happy to get to a structure where White has an isolated pawn. The threat is to develop our Bishop to g4, disturbing the main defender of the d4 pawn.} 10. Nc3 (10. h3 {will be met by} Nce7 {followed up by g6 and Be6, preparing then to double on the d-file and pressure the isolated d4 pawn.}) (10. Bxc6 {is not dangerous, as it not only gives us the Bishop pair, but also opens the b-file for our Rook which will then target the b2-pawn.}) 10... Bg4 {With better chances for Black thanks to White's isolated d4-pawn.} *

