1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O {Together with 4.c3, this move is one of the most played ones after 3...g6. The ideas are similar to the ones in the 4.c3 line. The difference is that White first brings their King to safety and only then starts to fight for the centre. On the other hand, it allows us some extra time to finish our development as well.} Bg7 5. c3 {The idea is clear - prepare 6.d4.} a6 {Asking the b5 Bishop where does it want to retreat to.} 6. Bxc6 {An interesting try - giving up the pair of Bishops in order to obtain a pawn majority on the Kingside and good control in the centre.} dxc6 {Opening up the diagonal for our c8 Bishop.} 7. d4 ({There's no time for White to play} 7. h3 {preventing 7...Bg4, as then after either 7...Qd3 or} c5 {White won't be able to play d4 anymore.}) 7... exd4 8. cxd4 {White's central pawns look very nice, but they're quite unstable and we have an easy way to attack them.} Bg4 {Pinning the f3 Knight, thus attacking the d4-pawn.} 9. Nc3 Qf6 {An important move, getting ready to castle long, but at the same time - keeping the pressure over f3 and d4.} ({White correctly argues that the d4-pawn is untouchable for now as after} 9... Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Bxd4 11. Bf4 {Black will be behind with the development and very likely to run into big trouble over the d-file.}) 10. Qb3 {Getting rid of the pin and going for b7 pawn.} Bxf3 11. Qxb7 {An intermediate move forcing our Rook to move away.} Rd8 12. gxf3 Qxf3 {White's King is now quite weak and despite us being behind with the development, it grants us just enough counterplay.} 13. Qxc7 (13. Qxc6+ {will be met by} Rd7 {where White's Queen will be no longer in time to get to the Kingside in order to avoid a perpetual.}) 13... Bxd4 14. Qxc6+ Kf8 {Our King will find safety on g7.} 15. Qc7 {A move with 2 ideas - one is of course to take our Rook on d8 and the other one is to be able to cover against a check by playing Qg3.} Kg7 $1 {Offering White our Rook in order to distract the Queen from being able to cover against a perpetual check.} 16. Qxd8 (16. Qg3 {will be met by} Qxg3+ 17. hxg3 Nf6 {attacking the e4-pawn which White can't really protect in the long run, as the pawn on f2 is pinned. For example} 18. Re1 Rhe8 {and the threat is to take on c3 and then on e4 - White will not be able to stop it.}) 16... Qg4+ $11 {With a perpetual check: 17.Kh1 Qf3+.} *

