1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O {Together with 4.c3, this move is one of the most played ones after 3...g6. The ideas are similar to the ones in the 4.c3 line. The difference is that White first brings their King to safety and only then starts to fight for the centre. On the other hand, it allows us some extra time to finish our development as well.} Bg7 5. c3 {The idea is clear - prepare 6.d4.} a6 {Asking the b5 Bishop where does it want to retreat to.} 6. Bc4 {The Bishop goes immediately to the 'a2-g8' diagonal, keeping an eye on the f7 pawn.} f5 $5 {We have seen this idea in a slightly different position in the lines with 4.c3. The only difference is that compared to that position, there is an extra move for each side - short castle for White and Bg7 for Black. However the ideas are still the same - we take advantage of the fact that White's Bishop is exposed on c4 and once White take exf5 we can play d5. Let's take the best tries White has one by one and look into them!} 7. d4 {Another try to open up the central files against our King.} (7. exf5 {Gives up the control over the d5 square.} d5 {White's Bishop has to move away.} 8. Bb3 Bxf5 {Getting the pawn back and continuing the development.} 9. d4 {Trying to open up the centre.} e4 {As our King is still in the centre, we prefer to keep the e-file closed. We will then continue our development by 10...Ne7 followed by short castle. #1}) (7. Bxg8 {Giving up the pair of Bishops, but taking away Black's option to castle short.} Rxg8 8. exf5 (8. d4 {would be met by} d6) ({while} 8. Qb3 {by} Rf8) 8... gxf5 {There is no way for White to disturb our nice pawns in the centre and get to our King.} 9. d4 {An attempt to open up the e-file.} d6 10. Qb3 {Attacking our Rook thus making it move away from the semi-opened g-file.} (10. dxe5 {will be met by} Bxe5 {opening up the g-file for our Rook and after} 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 {Black will be better as the King is safe in the centre, while White's King will start running into trouble.}) 10... Rf8 11. Bg5 {White tries their best to develop fast.} Qd7 {This move might look odd, but it is actually perfectly fine, as the Queen wants to go to either e6 or f7 in order to trade Queens.} 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Re1 {White pressures the e5 pawn, but it's actually protected just enough times.} Qe6 {Offering a Queen trade. If White avoids it, we can bring our King to safety by playing Kf7-g8. The Bishop will then develop to d7 and we'll be very happy with a strong centre and the pair of Bishops. #2} 14. Z0 ({Trading Queens doesn't really help White as well, as after} 14. Qxe6+ Bxe6 {Black will castle long and then the nice central pawns will start moving - e4 will be a very unpleasant threat.})) (7. d3 {Simply protecting the e4 pawn is not good enough.} f4 {Closing up the path for White's c1 Bishop.} 8. d4 d6 {We want to be able to capture back on e5 with the d6-pawn, so that the f4-pawn stays protected. The plan is to finish the development by bringing our g8-Knight to f7 via h6, which will close up the diagonal for the c4-Bishop and allow us to castle short. We can throw in a Qe7(f6) move before playing Nf7 in order to be able to capture on f7 with the Queen. After castling, our plan will be to start an attack on the Kingside by means of a pawn storm - g5-g4. #3}) 7... fxe4 {Free central pawn alert!} 8. Nxe5 d5 {Closing the diagonal for White's light squared Bishop as fast as we can to save our King from trouble.} 9. Nxc6 {White tries an intermediate move in order to spoil Black's pawn structure.} bxc6 10. Be2 Ne7 {We now continue the development, preparing to castle short. Our Knight is better on e7 than on f6 because it both protects the c6 pawn (just in case) but also can head to the active f5 square.} 11. f3 {Trying to break our nice pawn chain and open-up the e file.} exf3 12. Rxf3 {Not allowing us to castle.} Nf5 {The issue can be easily solved - our Knight now covers the f-file, enabling our King to castle short on the next move.} 13. Nd2 (13. g4 {weakens White's King too much. After} Nd6 {our Knight is heading to another nice outpost - e4.}) 13... O-O 14. Nb3 {White found a nice square for their Knight as well: c5.} a5 {Gaining space on the Queenside and preparing to disturb the b2 Knight by playing a4. Ba6 is another additional idea we get.} 15. a4 Nd6 {While it is true that our c5 square is weak, but so are White's light squares e4 and c4. We plan to use them by bringing the Knight to e4, perhaps developing first our Bishop to f5. The position is balanced - do not trust Stockfish, Leela knows better! #4} *

