1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O {Together with 4.c3, this move is one of the most played ones after 3...g6. The ideas are similar to the ones in the 4.c3 line. The difference is that White first brings their King to safety and only then starts to fight for the centre. On the other hand, it allows us some extra time to finish our development as well.} Bg7 5. c3 {The idea is clear - prepare 6.d4.} a6 {Asking the b5 Bishop where does it want to retreat to.} 6. Ba4 {The main move.} Nge7 {Is also possible. However, White can avoid a transposition to the 4.c3 line if after 7.d4 exd4 8.cxd4 b5 they play 9.Bc2, as in those lines we aimed for setups without the Knight from g8 on f6 and now it's already on e7. That's the reason we go for a different setup after this move order.} 7. Z0 ({However, White can avoid a transposition to the 4.c3 line if after} 7. d4 exd4 8. cxd4 b5 {they play} 9. Bc2 {as in those lines we aimed for setups without the Knight from g8 on f6 and now it's already on e7. That's the reason we go for a different setup after this move order.}) *

