1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O {Together with 4.c3, this move is one of the most played ones after 3...g6. The ideas are similar to the ones in the 4.c3 line. The difference is that White first brings their King to safety and only then starts to fight for the centre. On the other hand, it allows us some extra time to finish our development as well.} Bg7 5. c3 {The idea is clear - prepare 6.d4.} a6 {Asking the b5 Bishop where does it want to retreat to.} 6. Ba4 {The main move.} d6 {Consolidating our e5 pawn and opening up the diagonal for the light squared Bishop.} 7. h3 {Not allowing Black's Bishop to g4.} Nf6 {Developing with a tempo!} 8. Re1 O-O {The King is safe now and Black is ahead in development already.} 9. d3 (9. d4 {can be met by} b5 {and then 10...Bb7 with positions very similar to the ones resulting after 7.d4 immediately, but with our Bishop much better placed on b7 than on d7.}) 9... Re8 {The plan is to prepare d5. First step - protect the e5 pawn.} 10. Nbd2 h6 {Covering the g5 square. Just a useful move so that after playing d5 we'd be able to develop our Bishop to e6 if needed without White's Knight being able to disturb it by Ng5.} 11. Nf1 b5 {Making the Bishop go away, so that we won't have to worry about the captures on c6 after playing d5.} 12. Bc2 d5 {We are finally ready for the action in the centre!} 13. Ng3 {It is not very clear what the Knight does on g3 since the f5 and h5 squares are covered by our g6 pawn. On the other hand, there wasn't a better place for that Knight.} Be6 {Continuing the development and planning to stick to a central strategy by bringing the Queen to d6 and the a-Rook to d8. I prefer Black here, as we have more space for our pieces to manoeuver around and it is us who decide when we are ready to take the pressure off in the centre by either taking on e4 or pushing the pawn to d4.} *

