1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O {Together with 4.c3, this move is one of the most played ones after 3...g6. The ideas are similar to the ones in the 4.c3 line. The difference is that White first brings their King to safety and only then starts to fight for the centre. On the other hand, it allows us some extra time to finish our development as well.} Bg7 5. c3 {The idea is clear - prepare 6.d4.} a6 {Asking the b5 Bishop where does it want to retreat to.} 6. Ba4 {The main move.} d6 {Consolidating our e5 pawn and opening up the diagonal for the light squared Bishop.} 7. Bxc6+ {Possible but harmless.} bxc6 8. d4 {White wants to take on e5 and force us to take back with the d6 pawn which will weaken the c7-c6 ones.} f6 {Temporarily closing our Bishop on g7, and more importantly getting ready to capture back on e5 with the f-pawn which will keep our pawn structure harmonious and open up the f-file for our Rook after we castle short.} 9. Qb3 {White tries their best to make it difficult for Black to castle short.} a5 {With the idea to make White's Queen go away from the a2-g8 diagonal by means of 10...a4.} 10. a4 Nh6 {We had a plan B: the Knight now heads to f7 - which will cover the a2-g8 diagonal, enabling us to castle short.} 11. dxe5 ({Giving up the 2nd Bishop is not a good option, as after} 11. Bxh6 Bxh6 {we can either castle artificially by bringing the King to g7 via f8 or we can prepare a regular castle by playing Qe7 followed by Be6.}) 11... fxe5 12. Ng5 {Not allowing our Knight to f7.} Qe7 {Insisting on the idea of Nf7 followed by short castle. There is no way for White to stop it, which means we'll have a superior position thanks to the Bishop pair. The plan will then be to gain control in the centre by preparing d5.} *

