1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O {Together with 4.c3, this move is one of the most played ones after 3...g6. The ideas are similar to the ones in the 4.c3 line. The difference is that White first brings their King to safety and only then starts to fight for the centre. On the other hand, it allows us some extra time to finish our development as well.} Bg7 5. c3 {The idea is clear - prepare 6.d4.} a6 {Asking the b5 Bishop where does it want to retreat to.} 6. Ba4 {The main move.} d6 {Consolidating our e5 pawn and opening up the diagonal for the light squared Bishop.} 7. d4 {The main move, gaining control in the centre and trying to make use of the pin on the a4-e8 diagonal.} Bd7 {Covering up the a4-e8 diagonal. Thus, neutralizing White's pin over it and offering White a choice - to close the centre by means of 8.d5, to take the pressure off by taking on e5, or to maintain the pressure by continuing their development. Let's examine the best tries.} 8. d5 {White closes the centre heading to a structure that reminds us of the King's Indian. Our plan will then be to finish our development by castling short and then attacking White's pawn chain by means of either f5 or b5 if White will play c4.} Nce7 {Having less space, the trades are favourable for us, as it will leave more room for our remaining pieces to manoeuver around.} 9. Bxd7+ {The main move. Even though White agrees with the trade of one bishop, they argue that it will weaken our control over the e6 square and it will be more difficult to play f5 as then White's Knight will be able to jump to g5 and then to e6.} (9. c4 {Consolidates the centre and frees the c3 square for the b1 Knight to jump to.} b5 {An important move which doesn't allow White time to take control over the b5 square by developing the b1 Knight to c3. It goes along very well with our plan of attacking White's central pawn chain (e4, d5, c4).} 10. Bc2 {Temporarily sacrificing the c4 pawn, but trying to stop Black from playing f5.} (10. Bb3 {Trying to keep the control over the pawn chain in the centre.} f5 {Attacking White's pawn chain from the other side and also preparing to finish the development by means of Nf6 followed by short castle.} 11. exf5 (11. Ng5 {is not dangerous, we can answer with} Nf6 {and then castle short.}) 11... gxf5 {Now it is Black who has the better control in the centre. We will also be able to create threats on the semi-opened g-file after first finishing the development with Nf6, 0-0 and then Kh8, Rg8.} 12. a4 {White tries to create some counterplay on the Queenside.} Ng6 {Another way of finishing the development. The g6-Knight controls very well the h4-square and also makes room for our second Knight on e7. We plan on castling short and then start pushing our pawns in the centre (f4 & e4) which will lead to an attack on White's King. #1}) (10. cxb5 axb5 {Slowly White loses the control in the centre.} 11. Bb3 f5 {With better prospects for Black thanks to White's unstable pawn construction in the centre. We will first finish our development by playing 12...Nf6, short castle, and then apply more pressure on White's e4 and d5 pawns. #2}) 10... bxc4 11. Nbd2 f5 {There is no reason to try sticking to the extra pawn. Instead, we are consistent with our plan of attacking White's pawn chain.} 12. Ng5 {White has spotted the somewhat weak e6 square and tries to exploit it.} Nf6 13. Nxc4 (13. Ne6 {will now be met by} Bxe6 14. dxe6 Qc8 {winning the e6-pawn.}) 13... O-O {With better prospects for Black. 14...h6 is a serious threat as it will force White to either go for 15.Nh3 where after 15...fxe4 and 16...Bxh3 will leave us with a superior pawn structure or go for 15.Ne6, where after 15...Bxe6 16.dxe6 Qc8 will once again lead to the loss of the e6 pawn. #3}) (9. Bc2 {White tries to avoid the trade of pieces.} f5 {This is what I like about these positions with a closed centre. Black has very easy play. We attack White's pawn chain and finish our development.} 10. Nbd2 Nf6 11. c4 {White tries to consolidate the centre, but it takes so much time that they will lack it for creating counterplay.} O-O {Black has successfully completed the development and will now start an attack on the Kingside.} 12. b4 {In the King's Indian spirit - White's counterplay should be on the Queenside - attacking Black's pawn chain by means of c5.} h6 {Preparing g5, Ng6, g4 in order to disturb White's Knight on f3. Pay attention to the fact that compared to a King's Indian, White's b1 Knight is on d2 rather than on c3 which actually takes away the d2 square from the f3 Knight and results in a very clumsy position for White.} 13. Bb2 g5 {One idea we can continue with is to bring our Queen via e8 to h5 and then follow up with g4. Another one is to close up the position even more by means of f4, then play Ng6 followed up by g4 as well. Black's attack on the Kingside is much faster than White's on the Queenside. #4}) 9... Qxd7 10. c4 {Consolidating the centre and planning to develop the Knight to c3.} h6 {The solution to the weakness of our e6-square. We cover the g5 square first so that White's Knight isn't able to use it after we play f5.} 11. Nc3 f5 {The same idea of fighting against White's e4, d5, c4 pawn chain. Following up with Nf6 and short castle.} 12. Ne1 {White's plan is to consolidate the central pawn chain by playing f3 and then bring the e1 Knight to d3, preparing c5.} (12. exf5 {Taking of the pressure in the centre and then trying to make use of the somewhat weak light squares.} gxf5 {On the other hand, it gives us nice control in the centre. Also, after we'll finish the development, these pawns (e5 and f5) will start moving.} 13. Nh4 {White tries to get to our King by means of 14.Qh5+, but also plans to fix the pawn structure by playing 14.f4.} Nf6 {Covering h5.} 14. f4 {With the idea of opening up the f-file so that our f5-pawn would become weak. We can't allow that.} e4 15. Be3 {White finishes their development.} O-O {And so do we.} 16. h3 {Taking control of the g4 square, so that Black's Knight would not be able to disturb White's Bishop on e3.} c6 {We do still fight against White's pawn chain in the centre, planning to follow up with Rc8, take on d5 and then put extra pressure on the d5 pawn by means of b5-b4 - attacking the Knight on c3.} 17. dxc6 bxc6 {Allows us a nice pawn majority in the centre, but we should be careful about advancing it, as a move like d5 played at the wrong time will weaken our dark squares (d4, c5).} 18. Rf2 {Trying to put pressure on our d6-pawn and force it to advance to d5.} Qe6 {Eyeing the c4-pawn.} 19. Rd2 Ne8 {With an advantage for Black. The d6-pawn is now safe, meaning that White's c4-pawn is hanging. If White protects it, we have another idea as well - disturb White's Knight on h4 by means of Bf6. #5}) 12... Nf6 {We stay true to our setup.} 13. f3 {White's pawn chain now resembles the Chinese wall, it looks very long and stable. Is it the case though?} O-O 14. Nd3 {White hopes that they will be faster with the attack on the Queenside than Black's attack on the Kingside.} Rf7 {Preparing to bring the 2nd Rook to the Kingside as well!} 15. Be3 {White is still preparing c5.} Raf8 16. c5 g5 {The position is balanced. Our idea is to breakthrough on the Kingside by means of g4 so the e7 Knight can come closer to the action on g6.  I believe it is easier to play this kind of position for Black, as an attack on the Kingside is much more dangerous than one on the Queenside. Worst-case scenario - we can lose the battle on the Queenside, while the worst which can happen for White is to win some pawns on the Queenside and still get mated. #6} *

