1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O {Together with 4.c3, this move is one of the most played ones after 3...g6. The ideas are similar to the ones in the 4.c3 line. The difference is that White first brings their King to safety and only then starts to fight for the centre. On the other hand, it allows us some extra time to finish our development as well.} Bg7 5. c3 {The idea is clear - prepare 6.d4.} a6 {Asking the b5 Bishop where does it want to retreat to.} 6. Ba4 {The main move.} d6 {Consolidating our e5 pawn and opening up the diagonal for the light squared Bishop.} 7. d4 {The main move, gaining control in the centre and trying to make use of the pin on the a4-e8 diagonal.} Bd7 {Covering up the a4-e8 diagonal. Thus, neutralizing White's pin over it and offering White a choice - to close the centre by means of 8.d5, to take the pressure off by taking on e5, or to maintain the pressure by continuing their development. Let's examine the best tries.} 8. Bg5 {Asking Black a question - on which square to place the g8 Knight in order to cover the Queen.} Nge7 {We go for this move in order to enable the later ideas with f5 should White close the center with 9.d5.} 9. d5 {Closing up the centre and forcing our Knight to its initial square.} (9. dxe5 {White argues that our Knight won't be optimally placed on e7 in the resulting position as it will not put pressure on the e4 pawn.} dxe5 10. Nbd2 {Finishing the development.} (10. Qc1 {Making room for the Rook to come to the d-file and x-ray our Queen. There are also ideas linked with the Bh6 move.} O-O 11. Rd1 {Our pieces are a little bit unhappy with the little room for manoeuvering they gave. We should solve this problem.} Qe8 {Planning on bringing our own Rook to the d-file.} 12. Bh6 {White tries to trade Bishops in order to later use the slightly weakened dark squares around our King.} Rd8 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Qe3 {The optimal place for White's Queen, as it controls both flanks. White also want to develop their b1 Knight to d2, perhaps continuing then to c4.} Nc8 {Our Knight on e7 was very unhappy, we find a better place for it - the d6 square and reroute towards it. Later we can consolidate our e5 pawn by playing f6, following up with b5, Be6, and Qe7 with a balanced position. #1}) 10... h6 11. Be3 O-O {Black has finished the development as well, now we will have to start improving the position of our pieces.} 12. Bc5 Re8 {Getting rid of the pin, thus freeing our e7 Knight.} 13. Bb3 {The Bishop had nothing to do on a4 any longer. Moving it to b3 allows ideas with Nc4, as before it wasn't possible due to the b5 fork.} b6 {Forcing White's dark squared Bishop to leave its active position.} 14. Ba3 Na5 {The plan is to restrict White's a3 Bishop by means of c5, following up then with Qc7 and Rd8. After which, the fight in the centre will begin. We can later consider ideas with b5 and c4. #2}) 9... Nb8 {The Knight on b8 is of course not a great piece, so we would love for White to capture on d7 and allow our Knight to take that square.} 10. Bc2 {Making it more difficult for Black to develop the b8 Knight.} (10. c4 {An idea which we're already familiar with, White consolidates the centre and wants to bring the Knight to c3.} h6 {Asking the Bishop to leave and take control over the g5-square.} 11. Be3 f5 {With a balanced position. Our ideas stay the same - attack White's central pawn chain (e4, d5, c4). We'll continue with short castle and then we'll have a pleasant choice. Either attack the pawn chain from the other side by means of f5 or prepare an attack on the Kingside combining the ideas of g5, Ng6 with the one of f4. #3}) 10... h6 {However, given that the position has a closed character - time becomes less important and we may slowly finish our development.} 11. Be3 O-O {The idea is still to attack White's pawn chain by means of f5. It will be great if we'll then capture back on f5 with the Bishop, as it would make room for our b8 Knight, enabling the move Nd7.} 12. Qd2 Kh7 {Pawn attacked - pawn protected!} 13. c4 {White's Knight wants to land on c3.} f5 {Even though White's c2 Bishop is x-raying our King, we have very good control over the f5 square and have nothing to worry about. 14...f4 is now a threat as it would trap White's e3 Bishop.} 14. exf5 Bxf5 {As planned, the d7 square is now free for our Knight.} 15. Nc3 Nd7 {The optimal position for our Knight as it keeps an eye on the c5 square and can also go to f6 if needed.} 16. Nh4 {White would love to trade their Knight for our f5 Bishop, as the x-ray on the b1-h7 diagonal will then become dangerous.} Bxc2 17. Qxc2 Qe8 {Protecting the g6-pawn and planning to follow up with 18...Nf5 - trading more pair pieces. Then we can take back with the pawn on f5, the Queen will come to g6, the Knight to f6 and we can start an attack on White's King on the g-file. #4} *

