1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O {Together with 4.c3, this move is one of the most played ones after 3...g6. The ideas are similar to the ones in the 4.c3 line. The difference is that White first brings their King to safety and only then starts to fight for the centre. On the other hand, it allows us some extra time to finish our development as well.} Bg7 5. c3 {The idea is clear - prepare 6.d4.} a6 {Asking the b5 Bishop where does it want to retreat to.} 6. Ba4 {The main move.} d6 {Consolidating our e5 pawn and opening up the diagonal for the light squared Bishop.} 7. d4 {The main move, gaining control in the centre and trying to make use of the pin on the a4-e8 diagonal.} Bd7 {Covering up the a4-e8 diagonal. Thus, neutralizing White's pin over it and offering White a choice - to close the centre by means of 8.d5, to take the pressure off by taking on e5, or to maintain the pressure by continuing their development. Let's examine the best tries.} 8. dxe5 {Taking off the pressure in the centre can rarely give any hopes at all for an advantage.} dxe5 9. Be3 (9. Bg5 Nge7 {transposes to 8.Bg5 Nge7 9.dxe5.}) 9... Nf6 {Compared to the lines with the Knight on e7, where we had to solve the problem of its passive placement, here we have the option of bringing it to the more active f6-square from where it puts pressure on the e4-pawn.} 10. Nbd2 O-O {Development finished!} 11. h3 {Covering the g4-square so that our Knight can't disturb the Bishop on e3.} Nh5 {We have another plan for it though, the Knight aims for the f4 square, from where it will keep an eye on the h3 pawn, enabling different ideas connected with a piece sacrifice on h3. We will then continue with a central strategy, bringing the Queen to e7 and the a-Rook to d8.} *

