1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O {Together with 4.c3, this move is one of the most played ones after 3...g6. The ideas are similar to the ones in the 4.c3 line. The difference is that White first brings their King to safety and only then starts to fight for the centre. On the other hand, it allows us some extra time to finish our development as well.} Bg7 5. c3 {The idea is clear - prepare 6.d4.} a6 {Asking the b5 Bishop where does it want to retreat to.} 6. Ba4 {The main move.} d6 {Consolidating our e5 pawn and opening up the diagonal for the light squared Bishop.} 7. d4 {The main move, gaining control in the centre and trying to make use of the pin on the a4-e8 diagonal.} Bd7 {Covering up the a4-e8 diagonal. Thus, neutralizing White's pin over it and offering White a choice - to close the centre by means of 8.d5, to take the pressure off by taking on e5, or to maintain the pressure by continuing their development. Let's examine the best tries.} 8. Be3 {Maintaining the tension in the centre and planning to finish the development by means of 9.Nbd2.} Nf6 {Developing move, attacking the e4 pawn and preparing to castle short.} 9. Nbd2 O-O {Now that we finished our development, the threat is to go after White's dark squared Bishop by playing 10...Ng4.} 10. h3 Re8 {Now we will see a battle of patience. We should try to find as many useful moves as possible while keeping the tension in the centre. White will do the same. The side who loses their patience first will be the one to suffer. We threaten to take on d4 and then collect the e4-pawn.} 11. Bc2 h6 {Taking the g5-square under control.} 12. Re1 a5 $5 {A bit of an unusual move - the idea is to take more space on the Queenside and try to weaken White's long dark diagonal by means of a4-a3.} 13. Bd3 {The best try. White sticks to a central strategy, avoiding to make unnecessary weaknesses and maintaining the tension in the centre.} (13. d5 {will be met by} Ne7 {where we'll start an attack on the Kingside by means of Nh5/f4, g5, Ng6. Another idea can be Nh7, f5. Both work just fine.}) (13. a4 {Not allowing our pawn to reach the a4 and the a3 squares.} exd4 {White's last move had a downside - it made the b4-square weak.} 14. cxd4 Nb4 {Our Knight has now a fantastic outpost where no one can disturb it. If allowed, we'd love to get the pair of Bishops.} 15. Bb1 Re7 {Now that the e-file has opened for us, we will put pressure on the e4-pawn by means of Qe8, Bc6. #1}) 13... b6 {A solid move with a hidden purpose. We want to bring our Queen to b7, from where it will eye the e4-pawn.} 14. Qc2 {I believe this is one of the best lines for White as their play is very logical. Just follow a central strategy by placing all of the pieces close to the centre.} a4 {Restricting White's d2 Knight a little bit while keeping in mind the ideas of weakening the long dark diagonal by means of a3.} 15. Rad1 {White's Rook x-rays our Queen, meaning that the time has come for it to leave for a better place.} Qc8 {From here, our Queen not only has the idea of moving to b7 in order to pressure the e4 pawn, but we get additional ideas linked with a piece sacrifice on h3.} 16. Qc1 {White shows true patience. Also, from c1 the Queen eyes the h6-pawn.} (16. Nf1 {The moment one of White's pieces departs from the centre, we make use of it!} exd4 17. Nxd4 (17. cxd4 {is not possible due to} Nb4) 17... d5 {Simplifying the position and keeping the game balanced. #2}) 16... Kh7 {Prophylaxis at its finest. The h6-pawn was definitely not attacked, but we protect it - just in case.} 17. b3 {The useful moves ended for White so they try to open up additional files for their pieces.} axb3 18. axb3 Qb7 {The Queen feels just fine on b7 as it eyes the e4-pawn, but also keeps close the newly opened a-file.} 19. d5 {Closing up the centre in the hope that having less space, Black will be unable to position well all of their pieces.} Ne7 20. c4 {Now if White's d2-Knight would be on c3 rather than on d2 - White would have a clear advantage. In this case, we have just enough time to get some counterplay.} c6 {I hope that by this point, you have got the feeling about playing with and against pawn chains. There's nothing difficult about them. The strategy is to attack them from one side or the other, depending on what are our possibilities.  Here, as f5 is difficult to achieve, we attack it from the Queenside planning to follow up with b5 with imminent simplifications. Thus, a balanced position. #3} *

