1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O {Together with 4.c3, this move is one of the most played ones after 3...g6. The ideas are similar to the ones in the 4.c3 line. The difference is that White first brings their King to safety and only then starts to fight for the centre. On the other hand, it allows us some extra time to finish our development as well.} Bg7 5. c3 {The idea is clear - prepare 6.d4.} a6 {Asking the b5 Bishop where does it want to retreat to.} 6. Ba4 {The main move.} d6 {Consolidating our e5 pawn and opening up the diagonal for the light squared Bishop.} 7. d4 {The main move, gaining control in the centre and trying to make use of the pin on the a4-e8 diagonal.} Bd7 {Covering up the a4-e8 diagonal. Thus, neutralizing White's pin over it and offering White a choice - to close the centre by means of 8.d5, to take the pressure off by taking on e5, or to maintain the pressure by continuing their development. Let's examine the best tries.} 8. Re1 {The move which was played the most according to my database. White protects the e4 pawn and wants to delay a bit the moment of decision for where their remaining light pieces should move to.} Nf6 9. Nbd2 (9. h3 {A move order meant to delay the development of the b1-Knight, so that if Black takes on d4, after cxd4, White's Knight could develop to c3.} O-O {Black finishes the development normally.} 10. Bc2 {An interesting move, as it fights against Black's idea with 10...exd5 11.cxd5 Nb4, which is what Black wants after White's 10.Nbd2. The difference is that if we try to do the same thing here, after 11.Bb3, White's Knight will be able to come to c3, a much better position.} Re8 {A solid move, waiting for White to develop their Knight on d2.} 11. Nbd2 b5 {Switching to a different plan, one linked with taking space on the Queenside.} ({White isn't afraid of} 11... exd4 12. cxd4 Nb4 {as after} 13. Bb3 {Black doesn't have the move} Nd3 {because of} 14. Bxf7+ {that's the downside of Black's Rook on f8 rather than on e8 compared to the mainline.}) 12. Nf1 {Even though White's Knight on f1 doesn't have great prospects, as it will be quite restricted by our g6-pawn if it lands on g3, White needs to open up the diagonal for their dark squared Bishop.} Qb8 {The Queen is rerouting to a better square, b7, from where it will both put pressure on the e4-pawn, but also support the pawns' advance on the Queenside.} 13. Ng3 a5 {The b2, c3, d4 pawn chain is what Black wants to attack here.} 14. Be3 {Finishing the development and hoping that a central strategy will be enough to keep an advantage.} a4 {With a balanced position, as we have a nice play on the Queenside. #1} 15. Z0 (15. a3 {preventing Black's b4 and a3 isn't good, as it weakens the light squares, which we can use immediately by playing} Na5 {and the Knight aims for c4. Black's plan is simple, improve the position of the Queen by playing Qb7 and then choose from ideas with Na5-c4 or attacking White's pawn chain with b4.})) 9... O-O {Black is the first one to complete the development. White will have to decide what plan to choose now.} 10. h3 {Prohylaxis against a potential Bg4.} (10. Nf1 $6 {Not the best try, as the Knight on f1 doesn't really have great prospects as after bringing it to g3 it will still be very restricted by our g6-pawn. It also doesn't control the centre well from there, giving Black the opportunity to start targeting the e4-pawn.} b5 11. Bc2 exd4 {Opening up the e-file so that the e4-pawn becomes a target for us to attack.} 12. Nxd4 {Avoiding the trouble with the d4-pawn.} (12. cxd4 {Looks natural, but makes the d4-pawn run into some trouble, as White did not play h3 preventing our next move.} Bg4 {13...Bxf3 followed by 14...Nxd4 if White recaptures with the Queen is now the threat.} 13. Be3 Nh5 {Once again, 14...Bxf3 is being threatened, as the Bishop on g7 attacks the d4-pawn once again.} 14. Ng3 Qf6 {Reinforcing the threat of 15...Bxf3, as even after 16.gxf3, we can collect the d4-pawn. White doesn't have a good way of solving this problem, leaving Black with a clear advantage. #2} ({Taking on g3 now and then on f3 is possible but it doesn't grant us much, as after} 14... Nxg3 15. hxg3 Bxf3 {White has the option of} 16. gxf3 {keeping their central pawns alive. We've got a better move instead!})) 12... Re8 {We then slowly build up the pressure on the e4-pawn.} 13. h3 {Prophylaxis against potential ideas of Bg4 and Ng4.} Ne5 {White's Knight is quite well placed on d4, so we want to make it leave by playing c5. Our Knight might also want to jump to c4, from where it will keep an eye on the b2-pawn, not allowing White to develop comfortably.} 14. f4 Nc4 {Our strategy has been to provoke White to create more weaknesses. By playing f4 they will no longer be able to defend the e4 pawn by means of f3 and there might also be trouble around the dark squares (f2, e3, d4).} 15. b3 {We've succeeded in provoking yet another weakening - the one of the long dark diagonal. White didn't have much choice though. The alternative would be to keep their Bishop on c1 forever, thus not allowing the Rook from a1 into the game.} Nb6 16. Ng3 {Trying to consolidate the e4-pawn.} c5 {Time has come for this Knight to leave its active position.} 17. Nf3 Bc6 {We keep reassuring the e4-pawn and plan to combine ideas on the long dark diagonal with creating even more weaknesses in White's camp by pushing a5-a4. At the same time, we can continue making useful moves by bringing the Queen to c7, while the a-Rook may reposition to d8. #3}) (10. Bxc6 {Another modest try, good enough to only get an equal position.} Bxc6 {Offering a temporary pawn sacrifice.} 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Nxe5 {White has too many tactical weaknesses - the Knight on e5, the e4-pawn and the Queen on d1. We can use them in order to get our pawn back.} Bxe4 13. Nxe4 Qxd1 {It turns out that the Rook on e1 is overloaded.} 14. Nxf6+ {An intermediate move which doesn't change much.} (14. Rxd1 {allows} Nxe4) 14... Bxf6 {Now the e5-Knight will be left unprotected.} 15. Rxd1 Bxe5 $11 {With a nearly symmetrical position and complete equality. #4}) (10. dxe5 {Also suboptimal, as it allows too many simplifications.} Nxe5 {We take with the Knight in order to be able to trade the light squared Bishops. If White doesn't take on e5, we will then continue by increasing the pressure on the e4-pawn as we saw in other similar lines.} 11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. Nf3 {Attacking the e5-pawn.} Re8 {An easy way to protect it.} 13. Bg5 {What do we do about Bishops on top of diagonals? Start the hunt on them!} b5 14. Bb3 h6 15. Bxf6 {The Bishop doesn't have a great choice, as 15.Be3 leaves the e4-pawn unprotected, while 15.Bh4 leaves the Bishop stranded on the Kingside, where there's not much for it to do.} Bxf6 {White hopes to be able to use the d5 square for their pieces and claim that our dark squared Bishop is quite passive. However, the d5 square can be easily covered by our c6 pawn, the King will go to g7, in order to protect the h6 pawn and we'll then follow up with a central strategy by bringing the Queen to e7 and the a-Rook to d8. #5}) 10... exd4 {A concrete approach - we force White to either give up on the pair of Bishops or to agree on trading the light squared one.} 11. cxd4 Nb4 12. Bxd7 ({There is no time for White to play} 12. Bb3 {as it will be met by} Nd3 {with a very unpleasant fork.}) 12... Qxd7 {13...Nd3 is still a serious threat.} 13. Nf1 c5 {Once again, we do our best to attack White's central pawns.} 14. a3 Nc6 {With the idea of taking on d4 as many times as possible, forcing White's Queen on d4. After which we can play Rfe8, pressuring the e4-pawn and threatening to actually take it by Nxe4, attacking the d4-Queen with our dark squared Bishop.} 15. d5 Nd4 $1 {A pawn sacrifice in the spirit of the King's Indian, where the most important thing is too keep our dark squared Bishop alive!} ({White tries to either force us to close the long dark diagonal for good after} 15... Ne5 16. Nxe5 dxe5 {which is an outcome we want to avoid at all costs, or to make our Knight go to a clumsy place - e7 or b/d8.}) 16. Nxd4 cxd4 17. Qxd4 {White claims that a pawn is a pawn.} (17. b4 {White wants to get to the d4-pawn with the Bishop by playing 18.Bb2.} Rfe8 {Creating threats of our own against the e4-pawn.} 18. f3 Qb5 19. Bb2 (19. Qxd4 {is no longer possible due to the x-ray on the e-file.} Nxd5 {wins material.}) 19... d3 $44 {It is not easy to get to our d3 pawn, as it is well protected by our Queen. Note the weakness of the a7-g1 diagonal, our Queen might want to infiltrate into White's camp by means of Qb6+, Qf2. Tactical motifs with Nxd5, where White's Rook on e1 and the Bishop on b2 are hanging in the end are to be taken into account. #6}) 17... Rfe8 {Threatening on playing18.Nxe4, winning back the sacrificed pawn.} 18. Qb4 {White finds a way to protect both the Rook on e1 (so we won't be able to capture on d5) and also the e4-pawn.} Qb5 {When we spot the piece on which our opponent relies the most, we should try to either drive it away or if not possible, trade it.} 19. Qxb5 axb5 {With a balanced position. White doesn't have a way to keep the extra pawn. #7} 20. Z0 ({If White tries to protect the e4 one by playing} 20. f3 {we will reply with} Nxd5 {(the Rook on e1 is hanging) and after} 21. Rd1 {we have} Nb6 {where after} 22. Rxd6 {there's} Nc4 {- with a fork on the Rook from d6 and the b2 pawn. The position tends to simplify a lot going into a very drawish endgame.}) *

