1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. c3 {The idea of this setup is to prepare d4, force Black to take and then recapture with the c3-pawn in order to get some nice control in the centre. The central pawn structure advantage will grant White more space for their light pieces to maneuver around, as well as prospectives of an attack on the Kingside. Black's counterplay will be linked with combining pawns advance on the Queenside (in order to secure important squares for their light pieces) with attacking White's central pawns (e4 and d4).  After years of playing the Ruy Lopez with both colors, I find that it's easier to go wrong while playing with the White pieces, as the 'visual' advantage of the space tends to make one over-optimistic about their chances. It often leads to getting over-ambitious and pushing too hard which is of course convenient for Black. Therefore, arm yourself with patience and you'll be ready to learn the most important ideas Black has in this structure!} a6 {We want White to decide on which diagonal should their Bishop land.} 5. Ba4 Bg7 {We go for the most natural developing move.} ({Avoiding all the} 5... f5 {drama. It doesn't work now as after} 6. d4 fxe4 7. Nxe5 {we no longer have the} d5 {move with a tempo (compared to when White had the Bishop on c4).}) 6. d4 {Forcing Black to take on as there's no other good way of continuing our development.} exd4 (6... Nge7 {would be met by} 7. d5) (6... Nf6 {drops the e5-pawn}) ({while} 6... d6 {allows} 7. Bxc6+ {ruining our pawn structure.}) 7. cxd4 b5 {Making sure to be able to play d6 or d5 without worrying about White taking on c6. White now has two options, both of them viable and played extensively.} 8. Bb3 {The most natural move - pressuring the f7 pawn and not allowing Black to play d5.} Nge7 {Continuing the development and preparing to castle short.} 9. d5 {White tries to make our Knight leave its central position for a worse one.} Na5 {Trading our Knight for White's Bishop is what we hope for.} 10. Bd2 {A move with 2 ideas - the first is to force our Knight to take on b3 and the 2nd is to bring the Bishop to c3 and trade our strong g7-Bishop.} (10. Bc2 {The direct way to avoid the trade.} O-O 11. O-O d6 {With a transpositionto 9.0-0 0-0 10.d5. #1}) (10. d6 {The most aggressive try- White wants to spoil Black's pawn structure and get a lot of activity for their Queen.} cxd6 11. Qxd6 {The downside is that White has also opened the a8-h1 diagonal for our Bishop and we can now attack the e4 pawn.} Bb7 12. Nc3 {Developing and in the same time protecting the e4 pawn.} Qb8 {The idea is to get rid of White's Queen o d6 so that the Knight on e7 will not hang anymore and we'd be able to castle.} 13. Qxb8+ ({If White tries to keep the pressure on the e7 Knight by playing} 13. Qb4 {we can take} Nxb3 {and if White recaptures} 14. axb3 {we can play} d6 {(closing up the a3-f8 diagonal) and then castle.}) 13... Rxb8 14. Bf4 {White do their best to finish the development quickly.} Rc8 15. O-O {Black doesn't really want to take on c3 and give up the very strong dark squared Bishop just yet.} O-O {Black is better thanks to the targets our Bishops have - one eyes the b2-pawn and the other the e4-pawn. 16...b4 is a serious threat. Black also wouldn't mind getting the pair of Bishops after an eventual Nxb3. #2}) 10... Nxb3 11. Qxb3 {Now 12.Bc3 is what White aims for.} c5 {A very energic reply - we want to get more space and squares and also challenge White's Queen position.} 12. Bc3 {Going for the Bishop trade immediately.} (12. dxc6 {The first move to consider.} O-O $1 {We don't take the pawn back, but try to get an advantage in development instead.} 13. Bc3 (13. cxd7 {would be met with} Bxd7 {where we'll have the pair of Bishops in an open position, thus more than enough compensation for the sacrificed pawn. White would still need some moves to finish the development and we can use it to start gaining control over the light squares by playing Be6-c4. White will struggle as they don't have a light squared Bishop to cover the light square complex.}) 13... Bxc3+ 14. Qxc3 Nxc6 {White has managed to trade our best piece - the dark squared Bishop and now hopes to be able to use the better pawn structure (3 island of pawns vs 2 islands) to their advantage.} 15. Nbd2 Bb7 {The best place for our Bishop - putting pressure on the e4-pawn and also supporting the d5 breakthrough.} 16. O-O Qe7 $11 {Connecting the Rooks and planning to prepare d5, which will solve the problem of our inferior pawn structure. Our next move will be 17...Rac8, x-raying White's Queen, followed by either immediately d5 or Rfd8 first and then d5. #3}) (12. d6 {Isn't dangerous.} Nc6 13. Bc3 c4 {Forcing White's Queen to a suboptimal position.} 14. Qc2 O-O 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. O-O Bb7 {Black's position is preferable thanks to the strong Bishop on b7 which will put pressure on the e4-pawn. An unpleasant threat is 17...Nb4 followed by 18...Nd3, planting a 'thorn' in White's camp. #4}) 12... f6 $1 {An odd-looking move, but one of great strength! We avoid the Bishop trade for now and argue that the c3 square was ideal for White's b1 Knight rather than the Bishop. The plan is to play 13...d6 if allowed, then castle and f5, attacking White's pawn chain in the centre. It will be then unclear what has White achieved by bringing the Queen to b3.} 13. d6 {The only way to stop Black's plan.} Nc6 {The thing about such advanced pawns as the d6 one is that they can easily become a weakness rather than a strength, as it's impossible to protect them with another pawn. White's Queen and Bishop are also quite unstable, as we can challenge them by either playing c4 or b4.} 14. Qd5 {White activates the Queen as much as possible but allows for their Bishop to be driven away from c3.} b4 15. Bd2 Bb7 {X-raying White's most active piece.} 16. Qxc5 (16. O-O {would be met by} Qb6 {protecting the c5 pawn and the b7 Bishop and planning to continue with 17...Nd4.}) 16... f5 {Opening up our monster Bishop once again. 17...Bxb2 is a serious threat, as the Rook on a1 will run into big trouble.} 17. e5 (17. Bg5 {would be a big mistake, as after} Qa5 {White doesn't have a good way to avoid the Queen trade and then the b2 and e4 pawns can not be both saved.}) 17... Rc8 {White has managed to close the diagonal for our g7 Bishop, but now, the e5 pawn become a target. 18...Nxe5 is already a threat.} 18. Qe3 g5 $1 {This is my favourite move in the whole course! It looks like our King might be in trouble, but it's actually the other way around. We want to play 19...g4 and win the e5 pawn, which will open up the diagonals for our super-strong Bishops.} 19. e6 {White tries to play for mate.} (19. Nxg5 {Getting greedy is not the right answer.} f4 $1 {Making White's Queen go on a less optimal square first, and only then capturing the e5-pawn.} 20. Qxf4 Nxe5 {With a winning position as there are too many threats White copes with. One is the fork on d3, another is 21...Rc4. 21...Rf8 is also unpleasant. #5} 21. Z0 (21. O-O {will be met by} Rc4 {where if White plays} 22. Qf5 {(not allowing us to castle) we can play} Qf6 {where we will either castle on the next move or trade Queens, leaving White in big trouble, as the b2-pawn is very weak and the a1 Rook and b1-Knight are stuck on their initial squares for good. We will basically have 2 extra pieces to play with.})) (19. Qxg5 $4 {Is terrible.} Qxg5 20. Bxg5 Nxe5 $19 {Winning one of the 2 pawns back and opening up the long diagonals for our Bishops. The b2 pawn is in big trouble and its d6 and g2 brothers might have to worry as well. #6}) 19... g4 {Making White's Knight leave from covering the d4-square, which we plan to occupy with our Knight.} 20. e7 {An intermediate move that makes our Queen go away but closes the e-file.} (20. Ng5 {will be met by} Nd4 {and White's position will be hopeless.}) 20... Qa5 {The best place for our Queen, as it controls the 5th rank, where the most important squares for our pieces are located. It can jump to e5 if necessary to trade Queens.} 21. Qg5 {White continues to ignore the attacked f3-Knight and goes for the g7-Bishop instead.} Qd5 $3 {'THE' move. We get ready for the moment White will take on g7 and attack our Rook on h8. Now that our Queen controls the g8 square, the Rook will not be trapped.} 22. Qxg7 Rg8 23. Qxh7 gxf3 $19 {With a winning position thanks to the much more active pieces. It is now White's King who starts to get in trouble. Look at our pieces and at White's pieces: the difference is clear. 24...Nd4 with the threat of a fork on c2 is in the air, various captures on g2 are also unpleasant for White. #7} 24. Z0 ({Our King is safe on e8 as} 24. Qh5+ {is just a check which we can meet with} Qf7) *

