1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. c3 {The idea of this setup is to prepare d4, force Black to take and then recapture with the c3-pawn in order to get some nice control in the centre. The central pawn structure advantage will grant White more space for their light pieces to maneuver around, as well as prospectives of an attack on the Kingside. Black's counterplay will be linked with combining pawns advance on the Queenside (in order to secure important squares for their light pieces) with attacking White's central pawns (e4 and d4).  After years of playing the Ruy Lopez with both colors, I find that it's easier to go wrong while playing with the White pieces, as the 'visual' advantage of the space tends to make one over-optimistic about their chances. It often leads to getting over-ambitious and pushing too hard which is of course convenient for Black. Therefore, arm yourself with patience and you'll be ready to learn the most important ideas Black has in this structure!} a6 {We want White to decide on which diagonal should their Bishop land.} 5. Ba4 Bg7 {We go for the most natural developing move.} ({Avoiding all the} 5... f5 {drama. It doesn't work now as after} 6. d4 fxe4 7. Nxe5 {we no longer have the} d5 {move with a tempo (compared to when White had the Bishop on c4).}) 6. d4 {Forcing Black to take on as there's no other good way of continuing our development.} exd4 (6... Nge7 {would be met by} 7. d5) (6... Nf6 {drops the e5-pawn}) ({while} 6... d6 {allows} 7. Bxc6+ {ruining our pawn structure.}) 7. cxd4 b5 {Making sure to be able to play d6 or d5 without worrying about White taking on c6. White now has two options, both of them viable and played extensively.} 8. Bb3 {The most natural move - pressuring the f7 pawn and not allowing Black to play d5.} Nge7 {Continuing the development and preparing to castle short.} 9. a4 $5 {White argues that we over-expanded on the Queenside and tries to make use of it.} Na5 {Sacrificing a pawn to get the Bishop pair.} 10. axb5 Nxb3 11. Qxb3 Bb7 {Now both of our Bishops are targeting White's central pawns - e4 is hanging.} 12. Nc3 {Protects e4 and continues the development.} axb5 13. Rxa8 Qxa8 {Increasing the pressure against the e4-pawn.} 14. O-O {White doesn't protect the e-pawn, as taking it is dangerous for now, as we might run into trouble on the e-file.} O-O {Now that our King is safe, taking on e4 will soon become a threat.} 15. Re1 b4 {Attracting White's Queen to a less favourable position.} 16. Qxb4 Nc6 {Attacking both the Queen and the pawn.} 17. Qc4 Qa6 {White can't avoid the Queens trade, as it will leave the pawn unprotected.} 18. Qxa6 (18. Qc5 {can be met by} d6) 18... Bxa6 {White now has to protect the pawn.} 19. Be3 Rb8 {Attacking the b2-pawn. Black has enough compensation to keep the position balanced thanks to the pair of Bishops and the control over the semi-opened b-file.} *

