1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. c3 {The idea of this setup is to prepare d4, force Black to take and then recapture with the c3-pawn in order to get some nice control in the centre. The central pawn structure advantage will grant White more space for their light pieces to maneuver around, as well as prospectives of an attack on the Kingside. Black's counterplay will be linked with combining pawns advance on the Queenside (in order to secure important squares for their light pieces) with attacking White's central pawns (e4 and d4).   After years of playing the Ruy Lopez with both colors, I find that it's easier to go wrong while playing with the White pieces, as the 'visual' advantage of the space tends to make one over-optimistic about their chances. It often leads to getting over-ambitious and pushing too hard which is of course convenient for Black. Therefore, arm yourself with patience and you'll be ready to learn the most important ideas Black has in this structure!} a6 {We want White to decide on which diagonal should their Bishop land.} 5. Ba4 Bg7 {We go for the most natural developing move.} ({Avoiding all the} 5... f5 {drama. It doesn't work now as after} 6. d4 fxe4 7. Nxe5 {we no longer have the} d5 {move with a tempo (compared to when White had the Bishop on c4).}) 6. d4 {Forcing Black to take on as there's no other good way of continuing our development.} exd4 (6... Nge7 {would be met by} 7. d5) (6... Nf6 {drops the e5-pawn}) ({while} 6... d6 {allows} 7. Bxc6+ {ruining our pawn structure.}) 7. cxd4 b5 {Making sure to be able to play d6 or d5 without worrying about White taking on c6. White now has two options, both of them viable and played extensively.} 8. Bb3 {The most natural move - pressuring the f7 pawn and not allowing Black to play d5.} Nge7 {Continuing the development and preparing to castle short.} 9. O-O O-O {Both sides have brought their Kings to safety and it is now White to choose from a variety of plans.} 10. Nc3 {The most logical try; a natural developing move which was played most.} (10. d5 {Once again, White forces our Knight to a less favourable position.} Na5 {The Knight on a5 is not ideally placed, thus a trade of it for the b3 Bishop is what we want.} 11. Bd2 {The a5 Knight is hanging and White wants to then trade the dark squared Bishops by playing Bc3. Taking on b2 is rarely good - even if we will win an exchange - giving up the dark squared Bishop while White gets to keep their will make our dark squares around the King very weak, thus endangering our King's safety.} (11. d6 {White tries to get a superior pawn structure (2 island of pawns vs 3 island of pawns).} cxd6 12. Qxd6 Bb7 {Finishing the development with a tempi- the e4 pawn is now attacked!} 13. Nc3 Nc8 {Making White's Queen go away from the good position on d6.} 14. Qd3 Nb6 {Taking the c4 square under control. Now one of our Knights will be able to jump to c4 any time we please.} 15. Bg5 Qb8 {The Queen stays better on b8 than on the c-file as it doesn't have to worry about x-rays over the c-file after a move like Rac1. In the same time, we want to increase the pressure against the e4 pawn by bringing our Rook to e8.} 16. e5 {White takes the f6 square under control and tries to get a grip over the dark squares by bringing their c3 Knight to e4. Taking on f3 and then on e5 is dangerous precisely because of the weakness of the dark squares.} Nbc4 {Instead we activate one more piece attacking both b2 and e5. Black is better as White doesn't have a way to protect both pawns. #1}) (11. Bc2 {Avoiding giving up the Bishop pair.} d6 {Now White no longer has the option of playing d6. At the same time, we open up our c8-Bishop.} 12. Nc3 {White continues the development.} b4 {Forcing the Knight to leave its ideal position on c3.} 13. Ne2 c6 {Solving the problem of the a5 Knight. White can't avoid taking on c6 as after 14...cxd5 15.exd5 Bb7 the pawn on d5 will be very difficult to protect.} 14. dxc6 Naxc6 {White struggles to finish the development because of the weak b2-pawn. The c1 Bishop can't really leave its position.} 15. Bb3 {Not allowing Black to play d5.} Na5 {Unfortunately, White is not ready to keep the Bishop on the a2-g8 diagonal and it means that we'll be able to play d5 anytime we please.} 16. Ba4 Bb7 {There's no reason to hurry with d5, we can do it anytime. The e4-pawn is now hanging.} 17. Ng3 Nc4 {It is now the b2-pawn turn to be hanging. Black's position is superior thanks to the better-placed pieces. 18...d5 is imminent. #2}) 11... Nxb3 12. Qxb3 (12. axb3 {runs into} f5 {and White's central pawns start running into trouble.}) 12... c5 {Getting ready to challenge White's pieces by means of c4 or b4.} 13. Bc3 {Going for the Bishop trade immediately.} (13. dxc6 {Giving up on the space advantage but trying to make use of either the weakness of the c-pawn if Black captures on c6 with the pawn or the superior pawn structure (2 islands vs 3 islands) if Black captures with the Knight.} Nxc6 $1 {The Knight didn't have many prospects on e7. From c6 it has a lot of options.} 14. Bc3 {Continuing with the idea to trade the dark squared Bishops.} Bh6 {Surprise! We avoid the trade, as White's Bishop is occupying the square where White's b1-Knight was supposed to land. Our d7-pawn would be indeed weak if White would have a way to attack it, but it doesn't, as in order to double on the d-file with the Rooks, White has to develop the Knight to d2 and it will close up the d-file giving us extra time.} 15. Nbd2 d6 {Our Bishop now wants to come e6, one Rook to e8, the other to c8, and then play d5 at the right moment. There's absolutely nothing for Black to worry about. #3}) 13... d6 {Stopping White from playing d6 and opening-up the c8 Bishop.} 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Qc3+ {White wants to get control over the dark squares around our King.} Kg8 16. Qf6 {There is no reason for us to worry about the safety of our King, with some precise moves, we will be able to get rid of the unpleasant White's Queen on f6.} Bg4 {Freeing the c8 square for our Knight and planning to offer a Queen trade by it.} 17. Nbd2 Nc8 {Trading Queens would be good for us, as it would leave the issues about our King's safety in the past.} 18. Qf4 {White tries to avoid it.} Bxf3 19. Nxf3 Nb6 {The ideal position for our Knight. It not only wants to jump to a4 or c4 (attacking the b2 pawn), but also supports the advance of our pawns on the Queenside, which is actually our main plan- to create a passed pawn.} 20. h4 {White wants to attack on the Kingside, though it is rather unclear with which pieces, as the material left on the board might not be enough.} Qe7 {Our main idea is as said before- create a passed pawn on the Queenside, but if we are worried about White's attack on the Kingside (say g3, Kg2, Rh1, h5) we can always play Rae8, Nd7-e5 and f5 simplifying things. The position is balanced. #4}) (10. a4 {Going for an attack on the Queenside. The b5-pawn is now hanging.} d5 $1 {Ignoring the threat on the b5-pawn and going for counterplay in the centre instead!} 11. exd5 (11. axb5 {will be met by} dxe4) 11... Na5 {Tempting White to win the b5-pawn at the price of giving up the Bishop pair.} 12. axb5 Nxb3 13. Qxb3 {White has two extra pawns for the moment, but they're not likely to survive since the d-pawns are doubled and are easy to be targeted.} Bb7 {Developing and increasing the pressure against the d5-pawn.} 14. Nc3 {Trying to catch up with the development.} (14. bxa6 {Trying to change material and hope that White will be able to convert the material advantage in an endgame. Is it the case though?} Bxa6 {The Rook got to move.} 15. Re1 Qxd5 {There's no time for White to capture the e7-Knight as the Queen's hanging.} 16. Qxd5 Nxd5 {Black has full compensation for the sacrificed pawn thanks to the pair of Bishops and the advantage in development. The b2- and d4-pawn are targets Black will attack. #5}) 14... axb5 15. Bg5 {Protecting the a1 Rook and pinning our Knight with the hope that Black won't have time to take back the d5 pawn.} Bxd5 {However, we can still take the pawn as the tactics work in our favour.} 16. Nxd5 (16. Bxe7 {is met by} Bxb3 {White can't avoid taking on d5 as 16...Bxf3 is an unpleasant threat.}) 16... Qxd5 {Once again, we rely on small tactics. White's Queen is hanging so there's no time for taking our Knight on e7.} 17. Qxd5 Nxd5 {With better chances for Black thanks to the superior pawn structure (2 islands of pawns vs 3 islands) and the strong Bishop on g7 which does a great job in attacking the isolated pawn. #6}) (10. Bg5 {Do you remember the concept of playing against a Bishop placed at the top of a diagonal? We will see it in the lines with 8.Bc2. A similar approach will be applied here as well, starting a hunt on the g5 Bishop.} h6 {The first question: where to go with the Bishop?} 11. Bh4 {Trying to keep the pin alive.} (11. Be3 {White hopes that the Bishop will be able to protect the pawn from here, but also attack the h6 one after an eventual Qc1 or Qd2.} Na5 {We are already familiar with this manoeuver meant to drive White's Bishop away from the a2-g8 diagonal, thus allowing us to attack the centre.} 12. Bc2 Nc4 {With better prospects for Black. It now becomes clear that e3 isn't an ideal place for the White's dark squared Bishop and it might have preferred to stay on its initial c1 square, where it has to go now if they want to keep the b2-pawn alive. It will be then met by 13...c5, taking advantage of the great control we have over the long dark diagonal. #7}) 11... d6 {Opening up the c8-h3 diagonal for our Bishop, which plans on going to g4, from where it will disturb the main defender of the pawn- the Knight on f3. White can't allow it.} 12. h3 g5 {The hunt on the Bishop continues!} 13. Bxg5 {An interesting and somewhat forced try. White takes advantage of the fact that our Knight is on e7 and not on f6, from where it protected the h7 square.} (13. Bg3 $2 {Doesn't work, as White's pawn gets in big trouble.} g4 $1 14. hxg4 Bxg4 {With a hopeless position for White, as there's no way to both save the pawn and get rid of the unpleasant pin on the h5-d1 diagonal. 15...Nxd4 is to follow. #8}) 13... Nxd4 {A nice resource, distracting the f3 Knight from controlling the g5-square.} ({Accepting the piece sacrifice is dangerous, as after} 13... hxg5 14. Nxg5 {15.Qh5, followed by a mate on h7, is a difficult threat to deal with.}) 14. Bxe7 (14. Nxd4 hxg5 {Now there's no one to disturb our g5-pawn.} 15. Nc3 {Trying to finish the development.} c5 {With a significant advantage for Black thanks to the pair of Bishops and the upcoming pawn storm on the Queenside. #9}) 14... Nxf3+ {But there's an intermediate check which saves the day!} ({White wants to win a piece after} 14... Qxe7 15. Nxd4) 15. Qxf3 Qxe7 {Once again we have the Bishop pair, but our light squares are quite weak...} 16. Nc3 {White tries to make use of their advantage on the light squares, planning to land the Knight on the nice d5 square.} c6 {With a balanced position. Our plan is to use our pawn majority on the Queenside and take more space there by playing a5-a4 and then b4, making White's light pieces reposition to worse squares. #10}) 10... Na5 {We stay true to our ideas, trying to either win the pair of Bishops or drive White's light-squared Bishop away from controlling the d5-square.} 11. Bc2 d6 {Getting ready to pin White's f3 Knight by bringing the Bishop to g4.} 12. h3 {A useful waiting move which stops our light squared Bishop from developing to g4.} (12. Bg5 {By now, we know that placing a Bishop 'on top' of a diagonal isn't always an inspired idea.} h6 {And so the hunt on the g5-Bishop begins!} 13. Bh4 g5 {The 'hunt' continues!} 14. Bg3 Nc4 {Now that White's Bishop is on g3, too far away from protecting the b2-pawn, we start disturbing it.} 15. b3 {White argues that our Knight doesn't have a good place to retreat to.} Na3 {It does look awkward on the side of the board, but it is actually very comfortable there.} 16. Bd3 b4 {One by one, we force White's pieces away from their optimal squares.} 17. Ne2 f5 {With better prospects for Black. 18...f4 is a threat now as it will win the Bishop on g3. #11} 18. Z0 (18. exf5 {will be met by} Bxf5 {leaving White's long dark diagonal exposed and the d5-square quite weak too; it will be a great place for our e7 Knight.})) (12. d5 {White tries to cut the board into 2 parts, leaving our Knight 'stranded' on a5 and the c7 pawn as a potential weakness if White succeeds to control the c-file with their heavy pieces.} b4 {Not allowing White to keep their pieces on the optimal squares.} 13. Na4 Bd7 {The Bishop aims for the b5 square.} 14. Rb1 {Preparing to play b3 and then either trade the dark-squared Bishops by playing Bb2, or reroute the a4 Knight via b2 to a better placement on c4 or d3.} Bb5 15. Re1 Nc4 {Taking the chance to reroute our otherwise stranded a5 Knight.} 16. b3 Na3 {Once again- this a Knight manoeuver to remember as it comes up quite often in this system. Black is better, as there's no way for White to avoid losing the pair of Bishops. Our plan will then be to make use of our control over the dark squares and activate our e7 Knight by playing c6. #12}) 12... c5 {We are ready now to attack White's central pawns and make them decide whether to close up the centre with 13.d5, simplify the position by taking on c5 or maintain the pressure in the centre. It is always good when we make our opponents face choices, as what might seem a natural decision for us, might be challenging for others.} 13. Bg5 {Once again: the Bishop comes to the top of the diagonal. It is a very tempting move and the most played one in the position, but doesn't really pose any problems for us. Black continues with the usual reply: we start the hunt on the Bishop.} (13. dxc5 {The simplifications in the centre usually work better for Black. Here, it is no exception.} dxc5 14. Qxd8 (14. Bg5 {Bishop on the top.} Qxd1 15. Raxd1 Nec6 {Our Knight is very comfortable on c6, as it plans to jump to d4. Black is better thanks to the better light pieces and the superiority on the Queenside. #13}) 14... Rxd8 {Trading Queens did not make White's life easier. The problems on the long dark diagonal persist. The b2-pawn will always be a target and we can increase the pressure on it by bringing our Knight to c4. The light-squared Bishop will come to e6, looking towards the a1-pawn. The 2nd Knight can come to c6, eyeing the d4 and b4 squares.} 15. Be3 {White's idea is simple- continue the development while creating threats- the c5 pawn is now attacked.} (15. Bg5 Re8 {We did spend a tempo on protecting our e7-Knight, but we can afford it.} 16. Rad1 {White wants to take on e7 and then infiltrate with the Rook on our backrank.} h6 17. Bxe7 Bxc3 {An important intermediate move! Once we take on e7, White will deliver a check on d8 and we don't want them to follow up with bringing their c3 Knight to d5.} 18. bxc3 (18. Bxc5 {will be met by} Bxb2) 18... Rxe7 19. Rd8+ Kg7 {White's Rook is very nice on d8, but it can't keep its' position, as both 20...Nb7 and 20...Bb7 are coming.} 20. Rfd1 Nb7 {The Rook has now to leave the 8th rank and we'll then be able to develop our Bishop to e6, from where it will attack the a2-pawn. Black is better thanks to the superior pawn structure (2 pawn islands vs 3) and the upcoming pawn storm on the Queenside. #14}) 15... Be6 {A positional pawn sacrifice. We want to get great piece activity for it and there's no way White can avoid it.} 16. Bxc5 Nec6 {Bringing the last light piece to the fight on the Queenside.} 17. Rab1 {Prophylaxis. White protects the b2-pawn, knowing that an attack on it is coming.} (17. Bb6 {would be met by} Rdc8 {creating pressure on the c-file.}) 17... Bc4 18. Rfd1 b4 {Getting back the sacrificed pawn. Once the Knight moves away from c3, the a2-pawn is going to fall. White's problems on the Queenside will not disappear though, as b2 is a weakness forever. #15}) (13. Bf4 {A neutral move, following the general principles. White wants to finish their development.} cxd4 14. Nxd4 Bb7 {We do know those principles as well: development complete! The a8 Rook wants to come now to the open c-file, while the b7 Bishop applies pressure on the e4-pawn.} 15. Re1 Rc8 {With a better position for Black, as there's no way for White to stop our Knight from coming to c4, from where it will attack the b2-pawn and force White to weaken the long dark diagonal by playing b3. #16}) (13. d5 {Trying to close-up the centre and argue that our Knight on a5 is out of play.} Nc4 {But we already know how to react to this- by rerouting our Knight to happier places via c4.} 14. Bd3 {Another try to disturb our Knight and spoil our pawn structure in case we don't avoid 15.Bxc4 bxc4.} (14. Rb1 {Protecting the b2 pawn so that the Bishop could move from c1.} f5 {Attacking White's central pawns!} 15. exf5 Nxf5 {Look at that square! Wouldn't our Knight feel great there?} 16. Ne4 {White might want to play b3 with a tempi, then follow it up with Bb2, to trade the dark squared Bishops and then try to make use of the weak dark squares around our King.} Ne5 {The Knight has done its job on c4 - time to fight now for the control over the e5-square! Trading the f3 Knight is a great idea as it eliminates the main defender of e5.} 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 {Our plan will now be to create threats on the Kingside. We can do so by placing our Knight on d4, the Bishop on b7 (from where it will attack the d5 pawn) and the Queen via d7 to g7. Black is better. #17}) 14... Ne5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 {If allowed, we would love to drive White's Knight away from the centre by playing 16...b4 and then attack the central pawns by playing f5.} 16. Bh6 {White develop their last piece with tempo!} b4 $1 {A typical exchange sacrifice. This is the case where our dark squared Bishop is more valuable than the f8 Rook.} 17. Bxf8 Qxf8 18. Na4 {The only square from which White can protect the b2-pawn. The threat is to jump to b6 with a fork.} Rb8 {Chess is simple as long as we can figure out what our opponent wants - the b6 square is covered.} 19. f4 Bd4+ 20. Kh1 Bd7 {Black has full compensation for the sacrificed exchange. The Bishop is a fantastically strong piece, especially since White's dark squares are quite weak (look at the g3) ones!  That means that White's King is not exactly safe and we might want to make it more uncomfortable by preparing f5. It can be achieved by trading the light-squared Bishops by means of Bb5. Also, look at that Knight on a4: is it getting back into play? Not really. #18}) (13. b3 {Covers the c4-square but weakens the long dark diagonal.} Nac6 {Making use of the newly weakened dark squares, now attacked.} 14. Be3 {No better way to protect the pawn.} f5 {White's central pawns are now compromised. 15...f4 is a serious threat, while taking on f5 allows an additional piece, our Knight from e7, to pressure the pawn. Black is better. #19}) 13... h6 14. Bh4 {The only way to maintain the pin alive.} Nac6 {Forcing White to make a decision about the central pawn structure as the pawn is hanging.} 15. d5 {Closing-up the centre but giving away some dark squares (d4, e5).} (15. dxc5 {Eliminating the pressure in the centre, hoping to be able then to play e5 and prepare a take-over of the dark squares.} dxc5 {Trading Queens would be good for us, as then White's counterplay on the Kingside will be less dangerous.} 16. Nd5 {Another way to avoid the Queens trade.} (16. Qxd8 $2 Rxd8 {It is now clear that Black's play on the Queenside is more effective than White's on the Kingside. We have great control over the long dark diagonal and the dark squares (d4, b4). We can start gaining more space by means of c4, b4.} 17. e5 {Making use of the pin over the h4-d8 diagonal, White tries to get control over the f6 square by means of 18.Ne4, closing up the long dark diagonal at the same time.} g5 {Getting rid of the pin.} 18. Bg3 Bf5 {Black has a decisive advantage thanks to the better placed pieces and the upcoming pawn storm on the Queenside. White doesn't really have any counterplay. #20}) (16. Qe2 {Avoiding the Queens trade and planning on taking the control over the d-file. The Queen from e2 also supports ideas with e5 and Ne4, aimed to disturb our King.} Be6 {The most natural developing move in the position. It also comes with a threat, 17...Bc4 winning an exchange.} 17. Rad1 Nd4 {A great move as it not only forks 3 White pieces and covers our Queen, but also reinforces the threat of 18...Bc4.} 18. Nxd4 cxd4 {Black's position is preferable as we have a nice passed pawn on and we do still threaten on 19...Bc4. #21}) 16... g5 {Once again, we get rid of the pin over the d8-h4 diagonal.} 17. Bg3 {White might want to use their great control over the c7-square by jumping with one of the light pieces there.} Ra7 {How easy it would be to play chess if only we could figure out each time what's our opponent's idea, right? Black covers the c7-square and gets ready to bring the Rook to d7, then the c8 Bishop to b7, pressing the d5 Knight which will eventually have to give up its active position. #22}) (15. Qd2 {White connects the Rooks, implying there's not enough time for us to win the pawn.} g5 {First, we need to get rid of the pin.} 16. Bg3 f5 (16... cxd4 {would be met by} 17. Ne2 {with White getting back the pawn.}) ({Capturing with the Knight first makes no difference as after} 16... Nxd4 17. Nxd4 cxd4 18. Ne2 {the outcome is the same. Instead, we attack the other pawn of White's centre, also keeping in mind the idea of closing up White's dark squared Bishop by playing f4.}) 17. exf5 Nxf5 {The position is balanced. The pawn is now definitely hanging. The Bishop is on g3 is attacked. White's advantage on the light squares is not easy to be used, while our great control over the dark squares might prove vital. #23}) (15. a4 {Arguing that Black over-expanded on the Queenside; the b5-pawn is now hanging.} Nxd4 {A nice, healthy central pawn: why not take it?} 16. axb5 {White makes use of their pin on the a-file.} Bb7 {With a balanced position. We will combine threats over the 2 long diagonals, the dark and the light one, pressuring the b2-pawn and the e4-pawn. We can always get rid of the pin over the h4-d8 diagonal by either playing Re8, Qb6 or by simply pushing g5. #24}) 15... Nd4 {The Knights feel the best in the centre; it is the ideal square for it.} 16. Nxd4 Bxd4 {The Bishop doesn't mind being here. Unlike the previous cases which we saw with White's Bishop at the top of a diagonal (on g5), White can't attack our Bishop effectively as the b2-pawn is hanging.} 17. Qd2 {Aiming for the h6-pawn.} g5 {Protecting our h6-pawn and making White's Bishop retreat.} 18. Bg3 b4 {Trying to get to the b2-pawn.} 19. Ne2 {A pawn sacrifice.} (19. Nd1 {A quite passive move, but one which protects the b2 pawn.} a5 {As we have a pawn majority on the Queenside, we want to create a passed pawn there. a4-a3 is a great way of doing so, we also get the additional idea of developing our Bishop to a6 if needed.} 20. Ne3 {White has good control over the light squares.} Ng6 {While Black has very good control over the dark ones. We want to play 21...Nf4 if allowed, making sure White won't be able to open up our King and then continue with our ideas on the Queenside, pushing the a-pawn all the way to a3. #25} (20... Bxb2 {would have been dangerous after} 21. e5 {where White could create unpleasant threats towards our King using the light squares.})) 19... Bxb2 20. Rae1 {If allowed to make 2 moves in a row, f4 and e5, opening up the light squared Bishop from c2 - White would be winning. Fortunately, the rules of chess don't allow that, giving us just enough time to prepare for it.} Ng6 {We've got a pawn up and White doesn't have enough compensation for it. #26} 21. Z0 (21. f4 {will be met by} gxf4 {where, thanks to our great control over the dark squares, after} 22. Nxf4 Qg5 {our King is safe. Meanwhile, being material up we wouldn't mind any trades.}) *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 4.c3 a6 5.Ba4 Mainline"]
[Black "8.Bc2 with 9.d5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C70"]
[PlyCount "37"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. c3 {The idea of this setup is to prepare, force Black to take on, and then recapture with the c3-pawn in order to get some nice control in the centre. The central pawn structure advantage will grant White more space for their light pieces to maneuver around, as well as prospectives of an attack on the Kingside. Black's counterplay will be linked with combining pawns advance on the Queenside (in order to secure important squares for their light pieces) with attacking White's central pawns (e4 and d4).   After years of playing the Ruy Lopez with both colors, I find that it's easier to go wrong while playing with the White pieces, as the 'visual' advantage of the space tends to make one over-optimistic about their chances. It often leads to getting over-ambitious and pushing too hard which is of course convenient for Black. Therefore, arm yourself with patience and you'll be ready to learn the most important ideas Black has in this structure!} a6 {We want White to decide on which diagonal should their Bishop land.} 5. Ba4 {Avoiding all the 5...f5 drama. It doesn't work now as after 6.d4 fxe4 7.Nxe5 we no longer have the 7...d5 move with a tempo (compared to when White had the Bishop on c4).} Bg7 {We go for the most natural developing move.} 6. d4 {Forcing Black to take on as there's no other good way of continuing our development. 6...Nge7 would be met by 7.d5, 6...Nf6 drops the e5-pawn, while 6...d6 allows 7.Bxc6, ruining our pawn structure.} exd4 7. cxd4 b5 {Making sure to be able to play d6 or d5 without worrying about White taking on c6. White now has two options, both of them viable and played extensively.} 8. Bc2 {White argues that they don't need to lose a tempo on playing 8.Bb3 , as after an eventual Na5, the Bishop will end up on c2 anyway. However, it allows Black an additional idea!} d6 {The classical approach, one which leads to more complex battles. I would recommend choosing it against opponents you are confident you could outplay. Otherwise 8...d5 is a simpler way to equalize.} 9. d5 $5 {The most aggressive and ambitious move, making us choose from the very beginning on which flank we want our Knight.} Nb4 $5 {Choosing the most forced line; if allowed, we'd love to trade our somewhat clumsy Knight for White's light squared Bishop.} 10. Bb3 {The most ambitious try, arguing that our Knight on b4 is misplaced.} (10. O-O {Isn't in the spirit of the position, as it allows Black a very simple and natural plan.} Nxc2 11. Qxc2 Nf6 {Just calmly finishing the development. Our Knight is best placed on f6, as now that White's light squared Bishop is gone, we can attack the e4-pawn more efficiently.} 12. Bg5 {A logical way to continue the development for White as well.} O-O 13. Nbd2 {Keeping the c-file opened for the heavy pieces, in order to attack Black's only weakness, the c7-pawn.} Bd7 {The best square for our Bishop, from here controls both the c8-h3 diagonal, but also supports the c6 idea.} (13... Bb7 {would be suboptimal, as after} 14. Nb3 {15.Na5, the Bishop will not feel great and we won't have time to get rid of our c7 weak pawn.}) 14. Rac1 {Attacking the c7-pawn.} (14. Nb3 {with the idea 15.Na5 (to stop us from playing c6) is premature, as after} h6 {followed by 15...Re8 we can put pressure on the e4-pawn (now that the Knight is no longer protecting it from d2).} 15. Bxf6 {isn't good in view of} Qxf6 {with pressure on the b2-pawn.}) 14... Rc8 {Now 15...c6 is unstoppable, meaning Black gets rid of the only weakness in our position and is ready to play for a potential advantage thanks to the pair of Bishops and the pressure on the e4- and b2-pawns. #1}) 10... a5 {Freeing the a6-square for the Knight but also planning on hunting White's Bishop with a4.} 11. a3 {Making the Knight go away from protecting the c6-square and panning on getting the control over it by bringing the f3 Knight to d4.} (11. a4 {Trying to take advantage of our 'weak' b5-pawn.} Nf6 {Developing with a tempo!} 12. O-O (12. axb5 {would be met by} Nxe4 {trading a marginal pawn for a central one is definitely a good deal for us!}) 12... O-O (12... Nxe4 {is dangerous because of} 13. Re1 {with an unpleasant pin. However, after castling, we already want to take the e4-pawn.}) 13. Nc3 {Protecting e4 and threatening to finally take our b5-pawn.} bxa4 14. Bc4 {The only way to avoid trouble on the f1-a6 diagonal.} (14. Bxa4 $6 {Isn't great because it gives up the control over the a6-f1 diagonal.} Ba6 {With a tempo!} 15. Re1 Nd3 {With a big advantage for Black. #2} 16. Z0 ({White can not really save the exchange, as after} 16. Re3 Nxc1 17. Rxc1 Bh6 {the pin over the h6-c1 diagonal proves fatal for White.})) 14... Re8 {But we find another target, the e4-pawn!} 15. Re1 Bg4 {A really unpleasant pin.} 16. Bb5 {Trying to make us give up on the pressure over the e4-pawn.} ({the biggest problem for White is that} 16. h3 {doesn't work, as after} Bxf3 {White is forced to take back with the pawn, as after} 17. Qxf3 Nc2 {loses an exchange. At the same time, we want to play Nd7-Ne5, making even better use of the pin. f5 ideas are also not to be ignored.}) 16... Nd7 {We continue with our plan.} 17. Rxa4 Rf8 {The Rook has done its job on the e-file and goes on a new quest, preparing f5. 18...Ne5 is also an unpleasant threat. The Rook on a4 is totally misplaced and can be easily targeted by our d7 Knight; all reasons for Black to claim a comfortable advantage. #3}) (11. Nc3 {A natural developing move, threatening the b5-pawn in the same time.} a4 {Needless to be said, 12.Bc2 would be met with great joy after 12...Nxc2, getting the Bishop pair.} 12. Qe2 {A clever piece of tactics! 13.Qxb5+ would be a double attack now.} axb3 {Going for a pawn sacrifice in order to get the Bishop pair.} 13. Qxb5+ Qd7 {We need the Bishop on the a6-f1 diagonal.} 14. Qxb4 Ba6 {Not allowing White to castle short any longer.} 15. Qxb3 {The better looking but not the best option.} (15. axb3 {Conceding to double the pawns in order to get the control over the a-file.} Ne7 {A simple way to continue the development.} (15... Nf6 {would be a big mistake, as after} 16. e5 {all of our pieces would start being highly unstable.}) 16. Ra5 {Preparing to double on the a-file.} O-O 17. Qa4 {White would want to trade the Queens as their King will no longer have to worry about its safety in an endgame.} Qg4 {Avoiding the Queens trade and going for counterplay!} 18. Rg1 (18. Rxa6 {doesn't work, as after} Rxa6 19. Qxa6 Qxg2 {we attack both the Rook on h1 and the f3-Knight.}) 18... Bb7 {Trying to get the a-file under our control. 19...Rxa5 followed by 20...Ra8 and 21...Ra1 is a threat.} 19. h3 Rxa5 20. hxg4 ({White doesn't have time for} 20. Qxa5 {as after} Bxc3+ {the e4-pawn will drop.}) 20... Rxa4 21. bxa4 {White manages to get to an endgame with 2 pawns up.} f5 $44 {However, we have decent compensation thanks to our Bishop pair. With our last move, we aim to open as many files and diagonals as possible; piece activity is what grants us compensation. Don't forget that White's e4 and d5 pawns are compromised and we will get a pawn back in the next few moves. The position is balanced. #4}) 15... Nf6 {Our Knight can now safely jump on f6, as we don't have to worry about any instability on the a-file.} 16. Be3 (16. e5 {can be met by} Ng4) 16... O-O {Finishing the development and getting ready to bring the f8 Rook to the Queenside! White has a pawn up, but the King is stuck in the centre and we have great piece activity and coordination!} 17. O-O-O $2 {Trying to solve the safety issue of White's King.} c6 {Opening one more file against the poor White King!} 18. dxc6 Qxc6 $44 {With fantastic compensation for the 2 pawns we sacrificed! The e4-pawn is hanging, White's King is by no means safe with all the files against it being opened. Don't forget about the two Bishops who are simply monsters here! It wouldn't surprise me if White would collapse in a few moves. #5}) 11... Na6 12. Nd4 {A double attack! The b5-pawn is hanging and the c6-square is under siege.} Nc5 {Ignoring all of White's threats and creating some of our own! The e4-pawn is now hanging and White faces an uneasy choice- to take the b5-pawn, to play 13.Nc6, or to bring the king to safety by castling short?} 13. O-O {The best option, finishing the development.} (13. Nc6 {An active move, but one which only helps Black.} Qh4 {Increasing the pressure on the e4-pawn.} 14. O-O {White counts on us being behind in the development, with the King still unsafe in the centre. We don't have time to take the e4-pawn, as we'll get in trouble on the e-file, but we have a better option!} Ne7 {Trying to extract the 'thorn' from our position (the c6 Knight). White can't really avoid it.} 15. g3 {Chasing our Queen away from protecting the e7-Knight, so we'd have to capture back on e7 with the King. Is it though such a big problem?} Qg4 {Our answer is 'No'! Now if White takes on e7 we have the intermediate 16...Qxd1 move, trading Queens and going to an endgame, where our King will feel safe in the centre.} 16. f3 {Avoiding the Queens trade.} Qh5 17. Nxe7 Kxe7 {Our King looks weird in the centre, but there's no way for White to use it. We need just two moves to bring it to safety by playing 18...Re8 and 19...Kf8. We can then follow up with 20...Kg8 and then start to attack White's pawn chain by playing f5.   Thanks to the great light pieces we have (the c5 Knight and the perfect Bishop on g7) Black's position is preferable. #6}) (13. Nxb5 {Going for the material.} Nf6 {We don't hurry taking the e4-pawn, but develop one more piece and set up a nice trap at White's most logical answer!} 14. f3 {What is more natural than protecting the attacked e4-pawn?} Nfxe4 $1 {The point! Now White's King gets very quickly in trouble if accepting the piece sacrifice.} 15. O-O {Bringing the King to safety and planning to win a piece on the next move.} (15. fxe4 $2 {Doesn't work.} Qh4+ {White's position now falls apart.} 16. Kf1 O-O {With a winning position. 17...Ba6 is a threat, pinning the b5 Knight, the e4-pawn is at our mercy and White's King on f1 has definitely safety issues: 17...f5 with the idea to either open up the f-file or push the pawn until f3 is also not to be ignored. Look at White's pieces, almost all are still on their initial squares, while ours control all the board! #7}) 15... Nxb3 {An important intermediate move that saves our e4-Knight, as there's no time to capture it because the a1 Rook is hanging.} 16. Qxb3 Nc5 {Another move with a tempo; what should White's Queen do?} 17. Qe3+ {Leaving Black without the option to castle.} Kf8 {With a superior position for Black thanks to the pair of Bishops. The King is safe on f8 and it has an easy way to get even safer if needed by playing h5, Kg8-h7. Meanwhile, there's also the threat of 18...Ba6, pinning the Knight. #8} (17... Qe7 {doesn't work because of the 18...Nxc7 fork.})) 13... Nxb3 {Taking the Bishop pair.} 14. Nxb3 Ne7 {And our King will very soon be able to castle.} 15. Nd4 {White insists on attacking our b5-pawn, even at the cost of spending quite some tie moving the same piece instead of developing the others.} Bd7 {The optimal square for our light squared Bishop, as it both protects the b5-pawn and keeps control over the c8-h3 diagonal.} 16. Bg5 {A good developing move which also pins our Knight.} h6 {There can be no compromises, why agree to be pinned if we can avoid it?} 17. Be3 (17. Bh4 {Insisting on keeping the pin.} g5 {An easy away out of the pin.} 18. Bg3 O-O {With a superior position thanks to the Bishop pair that will soon control the whole position. Our threat is 19...f5 and it makes no difference if White plays 19.f4, we still go for 19...f5. Remember, when one has the Bishop pair, it is vital to open up as many diagonals for them as possible! #9}) 17... O-O {The development is now finished.} 18. Qd2 {Does White hope we won't notice that the h6-pawn is hanging?} Kh7 {Protecting h6 and planning on starting the attack of White's central pawn chain by playing 19...f5. #10} 19. Z0 (19. Nc3 {can be met by} b4 {with a balanced position.}) *

