1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. c3 {The idea of this setup is to prepare, force Black to take on, and then recapture with the c3-pawn in order to get some nice control in the centre. The central pawn structure advantage will grant White more space for their light pieces to maneuver around, as well as prospectives of an attack on the Kingside. Black's counterplay will be linked with combining pawns advance on the Queenside (in order to secure important squares for their light pieces) with attacking White's central pawns (e4 and d4).   After years of playing the Ruy Lopez with both colors, I find that it's easier to go wrong while playing with the White pieces, as the 'visual' advantage of the space tends to make one over-optimistic about their chances. It often leads to getting over-ambitious and pushing too hard which is of course convenient for Black. Therefore, arm yourself with patience and you'll be ready to learn the most important ideas Black has in this structure!} a6 {We want White to decide on which diagonal should their Bishop land.} 5. Ba4 {Avoiding all the 5...f5 drama. It doesn't work now as after 6.d4 fxe4 7.Nxe5 we no longer have the 7...d5 move with a tempo (compared to when White had the Bishop on c4).} Bg7 {We go for the most natural developing move.} 6. d4 {Forcing Black to take on as there's no other good way of continuing our development. 6...Nge7 would be met by 7.d5, 6...Nf6 drops the e5-pawn, while 6...d6 allows 7.Bxc6, ruining our pawn structure.} exd4 7. cxd4 b5 {Making sure to be able to play d6 or d5 without worrying about White taking on c6. White now has two options, both of them viable and played extensively.} 8. Bc2 {White argues that they don't need to lose a tempo on playing 8.Bb3, as after an eventual Na5, the Bishop will end up on c2 anyway. However, it allows Black an additional idea!} d6 {The classical approach, one which leads to more complex battles. I would recommend choosing it against opponents you are confident you could outplay. Otherwise 8...d5 is a simpler way to equalize.} 9. h3 {A slow, python style approach. White wants to prove that their space advantage (thanks to the central d4 and e4 pawns) will be decisive and Black will struggle to find good places for their pieces.} Nf6 {The main idea for Black in this setup is to attack White's central pawns and make one of them move forward. It will either make the pawn that moves weak and a target for us to attack, or it will weaken important central squares.} 10. O-O O-O 11. Nc3 {Both sides do their best to finish the development.} Bb7 {Staying true to our plan of building-up pressure against White's central pawns.} 12. Re1 {Prophylactical move, over-protecting the e4-pawn.} Re8 {Another one bites... the e4-pawn! With the development complete for both sides, White's task is now to come up with a plan. Let's examine the most played and most natural tries.} 13. a3 {Prophylaxis against Black's idea to challenge the c3-Knight by means of playing b4.} (13. Bg5 {Pinning the f6-Knight might seem tempting, but there's an interesting thing about Bishops: they are not always best placed on the top of the controlled diagonal (c1-h6 in our case) as the closer they get to our troops, they become targets.} h6 {You see, the g5-Bishop is definitely not feeling comfortable on g5 anymore.} 14. Bh4 {Keeping the pin alive.} (14. Bf4 {Giving up on the pin over the h4-d8 diagonal and switching to the idea of playing e5.} Na5 {A move which we count on a lot in this setup. It opens up the diagonal for our light square Bishop and gives us control over the d5-square if White will challenge our f6 Knight with 15.e5. 14...Nb4 is another move to rely on, but we prefer it when White's Knight is still on b1, so that White's c2-Bishop doesn't have the option to retreat to b1.} 15. e5 {Attacking our Knight but giving up the control over the d5-square.} Nd5 {Proving once again my point about the location of the Bishops on top of a diagonal; the f4 Bishop is again targeted now.} 16. Nxd5 Bxd5 {It is now the turn for our light-squared Bishop to be the 'star' - look at its great control over the long light diagonal!} 17. Qd3 {Connecting the Rooks.} Nc6 {A move with many ideas. The first one is to continue with 18...Bxf3, where after 19.Qxf3, the d4-pawn drops. On the other hand, 18...Nb4 is also an unpleasant threat. Black's position is preferable thanks to the good control over the light squares. The d4-e5 pawn duo is too unstable. #1}) 14... Na5 {14...g5 might have been tempting, but not in this exact position where we can't follow up with f5 ideas, as our light-squared Bishop is not on the c8-h3 diagonal anymore and the Rook isn't on f8. That means that g5 would only weaken the light squares in this case and there's absolutely no reason for us to do White's job easier.   Instead, we go for our reliable Knight move, freeing once again the d5 square for our Knight.} 15. b3 {Taking control of the c4-square, but weakening the long dark diagonal.} (15. e5 {will be met by} dxe5 {and White is not winning the f6 Knight after} 16. dxe5 {as we have the intermediate} Qxd1 {move.}) 15... g5 {Now it works, as White can't just retreat with the Bishop to g3, as it loses the e4-pawn after 16...b4.} 16. Nxg5 {The only worthy try is to muddy the waters.} hxg5 17. Bxg5 Nc6 {The position is balanced; White has compensation for the sacrificed piece, but it is easier to play with Black, as our plan is quite simple. For now, we control the e5-square so that we don't get in trouble because of the pinned f6 Knight. The logical next step is to get rid of the pin by playing 18...Ne7 or if not worried about the pin, 18...Nb4, followed up by 19...c5, staying true to the plan of making White move the central pawns in order to get squares for our light pieces. #2}) (13. e5 $2 {Doesn't work.} dxe5 14. dxe5 Qxd1 {Another move which we count on a lot in this position in order to wither get rid of the pin on the h4-d8 diagonal, or to simply win the e5-pawn, as in this case.} 15. Bxd1 (15. Rxd1 {loses the e5 pawn on the spot}) ({while} 15. Nxd1 {has the same outcome after} Nd5) 15... Nd7 {'One for all and all for one' and the e5-pawn is lost. #3}) (13. d5 {Makes our Knight leave its central position but gives up some important dark squares.} Na5 {Our reliable move once again!} 14. Nd4 {The Knight on d4 is nicely placed and the c6-square might potentially become weak if not Black's next move.} c6 {You see? Once again, when one of the pawns (the d-one in this case) moves forward it immediately becomes a target.} 15. dxc6 Nxc6 {Now White's only active piece has to either give up its position or agree to be traded. The e4-pawn will be our next target.} 16. Nxc6 Bxc6 {Threatening to play 17...b4 and challenge one of the defenders of the 'yummy' e4-pawn.} 17. Bf4 {White decides to defend by creating a threat of their own, attacking the d6-pawn.} b4 18. Nd5 {The only way to avoid losing the e4-pawn.} Bxd5 19. exd5 Rxe1+ 20. Qxe1 Nh5 {After a series of trades, we don't take the d5-pawn, as it allows White enough compensation to hold equality. The time has come for our g7 Bishop to show its teeth - the b2-pawn is now under attack and White won't be able to save the problem of the long dark diagonal, which leaves Black with a vetter position. We can then follow up with 21...Rc8 or 21...Qh4. #4}) 13... Na5 {Did you guess it? Our most reliable move once again! The interesting thing about these positions is that the one who losses their patience first is usually the one who goes wrong and having a visually more active position as well as running out of useful moves makes White the better candidate for an unforced error.} 14. Bf4 {The move played the most according to my database. We are already familiar with the idea of moving the Bishop to the top of the diagonal, now it's time to use another downside of it leaving the c1-square leaving the b2-pawn unprotected.} (14. d5 {We already know that moving the central pawns forward is usually not a great idea for White.} c6 {Aiming to open up the long light diagonal for our Bishop and then attack the e4-pawn.} 15. dxc6 Bxc6 {Look at our pieces, they all work very well together! The e4-pawn is one target, another problem White will always have is the long dark diagonal. We can simply combine our threats on the e4-pawn with bringing more pieces to the action; for example 16...Rc8. d5 ideas are also to be considered. Despite the fact that we trade White's e4 weakness, we also trade the f6 Knight for the c3 one, opening up the long dark diagonal for our Bishop and making a target out of the b2-pawn. #5}) (14. b3 {Also not great as it weakens the long dark diagonal.} c5 {Exploiting the weakness on the a1-h8 diagonal immediately.} 15. d5 b4 {White now struggles to save all their 'warriors'.} 16. axb4 cxb4 {The Knight has to move.} 17. Na4 Nxd5 {Winning a pawn as the d5 Knight is untouchable, the a1 Rook is hanging. #6}) (14. Bd3 $5 {A true show of patience- the best move in the position to my taste, just taking some control over the c4-square and not committing to any change of the pawn structure.} c5 {Our last resort in order to force a movement from White's central pawns. However, being the last resort, it doesn't mean it's not good enough.} 15. d5 {White closes up the centre arguing that our Knight on a5 is now misplaced and doesn't have a good way of getting back into the game.} Nd7 {Opening up the path for the dark squared Bishop and planning on getting even better control over the dark squares by means of playing c4 and Nc5 eventually.} 16. Bf4 Qe7 {The position is balanced. Our plan is still to attack White's pawn chain by preparing f5, but not before improving the position of our pieces by means of 17...Qf8, 18...c4, 19...Nc5. The Bishop from b7 can also support the f5 push if placed on c8. The a5 Knight will get the b3 square after its 'brother' occupies the c5 position. #7}) 14... Nc4 15. Qc1 {Protecting b2 and hoping to trade the dark squared Bishops by means of 16.Bh6.} c5 {As all of our pieces are in their best positions, the time has come for breaking-up White's pawn structure in the centre.} 16. d5 (16. b3 {Challenging our c4-Knight.} cxd4 {A nice intermediate move!} 17. Nxd4 Nh5 {Look at the long dark diagonal, it will take a miracle for White not to get in big trouble because of it.} 18. Bg5 Qa5 {Two 'horses' under attack!} 19. Nce2 {Trying to keep alive.} Ne5 {Moving away from trouble and planning to continue with 20...Rac8, creating one more pin over the c-file. Black's position is preferable. #8}) 16... Nd7 {Dark squares - we can be proudly called their masters now!} 17. Bd3 {Planning on winning the d6-pawn after first taking down its defense, the c4-Knight.} Nce5 {Our solution couldn't have been simpler.} 18. Nxe5 Nxe5 {Giving up the Bishop pair is surely not an option for White.} 19. Bf1 Bc8 {A move which shows good position understanding. There was nothing left to be done for our Bishop on b7, as the a8-h1 diagonal was shut for good. We now find a better position for it, on a friendlier diagonal.} 20. Qd2 {Connecting the Rooks.} Bd7 {The Bishop arrived at its destination!} 21. Bg5 f6 {With the same idea of attacking White's central pawn chain by means of f5. It needs some preparation, the Queen should be repositioned to either f8 or c7-b6. Another interesting plan is to get a grip over the dark squares by means of g5 and then follow up with a pawn expansion on the Kingside (h5-h4-g4) with a potential attack on White's King. #9} *

