1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. c3 {The idea of this setup is to prepare, force Black to take on, and then recapture with the c3-pawn in order to get some nice control in the centre. The central pawn structure advantage will grant White more space for their light pieces to maneuver around, as well as prospectives of an attack on the Kingside. Black's counterplay will be linked with combining pawns advance on the Queenside (in order to secure important squares for their light pieces) with attacking White's central pawns (e4 and d4).   After years of playing the Ruy Lopez with both colors, I find that it's easier to go wrong while playing with the White pieces, as the 'visual' advantage of the space tends to make one over-optimistic about their chances. It often leads to getting over-ambitious and pushing too hard which is of course convenient for Black. Therefore, arm yourself with patience and you'll be ready to learn the most important ideas Black has in this structure!} a6 {We want White to decide on which diagonal should their Bishop land.} 5. Ba4 {Avoiding all the 5...f5 drama. It doesn't work now as after 6.d4 fxe4 7.Nxe5 we no longer have the 7...d5 move with a tempo (compared to when White had the Bishop on c4).} Bg7 {We go for the most natural developing move.} 6. d4 {Forcing Black to take on as there's no other good way of continuing our development. 6...Nge7 would be met by 7.d5, 6...Nf6 drops the e5-pawn, while 6...d6 allows 7.Bxc6, ruining our pawn structure.} exd4 7. cxd4 b5 {Making sure to be able to play d6 or d5 without worrying about White taking on c6. White now has two options, both of them viable and played extensively.} 8. Bc2 {White argues that they don't need to lose a tempo on playing 8.Bb3, as after an eventual Na5, the Bishop will end up on c2 anyway. However, it allows Black an additional idea!} d5 $5 {The move we wouldn't have if the Bishop was on b3. We want to force White into an isolated pawn structure. In the long term, Black can count on an advantage thanks to it. However, White can argue that their piece activity will be enough to make it difficult for us to exploit the weakness of the isolated d-pawn.} 9. exd5 (9. Bg5 {White develops their Bishop with a tempo and forces our g-Knight to e7.} Nge7 10. Nc3 {Attackig the d5-pawn.} h6 {The g5-Bishop is 'on top of a diagonal' - time to hunt it!} 11. Bxe7 (11. Bh4 $6 {Doesn't work well.} dxe4 {Aiming for a position where White has an isolated pawn on d4.} 12. Bxe4 g5 {Getting rid of the pin over the h4-d8 diagonal.} 13. Bg3 Bf5 {With a very comfortable position for Black. We plan to finish our development by castling short, after which we'll start to attack White's isolated d4-pawn. #1}) 11... Nxe7 {Threatening to take on e4, which will lead to a very convenient position for us thanks to White's isolated d4-pawn.} 12. e5 {Avoids dxe4 and tries to close up our dark squared Bishop.} Bg4 {The f3-Knight is a very important piece, as it protects the d4 and e5-pawns, keeping White's centre stable. We want to trade our Bishop for the Knight in order to destabilize White's central pawn construction.} 13. O-O Rc8 {Preparing to play c5 after first taking on f3.} 14. h3 (14. b4 {(trying to stop 14...c5) will be met by} Nc6 {with a double attack on b4 and d4.}) 14... Bxf3 15. Qxf3 c5 {With a balanced position, we've managed to destabilize White's d4 and e5 pawns. Our strategy is now to build up pressure on them. 16...cxd4 is a serious threat. #2}) (9. O-O Bg4 {The d4-pawn is now under serious attack.} 10. exd5 {White hopes to be able to use the newly opened e-file in order to create threats against our King.} Bxf3 {An important intermediate move, leaving White's d4-pawn unprotected.} 11. Qxf3 Nxd4 {A nice fork on White's Queen and c2-Bishop.} 12. Qe4+ Ne7 {Preparing to castle.} 13. Bg5 {White tries to stop us from castling, as the e7-Knight will be hanging.} h6 14. Bxe7 (14. Bh4 {would be a blunder, as after} g5 15. Bg3 f5 {the g3-Bishop is trapped.}) 14... Qxe7 {Black is better thanks to the fantastic dark squared Bishop and White's weak d5-pawn. After trading the Queens, we will castle long, putting pressure on the d5-pawn immediately. White can't avoid it as if the Queen moves away, to d3 let's say, 15...Ne2+ followed by 16...Bxb2 wins material. #3}) 9... Nce7 {The Knight does a very good job here, both covering the e-file and attacking the d5-pawn.} 10. O-O Nf6 {We want to finish the development as fast as possible!} 11. Nc3 {So does White.} O-O 12. Bg5 {Hoping that the pin over the h4-d8 diagonal will be enough to discourage Black from taking the d5-pawn.} Nexd5 {But hope alone is not enough. The pawn is safe to capture!} 13. Be4 {White gets tempted by pinning us one more time.} (13. Nxd5 {will be met by} Qxd5 {and if} 14. Bb3 {we have} Qd6 {with a balanced position.}) 13... Be6 {There was nothing wrong with 13...Bb7 as well, it is just a matter of taste.} 14. Ne5 Qd6 {White's pieces look nice and active but they're not creating any threats. On the other hand, the d4-pawn will be forever isolated and weak and Black will most certainly try to make use of it. 15...Nxc3 is a big threat, as the Bishop on e4 will then drop. #4} 15. Z0 (15. Bf3 {can be met by} Rac8 {with the threat of 16...c5 highlighting the instability of the e5-Knight. Black's position is preferable.}) *

