1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. c3 {The idea of this setup is to prepare, force Black to take on, and then recapture with the c3-pawn in order to get some nice control in the centre. The central pawn structure advantage will grant White more space for their light pieces to maneuver around, as well as prospectives of an attack on the Kingside. Black's counterplay will be linked with combining pawn advances on the Queenside (in order to secure important squares for their light pieces) with attacking White's central pawns (e4 and d4).  After years of playing the Ruy Lopez with both colors, I find that it's easier to go wrong while playing with the White pieces, as the 'visual' advantage of the space tends to make one over-optimistic about their chances. It often leads to getting over-ambitious and pushing too hard which is of course convenient for Black. Therefore, arm yourself with patience and you'll be ready to learn the most important ideas Black has in this structure!} a6 {We want White to decide on which diagonal should their Bishop land.} 5. Bxc6 $5 {An interesting try which I came across when preparing vs GM Alexandra Kosteniuk. White aims for a structure with a pawn majority in the centre.} dxc6 {The typical reply, to open up the diagonal for our c8 Bishop.} 6. d4 {Trying to seize the control in the centre.} (6. Nxe5 $2 {Doesn't work well.} Qg5 {A double attack on the Knight on e5 and the g2 pawn.} 7. Nf3 Qxg2 {Got the pawn back!} 8. Rg1 Qh3 {With a better position for Black thanks to the pair of Bishops and the potential weakness of White's King who will struggle to find safety. Our plan is to bring our Queen to e6, from where it will pressure the e4-pawn, then continue our development by means of Nf6. #1}) 6... exd4 7. cxd4 {White has got a really nice centre. However, Black can start attacking it immediately.} Bg4 {Pinning the main defender of the d4-pawn - the Knight, and planning on increasing the pressure on White's centre while continuing the development at the same time by means of Bg7.} 8. Qb3 {White gets rid of the pin and attacks our b7-pawn.} Bxf3 9. gxf3 Bg7 {Continuing the development and planning to capture on d4 with the Bishop; it involves a temporary pawn sacrifice on b7.} ({The d4-pawn is untouchable for now, as} 9... Qxd4 {will be met by} 10. Qxb7 {with a double attack on the Rook on a8 and the pawn on c6.}) 10. Nc3 {White continues their development. By choosing this move order, White gets the additional idea of protecting the d4 pawn with the Knight, by means of Ne2.} (10. Qxb7 $6 {Accepting the pawn sacrifice is not the best try, as it leaves White quite behind with their development.} Ne7 {Protecting the c6-pawn and preparing to castle short. The pawn on d4 is still hanging.} 11. Nc3 {White tries to catch up on their development, preparing to bring the Bishop to e3 and then castle long.} O-O {Now that our King is safe, we can start thinking about getting our pawn back by means of Bxd4.} 12. Be3 {White is ready to castle long.} Bxd4 13. O-O-O {Pinning our Bishop on the d-file and forcing us to do something about it.} c5 {The best way to protect our Bishop. The plan is now to start an attack on White's King. We can do it by bringing our Queen to e6 via d7, aiming for the a2-pawn. The semi-opened b-file will come in handy for our Rooks. It is important to remember that in positions with castling on different sides of the board, one should try to attack their opponent's King as quickly as possible. #2} 14. Z0 ({For example, a move like} 14. Bf4 {will be met by} Qd7 {and after} 15. Qxc7 {we avoid the Queen trade by playing} Qe6 {(with the threat of taking on c3 and then on a2. Black will have excellent compensation there for the sacrificed pawn.})) (10. Be3 {Protecting the pawn. Since after all the captures on d4 White still has Qxb7 and we can't answer it with castling short, the d4-pawn is untouchable for now.} Ne7 {Ready to castle short!} 11. Nc3 Bxd4 12. O-O-O {Pinning our Bishop.} ({It is ok to take the pawn now as after} 12. Bxd4 Qxd4 13. Qxb7 {we've got} O-O) 12... c5 {The best way to protect it.} 13. Ne2 {Increasing the pressure against our Bishop on d4.} (13. Qxb7 O-O {With a transpositionto 10.Qxb7. #3}) 13... Nc6 14. Qxb7 {Getting back the sacrificed pawn and attacking one of the defenders of the d4-Bishop, the Knight on c6.} Na5 {Forcing a Queen trade.} 15. Qd5 Qxd5 16. exd5 {With even material, the endgame is quite safe for us.} Bxe3+ 17. fxe3 O-O-O {Black has an inferior pawn structure because of the doubled c-pawns. However, White doesn't have good ways to make use of it.} 18. e4 {Consolidating the d5-pawn, so that the Rook can switch to the c-file, pressuring our doubled pawns. White wants to play Kb1 followed by Rc1.} Rhe8 {X-raying the Knight on e2 and not allowing White time for their plan with attacking our doubled pawns in view of the 19...f5 threat. Our plan is to attack White's central pawn chain by combining ideas of f5 and c6. Our Knight can be rerouted to a better square via c4-e5 or c4-b6. The position is balanced. #4}) 10... Ne7 {If not sure when it is possible to take the pawn on d4 and when not, we can rely on an easy rule: we do never take the pawn when our Knight is still on g8 and we don't have the option to follow up with short castle.} 11. Ne2 {Now that White has protected the d4 pawn with the Knight, taking the pawn means giving up our dark squared Bishop, thus weakening our dark squares which White will be able to exploit since they still have a dark squared Bishop on the board. We prefer to avoid such an outcome.} O-O 12. h4 {White argues that their King is safe in the centre and tries to start a quick attack on the Kingside.} (12. Qxb7 {leaves White behind with their development and we can meet it with} Qd7 {with the threat of 13...Rfb8, trapping White's Queen. Black will have great compensation for the sacrificed pawn thanks to ideas linked with c5, opening the long dark diagonal for our Bishop and Ra(f)b8 - targeting the b2-pawn.}) 12... a5 {The Queen on b3 is very well placed as it not only attacks the b7-pawn, but also keeps an eye on the Kingside. We want to disturb it by playing 13...a4.} 13. a4 {The most direct way to stop our pawn advance on the a-file, thus keep the b3 position for the Queen.} (13. h5 {Staying true to the idea of an attack on the Kingside.} c5 {One of the basic chess principles says that when your opponent starts an attack on one of the flanks, one should counter-attack in the centre. Exactly what we do here!} 14. dxc5 {Accepting the pawn sacrifice right away.} (14. hxg6 {White uses the fact that our f7-pawn is pinned and we have to capture back with the h-pawn.} hxg6 15. dxc5 {We have sacrificed a pawn in order to get counterplay via the d-file.} a4 {Disturbing White's Queen and planning to use our super-strong Bishop on g7 by means of playing a3 if allowed.} 16. Qa3 Qd7 {White has stopped our a3 threat, but their Queen is not ideally placed now. On the other hand, our Queen does a great job on the d-file and we plan to start disturbing White's King by bringing our f-Rook to d8. Black has good compensation for the sacrificed pawn, mainly because White can't solve the issue of their King's safety. #5}) 14... a4 {Not only attacking the Queen, but also planning to follow up with a3.} 15. Qa3 Nc6 {Our Knight aims for the d4-square, to trade the main defender of White's King - the Knight.} 16. Bf4 {The best way to fight against Black's threat of 16...Qf6. 16.hxg6 doesn't work well as we can recapture with the f-pawn, opening up the f-file, thus making White's doubled f-pawns easy targets.} (16. Be3 {will be met by} Qf6 {with a double attack on the f3 and b2 pawns.}) 16... Qe7 {With good compensation for the sacrificed pawn thanks to our strong dark squared Bishop, the weakness of White's c5-pawn, and our good control over the dark squares. We plan on bringing our Knight to e5, creating threats against White's b2-pawn by means of Nc4. #6}) 13... Bxd4 {Do you remember that we wanted to avoid trading our Bishop for White's Knight?} 14. h5 {White continues their Kingside attack.} ({Well, now we can do that as we've got control over the b4-square and after} 14. Nxd4 Qxd4 {we have the important threat of 15...Qb4+, forcing the Queen trade.}) 14... Re8 {The Rook wasn't doing much on f8, so we bring it to x-ray White's King.} 15. Bg5 {Planning to castle long.} Bg7 {The best way to stop White from castling long.} 16. h6 {Forcing our Bishop to a less comfortable square.} Bh8 17. Rd1 Qc8 {Given that we are a pawn up, we'd love to trade Queens and head to an endgame. Our plan is to prepare Qe6 by means of b6 - so that the b7-pawn won't be hanging. White has compensation for the sacrificed pawn, but it is not easy to make use of it, as there are no direct ways to create threats against our King. #7} *

