[PlyCount "26"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. c3 {The idea of this setup is to prepare, force Black to take on, and then recapture with the c3-pawn in order to get some nice control in the centre. The central pawn structure advantage will grant White more space for their light pieces to maneuver around, as well as prospectives of an attack on the Kingside. Black's counterplay will be linked with combining pawn advances on the Queenside (in order to secure important squares for their light pieces) with attacking White's central pawns (e4 and d4).  After years of playing the Ruy Lopez with both colors, I find that it's easier to go wrong while playing with the White pieces, as the 'visual' advantage of the space tends to make one over-optimistic about their chances. It often leads to getting over-ambitious and pushing too hard which is of course convenient for Black. Therefore, arm yourself with patience and you'll be ready to learn the most important ideas Black has in this structure!} a6 {We want White to decide on which diagonal should their Bishop land.} 5. Bc4 {Is an interesting and logical try, eyeing the f7-pawn with ideas of d4, Ng5, to make it feel even more uncomfortable. However, it allows Black an unexpected move!} f5 $5 {The pawn was weak on f7, why not make it challenge White's centre then? This move goes against the basic chess principles, which say that one needs to finish the development first and only then go for breakthroughs. Despite it, White doesn't have a good way to punish our 'eccentric' move!} 6. d3 {The most logical and solid move.} (6. d4 {An attempt to open up the centre and create threats against our King.} fxe4 {With tempo! If White's Knight moves to g5, eyeing the f7-square, we can cover it all by playing 7...d5. White must try to prevent it.} 7. Bxg8 (7. Qb3 {A double purpose move, taking control over the d5-square and attacking our Knight on g8.} Na5 {We can make our own threats - Fork!} 8. Bf7+ {Might look as if our King is in big trouble - but it's not the case!} Ke7 {White's Queen will struggle to find a safe square and protect the f7-Bishop at the same time.} 9. Qd5 {Forcing us to find an only, but quite an obvious move.} (9. Bg5+ {will be met by} Nf6 {as well.}) 9... Nf6 10. Qxa5 (10. Bg5 {will be met by} Bh6 {distracting White's dark squared Bishop. White will have a hard time saving all their hanging pieces.}) 10... exf3 11. Bb3 c5 {Trading off the Queens would be convenient for us, as our King is not exactly safe on e7 and we also have an extra pawn for the moment, one which will be easier to convert in an endgame.} 12. Qxd8+ ({White can't really avoid it, as} 12. Qxc5+ {can be met by} d6 {and if} 13. Qc4 {then} d5 {where White's Queen will struggle to find a good position.}) 12... Kxd8 {The g2-pawn is hanging and White has to do something about it, but the problem is that the d4-pawn is hanging as well! White can only hope for good enough compensation for the sacrificed pawn in order to maintain the balance, definitely not for more! We will of course take the d4-pawn and then finish our development by bringing one Bishop to g7 and the other to b7 (after playing b5). #1}) 7... exf3 {Once again, we prefer to take the Knight and leave White's light squared Bishop trying to find a safe square. When remembering these lines, one can use this pattern in order to recall things easily 'When I can take the f3-Knight and light squared Bishop, I go for the Knight!'. Now White has to part with either the Bishop on g8 or the g2-pawn.} 8. Bd5 fxg2 {With a pawn up and a decisive advantage. White's King is definitely not safer than ours and then the question appears 'What did White sacrifice the pawn for?'. We will continue the development by playing Bg7, d6, 0-0 (if allowed) and then start creating threats against White's King by means of Qh4, Bg4. #2}) (6. exf5 $2 {Even though it looks very natural, it doesn't work, as it allows us to take a lot of space in the centre and force White's pieces to passive squares.} e4 {Attacking the Knight and planning to follow up with 7...d5, closing up the a2-g8 diagonal for White's light squared Bishop.} 7. Qe2 {An indirect way of protecting the f3 Knight. The e4-pawn is now hanging.} d5 {One can notice that all of Black's moves come with a threat so that White doesn't have time to create any big threats of their own.} 8. Bb3 Qe7 {Covering against the pin over the e-file, thus reinforcing the threat against the f3-Knight.} 9. Nd4 Ne5 {10...Nd3 is now a very unpleasant threat, so is 10...c5. The f5-pawn is at our mercy as well.} 10. Bxd5 {White can't afford to be greedy. On the other hand, there are no good alternatives.} Nf6 {Another move with a tempo, attacking the Bishop on d5.} 11. Bb3 (11. Bxe4 {doesn't work, as after} Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Nd3+ {White loses the Queen.}) 11... Nd3+ {Look at White's pieces, almost all of them are on their initial squares. The ones which are developed struggle as well.} 12. Kd1 c5 {White is lost. The d4-Knight is hanging and when it moves away, Black can choose from a variety of good continuations. 13...gxf5 is one of them, another would be 13...Ng4, attacking the f2-pawn. We couldn't have hoped for a better opening outcome! #3}) 6... Bg7 {Continuing our development. An important idea to keep in mind is closing up White's dark squared Bishop by means of f4.} 7. Ng5 {A non-dangerous one move threat.} Nh6 {Covering the f7-square and threatening 8...f4, which would leave White's g5-Knight unprotected.} 8. f4 {The only way to make sure we don't play f4 ourselves.} (8. O-O f4 {White has to do something about the hanging g5-Knight now.} 9. Nf3 (9. h4 {would make not much difference, as after} Bf6 {the Knight would still have to move away from g5.}) 9... d6 {Our dark squared pawn chain in the centre is very stable and can't really be disturbed by White's forces. It does an important job in limiting White's pieces. Our plan is simple: Nf7, 0-0, Qf6 and then start an attack on the Kingside by playing g5-g4. White doesn't have enough counterplay. #4}) 8... Na5 {But we now go for our favourite Bishop hunt!} 9. fxe5 (9. Bd5 {would be met by} c6) 9... Nxc4 10. dxc4 Qe7 {Black has gained the pair of Bishops and is now happily attacking White's weak doubled e-pawns.} 11. O-O {White has succeeded in bringing the King to safety, but it's the only good news for them.} b6 {The Bishop wasn't happy on c8, so we find a nice diagonal for it!} 12. exf5 (12. Qd5 {would be met by} Rb8 {followed up by 13...Bb7, with an outcome similar to the main line.}) 12... Nxf5 13. Qf3 {Does White hope for us to blunder the Rook?} Rb8 {With full compensation for the sacrificed pawn. 14...Bb7 will be our next move, followed by 15...0-0. White will need at least 2 moves to finish their development, but finding good squares for the b1-Knight and c1-Bishop is a big challenge.  The e5-pawn can be captured by us any time we please, which will create a material balance and a big positional imbalance in Black's favor thanks to the mighty Bishop pair. #5} *

