1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. c3 {The idea of this setup is to prepare, force Black to take on, and then recapture with the c3-pawn in order to get some nice control in the centre. The central pawn structure advantage will grant White more space for their light pieces to maneuver around, as well as prospectives of an attack on the Kingside. Black's counterplay will be linked with combining pawn advances on the Queenside (in order to secure important squares for their light pieces) with attacking White's central pawns (e4 and d4).  After years of playing the Ruy Lopez with both colors, I find that it's easier to go wrong while playing with the White pieces, as the 'visual' advantage of the space tends to make one over-optimistic about their chances. It often leads to getting over-ambitious and pushing too hard which is of course convenient for Black. Therefore, arm yourself with patience and you'll be ready to learn the most important ideas Black has in this structure!} a6 {We want White to decide on which diagonal should their Bishop land.} 5. Bc4 {Is an interesting and logical try, eyeing the f7-pawn with ideas of d4, Ng5, to make it feel even more uncomfortable. However, it allows Black an unexpected move!} Bg7 {Is the safer option, one to play if you're not in the mood for fireworks. It works quite well for Black as well.} 6. d4 exd4 7. Bg5 {White doesn't allow us to develop the Knight to f6, as it would be met by 8.e5.} (7. cxd4 b5 8. Bb3 {with a transposition to mainline, 5.Ba4}) 7... Nge7 {But our Knight is very well placed on e7 here, as it still supports the d5 breakthrough.} 8. Nxd4 Nxd4 9. cxd4 h6 {An useful move, asking the Bishop to decide whether to stay on the d8-h4 diagonal or not.} 10. Bh4 d5 {The key move! It is a temporary pawn sacrifice, but one which forces White to spoil their pawn structure and commit to playing with an isolated pawn.} 11. exd5 Qd7 {Getting rid of the pin over the h4-d8 diagonal and preparing to take on d5, but not before castling!} 12. O-O O-O 13. Nc3 {Protecting the d5-pawn and finishing the development.} (13. Bxe7 {isn't doing much good, as after} Qxe7 {the d4-pawn will be weak and we'll be able to put pressure on it by playing Qf6. The pair of Bishops together with White's isolated doubled d-pawns give us great compensation for the sacrificed pawn!}) 13... b5 {Forcing White's Bishop to a more passive position and preparing to finish our development by bringing our Bishop to b7, from where it will also attack the d5-pawn.} 14. Bb3 Nf5 {With a double attack on the h4-Bishop and d4-pawn. White can't save them both.} 15. Bg3 Nxd4 {With a preferable position for Black, as the pawn on d5 is still isolated and weak. We'll be able to attack it by bringing the light squared Bishop to b7 and the a-Rook to d8. Our Knight on d4 is a great asset, as it takes away from White many important squares!} *

[Event "London International Master 1883"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "MacKenzie, Ken"]
[Black "Steinitz, William"]
[Result "0-1"]
[PlyCount "96"]
[EventDate "2022.10.04"]

{Can you believe that this game was played almost 150 years ago but it is still relevant to modern theory? The first World Champion, William Steinitz was one of the first players to play 3...g6.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. d4 {White tries the most direct and aggressive move.} exd4 5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Be3 {Protecting the d4-Knight and continuing the development.} Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. O-O {Both sides tried to be as fast as possible with their development.} Ne7 {The best move and the one recommended in the course. I was so impressed that the first World Champion was actually the first one to play it in 1883!} 9. h3 {Taking the g4-square under control so that none of Black's pieces would be able to jump there after Black will play d5.} ({The idea is to play 9...d5, but it also has a little hidden trap for White, as the active and natural-looking} 9. e5 {is bad in view of} Nfd5 {attacking the e5-pawn and the Bishop on e3. One can check the 4.d4 line for more details on it.}) 9... c6 10. Bd3 d5 {Opening up the diagonal for the light squared Bishop. Black is slightly better thanks to the superior dark squared Bishop which puts pressure on the long dark diagonal.} 11. exd5 $2 {Even though it looks very natural, it is already a serious mistake as after trading the Knights on d5, White won't be able to keep the dark squared Bishop on the board because it has to stay on e3 and protect the Knight on d4.} (11. Nf3 {The only way to keep the game balanced.} dxe4 12. Bxe4 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 {Might be what White missed; Black can win the pawn on b2, but after} Bxb2 (13... Qxd1 14. Rfxd1 Bf5 {With a slightly better position for Black thanks to the Bishop pair.}) 14. Rb1 Bg7 15. Bc5 {White would have great compensation for it.}) 11... Nexd5 {All White's light pieces are uncomfortable now.} 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. c3 Nxe3 14. fxe3 $17 {Black has now a significant advantage thanks to the Bishop pair and White's very weak pawn on e3.} Qg5 {Double attack on the e3 and h3 pawns.} 15. Qf3 Bd7 {Preparing to mount pressure on the e3-pawn by attacking it with the Rook from e8.} 16. Bc4 {White hopes to get to the f7-pawn.} Rae8 17. Rae1 (17. Bxf7+ $4 {Is bad.} Kh8 {And White's Bishop on f7 is in big trouble; we want to win it by playing 18...Re7. The pawn on e3 is also still hanging.}) 17... Be5 $4 {A very surprising blunder by the 1st World Champion. White could now have won.} (17... Kh8 {Would keep Black's huge advantage, as White can't take on f7 with a tempo in any variation. Prophylaxis is important, especially given that Black's advantage is long-term and there are no reasons to hurry.}) 18. Ne2 $4 {Returning the favour.} (18. Bxf7+ $1 Kh8 (18... Kg7 {Makes no difference.} 19. Bxe8 Rxf3 20. Nxf3 Qe7 21. Bxd7 $18 {White is winning.}) 19. Bxe8 Rxf3 20. Nxf3 {Too many of Black's pieces are now under attack.} Qe7 21. Bxd7 $18 {With a completely winning position as White has 2 Rooks and a Knight for Black's Queen.}) 18... Re7 {Steinitz now makes sure not to allow his opponent any chances.} 19. Nf4 Kg7 20. Rd1 Bc8 {The World Champion does exactly what I was saying before, not hurrying to convert his advantage by taking some drastic measures. The pawn on e3 is weak forever and our pair of Bishops will not go anywhere, so we can take our time to slowly improve our position without allowing any counterplay.} 21. Rf2 Bc7 {Black plans now to triple on the e-file.} 22. Kh1 Qe5 23. Re1 Bf5 24. Kg1 Rfe8 {Finally, all of our pieces are ideally placed! 25...Qc5 with a double attack on c4 and e3 is now a serious threat.} 25. g4 {Desperation. White weakens his King even more.} Be4 26. Qd1 Rd8 27. Qe2 Red7 28. Qf1 Kh8 {Steinitz makes sure that White doesn't have even the slightest hope now.} 29. h4 f5 30. g5 Rd2 31. Qh3 Rxf2 32. Kxf2 Qc5 {An unexpected double attack on c4 and f4.} 33. Ne6 Qxc4 34. Nxd8 Bxd8 {With a decisive material advantage.} 35. Qg3 Qd5 36. c4 Qd7 37. Qe5+ Kg8 38. Re2 h6 39. Ke1 Bc7 40. Qd4 Bg3+ 41. Kd2 Qxd4+ 42. exd4 Bxh4 43. gxh6 Bg5+ 44. Ke1 Bxh6 45. Kf2 Kf7 46. b3 Bf4 47. a4 g5 48. a5 g4 {It would have been the perfect model game if not for that slip on the 17th move. However, if we don't take that into count, the game is a very good example of how a position that looks equal and almost symmetrical can go wrong very easily with just 1-2 inaccurate moves by White. Conclusions:   1. Little nuances can be game-changing. White had trouble in the game from the very beginning because he didn't realize his pieces are very unstable in the centre. Many times, thanks to our nice dark squared Bishop on g7 which has no opponent on the long dark diagonal, even positions with symmetrical pawn structures can be better for us.   2. Never relax until your opponent has resigned no matter how winning the position is.   3. If you have a long-term advantage, don't hurry to convert it as it is very unpleasant for your opponent to defend and they are likely to lose patience and make your job even easier. Try instead not to allow them any counterplay at all and slowly improve the position of your pieces.} 0-1

[Event "Leningrad 1975"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Kasparov, Garry"]
[Black "Smyslov, Vassily"]
[Result "0-1"]
[PlyCount "60"]
[EventDate "2022.10.04"]

{An interesting game between a future World Champion, 12-year-old Garry, and the very experienced ex-World Champion at the time, Vassily Smyslov (64 years old).} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 {Vassily Smyslov's favorite weapon. He played this line extensively throughout his chess career and it was not a surprise this line was later named in his honor.} 4. d4 {One of the most aggressive moves.} exd4 5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Be3 (6. Nxc6 {Doesn't work well due to a tactical trick we have covered in the course.} bxc6 7. Bc4 Nf6 8. e5 Ne4 9. Qe2 O-O {The point! Now} 10. Qxe4 {will be met by} d5 {getting back the sacrificed piece, as White can't take} 11. exd6 {because of} Re8 {and White loses the Queen.}) 6... Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O {Black tries to finish the development as fast as possible.} 8. O-O Re8 $5 {Also interesting, just putting pressure on White's e4-pawn. Perhaps the experienced ex-World Champion wanted to keep the game complicated instead of just comfortably equalizing against his young opponent.} (8... Ne7 {The move recommended in the course. It equalizes quite easily. Smyslov played this move in some of his later games.}) 9. f3 $6 {Imprecise, though it looks very natural. The problem is that the Bishop on e3 is now a tactical weakness (it's not protected by any other piece while Black's Rook from e8 is x-raying it).} (9. Re1 $1 {Would be the best, indirectly protecting the e4-pawn.} Nxd4 (9... Nxe4 $4 {A huge blunder.} 10. Nxe4 Rxe4 11. Nxc6 {The point, Black can't recapture on c6 with the d-pawn, as the Queen on d8 is hanging.} bxc6 12. Bxc6 $18 {Winning material.}) 10. Bxd4 c6 11. Bf1 (11. Bc4 {Isn't optimal, as it allows Black to force White's pieces to less optimal squares.} b5 {Planning to continue with 12...b4, then 13...d6, preparing to take the e4-pawn at the right time.}) 11... d6 {With the idea of continuing with 12...b5, or if White doesn't allow it by playing 12.a4, we can go for c5. The idea is still to build up pressure against White's e4-pawn.}) 9... Ne5 {Playing against White's b5 Bishop which might run into trouble. Ideas like 10...c5 followed by 11...c4 and 12...a6 trapping the Bishop are now in the air.} 10. h3 {White takes the g4-square under control and prepares to play 11.f4.} a6 {The hunt on the Bishop starts now.} (10... c5 {Was also possible.} 11. Nb3 a6 ({Now} 11... c4 {doesn't work in view of} 12. Nd2 {attaking the c4-pawn.}) 12. Be2 d6 {With a complicated position and chances for both sides.}) 11. Be2 d5 (11... d6 {Would be better, as White's light pieces stay in each other's way and Black threats to make use of it by playing 12...c5 or 12...b5 if allowed, continuing then to put pressure on the e4 pawn.} 12. f4 $2 Ned7 {The pawn on e4 is now attacked.} 13. Bf3 Nc5 {And White can't protect their e4-pawn.}) 12. f4 {A strong intermediate move!} (12. exd5 $6 {The simplifications don't work well for White, as their Bishop on e3 is very uncomfortable, White ours does a great job on the long dark diagonal.} Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 {Our e5-Knight now wants to jump, opening up the e-file for our Rook to attack the e3 Bishop.} 14. Bf2 Nc6 $15 {With a better position thanks to our strong dark squared Bishop and White's weakened dark squares (e3, f2, g3).}) 12... Nc4 {Black allows White to double his pawns on the c-file but gets the Bishop pair for it.} 13. Bxc4 dxc4 {The e4-pawn is now attacked.} 14. Qf3 {Somewhat slow.} (14. e5 {Was best.} Nd5 15. Qf3 Nxc3 (15... Nxe3 {would be met by} 16. Qxe3 {and White is still better, as there's no good way for Black to open up the position for the Bishop pair.}) 16. bxc3 {White would have been here better thanks to the nice pawn chain f4-e5 which restricts Black's dark squared Bishop, the extra pawn on the Kingside and the strong Knight on d4.}) 14... c5 15. Nde2 Bd7 $2 {Too slow.} (15... Nxe4 $1 {A little tactical trick.} 16. Nxe4 Qe7 {There are too many pieces on the e-file and White can't save them all.} 17. N2g3 Bf5 18. Nxf5 (18. Bxc5 Bxe4 {Also gets back the piece.}) 18... gxf5 {Winning back the piece.}) 16. e5 Bc6 17. Qf2 Nd7 {An interesting moment. Smyslov offers his younger opponent a pawn in order to try to get some activity for it.} 18. Bxc5 $2 {A mistake, as Black gets good compensation for the sacrificed pawn.} (18. Rad1 {Would be much better, threatening to take the pawn on c5 now, without giving up the dark squared Bishop.} b6 19. Nd5 $16 {With a big advantage thanks to the much better pieces and the pawn majority on the Kingside. White's plan is simple- bring the e2 Knight to c3 and then to e4, while it is unclear what's Black counterplay.}) 18... Nxc5 19. Qxc5 Rc8 {X-raying the Queen and threatening to take the g2-pawn. If White retreats with the Queen to e3 or f2, Black can open up the g7 Bishop by playing f6 with good compensation thanks to the pair of Bishops.} 20. Rad1 Qh4 {The threats are still the same.} 21. Qe3 g5 {Fighting against White's central pawn chain which restricts our dark squared Bishop. 21...f6 was also a good option.} 22. Nd5 $6 {Is imprecise as Black can now create dangerous threats of his own.} (22. Nd4 {Would be better as Black doesn't have a good way to avoid trading the c6-Bishop.} gxf4 23. Rxf4 Qg5 24. Nxc6 Rxc6 {The position remains complicated as White's e5-pawn is weak, but White is still a pawn up for now.}) 22... gxf4 23. Rxf4 Qg5 {Suddenly, White has a lot of weaknesses to keep an eye on the g2-pawn, the e5-pawn, and the Queen on e3 is x-rayed.} 24. Nf6+ Kh8 {Threatening mate on g2.} (24... Bxf6 {doesn't work because of} 25. Rg4 {winning Black's Queen.}) 25. Qf2 Rxe5 {Getting back the sacrificed pawn.} 26. Nd4 $4 {Young Garry blunders.} (26. Ng3 {Covering the g-file would be the only way to keep the game going.} Bxf6 27. Rxf6 Rg8 28. Rxf7 Qe3 (28... Qxg3 {doesn't work because of} 29. Qf6+) 29. Kf1 Qxf2+ 30. Kxf2 Reg5 {Black is still better but will need a lot of moves to prove it is enough for winning.}) 26... Bxf6 27. Rxf6 Bxg2 {The Queen on f2 was overloaded, both protecting g2 and f6. White's position is now hopeless.} 28. Kh2 Re3 29. Qxg2 Qxf6 30. Qxb7 Qf4+ {A game with quite some mistakes, but one from which we can learn a lot.   Conclusions:   1. 8...Re8 is an interesting alternative to the 8...Ne7 move given in the course.   2. When we feel that the game is going not our way, we can try to change its character as Smyslov did in this game when sacrificing his c5 pawn.   3. When one has the Bishop pair and open diagonals for them, it can be worthy of more than even a pawn. If one plays against the Bishop pair in a position with an open character, trading one of them should be the main goal.   4. Stay always tactically alert and don't overload your pieces like Garry did here with his Queen on f2.} 0-1

[Event "Szolnok 1975"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Rajna"]
[Black "Smyslov"]
[Result "0-1"]
[PlyCount "84"]
[EventDate "2022.10.05"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Nc3 {A line which isn't played often. White was probably surprised by Black's choice of opening and tries to simply continue the development. However, he can't really hope for an advantage.} Bg7 5. d3 ({Interesting would be} 5. h4 $5 {check the corresponding line in the course for more on it.}) 5... Nge7 {Isn't bad either, but allows White to play 6.h4.} ({In the line with} 5... h6 {after} 6. h4 {we have} Nf6 {this is the main difference and the reason we prefer to start with 5...h6.}) (5... h6 {Is the move on which we rely in the course, preventing White from playing 6.Bg5.} 6. O-O Nge7 7. Be3 Nd4 {Stopping d4 and then planning to castle and prepare either d5 or f5.}) 6. Bg5 $6 {I believe that developing this Bishop too soon gives better chances for Black because of the 'Bishop at the top of a diagonal concept' thanks to which Black will be able to win a few tempi.} h6 {Starting the hunt on White's Bishop.} 7. Bh4 $6 {Not the happiest place for the Bishop, as it will get locked up on g3.} (7. Be3 {(which will be met by 7...Nd4) or 7.Bd2 was better, though it now becomes clear that it would have been even better not to develop that Bishop at all.}) 7... g5 8. Bg3 d6 {Planning to land the light squared Bishop on g4.} 9. h3 (9. Nd2 {Was maybe better.} h5 10. f3 {Hoping to bring the dark squared Bishop back into the game via f2.} h4 11. Bf2 Ng6 12. Nd5 {Black is still better thanks to the good control over the dark squares, but it is not clear if we can prove it to be enough.}) 9... a6 {Black starts instead another hunt on White's Bishop.} (9... f5 {Was more natural, with the idea to play 10... f4 if allowed.} 10. exf5 Bxf5 {And Black is clearly better, as White doesn't have good counterplay, while Black has everything- better control in the centre, more space, better-placed pieces.}) 10. Ba4 b5 11. Bb3 Na5 {White's Bishops are neutralized, thus strategically the battle is won by Black.} 12. h4 Nxb3 (12... g4 {Was also interesting.} 13. Nd2 f5 14. exf5 Nxb3 15. axb3 Bxf5 {Black is better thanks to the pair of Bishops.}) 13. axb3 Bg4 $2 {Black might have overestimated his pair of Bishops, playing against the g3 Bishop.} (13... g4 $1 {Was better.} 14. Nd2 b4 {Forcing away all of White's pieces.} 15. Ne2 f5 $17 {With a significant advantage for Black.}) 14. hxg5 hxg5 15. Rxh8+ Bxh8 16. Qe2 $6 (16. Qd2 $1 {Was more precise.} Bxf3 17. gxf3 Nc6 18. Nd5 Nd4 19. Qd1 c6 20. Ne3 Qf6 {White sacrifices a pawn, but makes Black's Knight go to a less active position.} 21. c3 $1 Nxf3+ 22. Kf1 {23.Ng4 is now a very unpleasant threat.} Nh4 23. Bxh4 gxh4 24. Qg4 $14 {White's problems are now left behind and it is now Black who actually struggles to bring the Bishop into the game.}) 16... Nc6 17. Nd5 Nd4 18. Nxd4 $4 {Too romantic. White hoped that the pair of Knights would be good enough against the Queen as the position is closed.} (18. Qd1 {Was the only move and the position is unpleasant, but still not that bad, as it would be difficult for Black to breakthrough.} Nxf3+ 19. gxf3 Be6 20. Ne3 {Black would have to work hard to prove his advantage to be enough for a win.}) 18... Bxe2 19. Nxe2 c6 $18 {The rest was easy, Black comfortably converted his material advantage.} 20. Ne3 Qb6 21. f3 O-O-O 22. Bf2 Qb7 23. b4 Bg7 24. Nf5 Bf8 25. Be3 f6 26. Nc1 d5 27. Bc5 Bxc5 28. bxc5 dxe4 29. fxe4 Kd7 30. Kf2 Rh8 31. Nb3 Ke6 32. Na5 Qc7 33. b4 g4 34. Nb3 g3+ 35. Nxg3 Qg7 36. Nc1 Qg5 37. Nce2 Qd2 38. c3 Rh4 39. Nh5 Rxh5 40. Rxa6 Rh1 41. Rxc6+ Kf7 42. Rc7+ Kg6 {Conclusions:   1. 4.Nc3 is a rather harmless line.   2. Remember to 'hunt' the Bishops which are at the top of a diagonal.   3. Even if you dislike your position, try to be resilient, getting into a desperado mood and sacrificing material makes the job easier for your opponent. Being able to defend is a very important skill that pays off at all levels.} 0-1

