[PlyCount "76"]
[EventDate "2022.10.08"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. c3 d6 {A different move than the one I recommend in the course (4...a6), but the position which later appeared on the board is very similar to some we get in the 4.0-0 line when White captures on e5 after playing c3 and d4.} 5. d4 Bd7 6. dxe5 {White chooses to take the tension off in the centre and argue that this will still grant some advantage.} dxe5 7. Qe2 Bg7 8. Be3 {White sticks to a central strategy, developing his pieces to central squares.} Nge7 $6 (8... Nf6 {Would have been better. If you remember, when allowed- we prefer to develop our Knight to f6, as it is a more active square (from which we attack the e4 pawn), but also one which none of our remaining pieces need, much unlike the e7-square.}) 9. Nbd2 a6 10. Bc4 Qc8 {Black wants to play 11...Be6 and trade Bishops.} 11. O-O O-O 12. b4 {A very good continuation. White wants to take more space on the Queenside and start disturbing our c6-Knight by means of a4, b5.} Nd8 {Smyslov doesn't wait until his Knight is attacked and prefers to immediately reroute it to a better place, the e6-square.} 13. a4 Ne6 {Perhaps hoping for 14...Nf4. Still, Black's position is quite difficult because their pieces are quite clumsy. That's why I actually wanted to present this game, in order to get once and for all that if possible. In these structures where White takes on e5, we prefer to have our Knight on f6, so that it won't fight for the same squares with our other Knight on c6.} 14. Ng5 $6 {Given that Black's pieces are clumsy and they fight for the same squares, trading some of them doesn't seem like an inspired decision.} (14. Rfd1 {Continuing with the central strategy would have been better.} Nf4 15. Bxf4 exf4 16. e5 $16 {White is much better thanks to the weakness of Black's f4 pawn and the fact that the Bishop on g7 is very restricted by White's e5-pawn.}) 14... Nc6 15. Nxe6 Bxe6 16. Nb3 Nd8 {Black goes once again with the Kight to d8, hoping to trade the light squared Bishops and then bring the Knight to e6.} 17. Rad1 b6 {Covering the c5-square.} 18. Bd5 {White wants to force the trade of Bishops on his own terms.} Bxd5 19. Rxd5 $2 {White is still better thanks to the control over the d-file and the slightly better-placed pieces, but the problem is that these are all short-term advantages, which can easily go away within a few moves.} (19. exd5 $16 {It is very surprising Tal did not go for this position where his advantage would be nearly decisive. Perhaps he didn't want to allow Black counterplay after} f5 {but there would be} 20. f3 {and it is unclear how Black would then continue the counterplay. Meanwhile, White's plan in this position is quite simple- create a passed pawn in the centre by pushing c4-c5, d6.}) 19... Ne6 {Black's Knight eyes the f4-square.} 20. Rfd1 Qe8 21. a5 Qa4 $2 {Not the most inspired idea, as White has an easy way to protect the Knight, and then, Black's Queen will be misplaced on a4.} (21... Nf4 {Would be better, as it forces White to open our dark squared Bishop.} 22. Bxf4 exf4 23. e5 c6 {Leaving all the worst behind, as the e5 pawn is now falling.}) 22. Qc2 Nf4 {Black hopes White would take on f4, opening up the long dark diagonal for his Bishop.} 23. R5d2 Qc6 24. g3 Nh3+ (24... Ne6 {Would not be better either.} 25. axb6 cxb6 26. Rd6 {Winning the pawn on b6.}) 25. Kg2 {The Knight on h3 is trapped.} f5 {Desperation.} 26. axb6 {Doesn't spoil things either.} (26. Kxh3 {Was winning, though White would still have to make a few accurate moves.} f4 27. Bxb6 {Returning the extra piece, but keeping a pawn and most importantly, a safe King.} (27. gxf4 $4 {It would be a mistake to open up the King even more.} exf4 28. Bd4 Qe6+ 29. Kg2 Qg4+ {How nice would be now to have a pawn on g3 to cover the King, right?} 30. Kf1 f3 {And the things are far from clear, as White still has many issues to solve regarding the King's safety.}) 27... Qe6+ 28. Kg2 f3+ 29. Kh1 {30...Qh3 is not something to worry about, as there is always 31.Rg1, covering the g2-square.} cxb6 30. axb6 Qxb6 31. Nc5 {With a decisive advantage.}) 26... f4 27. Bc5 f3+ 28. Kf1 (28. Kxh3 $4 {Loses.} Qe6+ 29. g4 Rf4 30. Rg1 g5 $19 {With mate in 3.}) 28... cxb6 29. Bxf8 Rxf8 30. Qd3 {White is completely winning and wants to trade Queens by delivering a check on d5.} Kh8 31. Qd5 (31. Qd7 {With a double attack was better.} Qc4+ 32. Rd3 Qxb3 33. Qxh3 $18) 31... Qxc3 32. b5 axb5 33. Qxb5 $6 {Allows unnecessary complications.} Qc8 34. Qd7 Qc4+ 35. Rd3 Ng5 36. Nd2 Qc2 {I suppose both players were in severe time trouble by this point, otherwise, explaining White's blunder on the next move is not easy.} 37. Ke1 $4 {Protects the Rook on d1, but runs into big trouble because of the very weak e2 square.} (37. Re1 $18 {Would be still totally winning for White.}) 37... Nxe4 {Threatening to take on f2 and then on d1, but also a fork on c5 is in the air!} 38. Ra1 Nc5 {An unexpected end for this game where it seemed that White was dominating throughout the whole game. I hope this is an example of how things can go wrong for Black so that you'd be able to avoid it.   Conclusions:    1. When allowed, we prefer to place our g8 Knight to f6, rather than e7.   2. Trading pieces is convenient for the side that has less space or bad piece coordination.   3. Once again- never relax too soon! You have to work at 100% capacity until your opponent resigns. Even World Champions forget about it sometimes.   4. When in a hopeless position, try to find moves that set little traps and prolong the battle; it is never too late to resign and nobody won a game by doing it.} 0-1

[Event "Tilburg 1982"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Timman, Jan"]
[Black "Smyslov, Vassily"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[PlyCount "80"]
[EventDate "2022.10.08"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. c3 a6 5. Bc4 {Choosing one of the sidelines.} Bg7 (5... f5 {was the aggressive alternative which was covered in the course as well.}) 6. d4 d6 {The most popular move, especially in the old times. However, it is more passive and Black's score here is worse than in our 6...exd4. It is helpful though to know how the theory developed and which are the dangers of these positions.} (6... exd4 {The move recommended in the course.} 7. cxd4 b5 8. Bb3 {transposes to the mainline with 5.Ba4 and 8.Bb3, check the corresponding chapter for more details on it.}) 7. Bg5 $6 ({The best is} 7. O-O h6 8. Re1 {Protecting the e4-pawn, though not allowing Black's Knight to f6, as then White will be able to win a pawn after 9.dxe5.} Nge7 9. Be3 $14 {White's position is preferable, as the Knight on e7 doesn't have great prospects and doesn't help Black to challenge White's centre.}) 7... Nge7 $6 (7... Nf6 {Knowing that the Knight is not ideal on e7, it was much metter to place it here, on a more active square.} 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qxd8+ Nxd8 10. Nxe5 Nxe4 11. Bxd8 Bxe5 {Black has no problems at all.}) 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qe2 h6 {I really like how Smyslov fights against the Bishops, asking the dark squared one a question, where to retreat?} 10. Bh4 $2 {The wrong route; there is nothing for the Bishop to do there, much better was 10.Be3 with a slightly better position for White.} b5 $6 {Smyslov is consequent with his plan of getting to White's both Bishops. Perhaps it was a bit too early for that, as it allowed White 11.Bxe7, solving the problem of at least one Bishop.} (10... g5 $1 {Continuing the hunt was the best.} 11. Bg3 Ng6 $15 {With a clear advantage for Black thanks to the good control over the dark squares and White's locked Bishop on g3.}) 11. Bb3 Na5 12. O-O Nxb3 13. axb3 O-O (13... g5 {Was again better.} 14. Rd1 Bd7 15. Bg3 Ng6 16. Ne1 {Preparing to bring the Bishop back into the game by means of 17.f3 and 18.Bf2.} h5 17. f3 h4 18. Bf2 Nf4 {With better chances for Black thanks to the more active pieces and the attack on the Kingside.}) 14. c4 $2 {A mistake as it weakens the d4-square and allows Black to lock up the Queenside.} (14. Rd1 Qe8 15. b4 {Taking under control the c5-square and preparing a nice route for the b1 Knight.} Be6 {Prophylaxy against a future Nb3.} 16. Nbd2 g5 17. Bg3 Ng6 18. Ne1 {With a balanced position with chances for both sides.}) 14... b4 {Locking up the Queenside, which means that White will have no counterplay there.} 15. Nbd2 g5 16. Bg3 Nc6 17. Qe3 Qe7 18. Rfc1 Rd8 19. Nf1 {What are White's light pieces doing? Nothing, meaning that something went terribly wrong for him.} a5 20. h3 f5 $1 {Opening up the Bishop pair.} 21. exf5 Bxf5 22. Ne1 e4 {The 'monster' on g7 has now awakened!} 23. Ra2 Rd7 24. Nc2 Rd3 25. Qe2 Rxb3 $6 {Allows White some counterplay.} ({Practicing some prophylaxis would be better.} 25... Bg6 $1 26. Nfe3 Qf7 27. Nd5 Ra7 $1 {That was it for White's active moves, there are no good ways to follow them up and Black's advantage is decisive.}) 26. Nfe3 Bg6 27. Nd5 Qf7 28. Bxc7 Rd3 $2 {Black goes wrong again.} (28... Bh5 $19 {Was the only way to keep the decisive advantage.} 29. g4 (29. Qxe4 $4 Re8 {White's Queen is trapped.}) 29... Rxh3 30. gxh5 b3 $19) 29. Nce3 {White managed to consolidate a bit.} a4 30. Bb6 a3 $6 (30... b3 $1 {Would keep some advantage.} 31. Ra3 Ne5 $17) 31. Rb1 Rb8 32. bxa3 bxa3 $6 (32... b3 {Was still the way to go.} 33. Rd2 Ne5 $17 {Threatening to take on c4 and destabilize White's d5 Knight.}) 33. Rb5 Nd4 34. Bxd4 Rxb5 35. cxb5 {White's b5 passer is now also dangerous.} Bxd4 36. Qc2 Qe6 37. Qc6 Qxc6 38. bxc6 Bxe3 39. Nxe3 Rc3 40. c7 Rxc7 {Conclusions:   1. The setups with d6, Nge7 when White's Bishop is on c4 are not very good, as the Knight on e7 does have not as many prospects as if on f6, and also it occupies an important square which we prefer to have free in order to put pressure on the e4-pawn.   2. When there's a chance, ask your opponent's Bishop placed at the top of a diagonal 'THE' question. If even such strong players as Timman sometimes struggle with the correct answer, it is definitely worth trying.   3. Don't forget to think about what your opponent wants to do. Even in positions with a big advantage, prophylaxis is very important and can be very frustrating for the opponent as it slowly kills their hope.} 1/2-1/2

