1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. d4 {This aggressive move was the way White tried to refute this line for many years. The young Vishy tried it himself against no other than 'the father' of this setup, Vassily Smyslov.} exd4 5. Bg5 {White wants to force Black to develop the Bishop to e7 so that the g7 and the h6 squares become weak.} Be7 6. Bf4 {Possible but suboptimal.} (6. Bxe7 {is the mainline. Both lines are covered in the course.}) 6... Nf6 {The most natural developing move, attacking the e4-pawn.} 7. e5 Nd5 8. Bh6 {This was the idea of White's declining the Bishop trade with his 6th move. Black's King is now denied castling short and White will try to create problems for it.} a6 {Starting the hunt against the Bishop placed at the top of a diagonal.} 9. Ba4 Nb6 10. Bb3 d5 {We have this as a final position of the line in the course, as Black has already solved all the opening problems and has a very clear way to continue. The plan is to develop the Bishop from c8 to either g4 or e6 and then continue with Qd7 and long castle.} 11. exd6 Qxd6 {Black has now a very healthy extra pawn on d4 and there's not much compensation for it on the horizon.} 12. O-O Be6 {Clearing the way for the King to castle long.} 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. Nbd2 O-O-O {White is in big danger of slowly but painfully losing the game because of being a pawn down.} 15. Re1 {Trying to create some pressure against the somewhat weak e6-pawn.} Qd5 {Prophylaxis against an eventual jump of White's d2 Knight to e4 or to c4, preparing 16...Na4.} (15... Rhe8 $2 {Preparing to defend the e6-pawn by moving the Bishop to f6 doesn't work well.} 16. Ng5 Bxg5 17. Bxg5 Rd7 18. Ne4 $16 {And Black is in trouble because of the weakness of the dark squares and the imminent fork on f6.}) (15... Na4 {Doesn't work well either.} 16. Ne4 Qd7 ({Black's queen is forced back to d7, as} 16... Qd5 {is bad because of} 17. c4) 17. c4 Nc5 18. Nxc5 Bxc5 19. Qd3 {White has enough compensation for the pawn to keep the game balanced thanks to the good control of the light squares (d3, e4) and the d4- and e6-pawns which are easy to be targeted.}) 16. Qe2 {White wants to get the e6-pawn.} Rhe8 $6 {A little unambitious, Black had a way to keep the significant advantage.} (16... Na4 $1 {Now that White's Queen is away from d1 and c4 isn't something to be afraid of. It was the best move, especially since there are no good ways to protect the b2-pawn.} 17. b3 $2 (17. Rab1 Nc5 {With a similar outcome to the one after 17.b3.} 18. b4 $4 {Is terrible as it weakens the c3-square.} Na4) (17. Qxe6+ Qxe6 18. Rxe6 Nxb2 19. Bg7 Rhg8 20. Bxd4 {Perhaps this is what Smyslov disliked as White got back the pawn, but with what price! White's light pieces are very unstable, the back rank is weak, as are the a2- and c2-pawns.} Na4 {White would have to work very hard to save this position.}) 17... Nc5 {With a decisive advantage for Black since the e6 pawn is protected and d3 is coming.}) 17. Qxe6+ Qxe6 18. Rxe6 Bf8 $2 {Letting White off the hook.} (18... Na4 {Would still keep some advantage.} 19. Rb1 Nc5 20. Ree1 Nb4 {With quite some problems for White to be solved.}) 19. Rxe8 Rxe8 20. Bxf8 Rxf8 {White simplified the position a lot and the worst is behind, feeling that his advantage is gone, Smyslov offered a draw. Conclusions:  1. The pawn sacrifice in this line is unjustified for White.  2. When there's no way of protecting something directly, try to come up with threats against one of your opponent's weaknesses (the b2-pawn here).  3. One compromise usually leads to another; try to always find the most principled ways to continue, especially when you've got the material advantage, otherwise the advantage may slowly slip away.} 1/2-1/2

[Event "Russian Championship 2014"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Pogonina, Natalija"]
[Black "Galliamova, Alisa"]
[Result "0-1"]
[PlyCount "102"]
[EventDate "2022.10.08"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 a6 6. Ba4 Nge7 {A different move order than the one suggested in the course (6...b5). However, it will transpose to our mainline in a few moves.} 7. d4 exd4 8. cxd4 b5 9. Bb3 O-O 10. Nc3 Na5 11. Bc2 d6 12. h3 c5 {White has various ways to continue here. One can check out the mainline with 8.Bb3 in the course for more details. GM Pogonina goes for the most played move, though not necessarily the most dangerous one.} 13. Bg5 {Do you remember the concept of a bishop on top of a diagonal? The experienced GM Alisa Galliamova uses it and continues with the best move, starting the hunt on the g5-Bishop.} h6 14. Bf4 {Suboptimal, as it doesn't keep the pin over the h4-d8 diagonal and the positions arising are very similar to the ones after 13.Bf4, which is covered in the course. We continue with the same reaction as there.} (14. Bh4 {Is the best move and the one covered in the course.} Nac6 {Forcing White to take a decision regarding the d4-pawn.} 15. d5 Nd4 {With good play for Black; check the course for more.}) 14... cxd4 15. Nxd4 Bb7 {Completing the development while putting pressure on the e4-pawn.} 16. Rb1 {White protects the b2-pawn in case Black wants to attack it by Nc4.} Rc8 {Occupying the open c-file.} 17. Nde2 $6 (17. Re1 {Was perhaps better as White can now meet 17...d5 with 18.e5.} Nc4 {The best square for our Knight.} 18. Bb3 Re8 {With the idea to build up the pressure on the e5-pawn by means of 19...g5 followed by 20...Ng6. Black is slightly better.}) 17... d5 18. e5 {Trying to close up Black's Bishops.} (18. exd5 {Leads to an inferior position as well.} Nxd5 19. Nxd5 Qxd5 20. Qxd5 Bxd5 {Attacking both the Bishop and the a2-pawn.} 21. Nc3 Be6 $17 {Black is significantly better thanks to the fantastic Bishops. 22...b4 is now a big threat.}) 18... Nc4 $6 {Is still good but gives White the chance to put up better resistance.} (18... Nac6 $1 {Would be better as it doesn't allow White the move 19.Nd4.} 19. Qd2 (19. Nd4 $2 Nxd4 20. Qxd4 Nc6 $19 {Winning the e5-pawn, as} 21. Qe3 {is not possible in view of} d4) 19... d4 20. Ne4 Nxe5 $19 {With a decisive advantage for Black, as White not only is a pawn down but also has a lot of tactical weaknesses.} 21. Bxh6 {doesn't work because of} ({while} 21. Nxd4 {fails in view of} Nc4) 21... Rxc2) 19. Re1 (19. Nd4 {Would be the best try as it allows White to at least untangling a bit the pieces. It is difficult to admit your mistake and come back to a square you've just left a few moves ago, but it is sometimes the best solution.} Nxe5 20. Nce2 {With the idea to play b3, Qd2, Rfd1 and try to put pressure on the d5-pawn. It is clear that Black is still much better thanks to the extra pawn, but at least White can hope here.}) 19... Nxe5 20. Nd4 Nc4 21. Qd3 (21. Nce2 {The Rook on e1 proves to be a rather unuseful inclusion.} Nc6 22. b3 {Is now too late, as Black's Knight is already on c4 and can nicely land on a3.}) 21... Nc6 22. Nxc6 Bxc6 {23...d4 is now coming.} 23. b3 Na3 24. Rbc1 b4 25. Nd1 d4 {White's position is hopeless, the pieces are terribly coordinated and as a compensation, Black is pawn up.} 26. Qd2 Nxc2 27. Rxc2 Qd5 28. f3 d3 29. Rc1 Bb5 30. Kh1 (30. Qxb4 {Doesn't help.} Qd4+ 31. Qxd4 Bxd4+ 32. Kh2 g5 {And Black's Rook will come to c2. The advantage is decisive.}) 30... a5 31. Ne3 Qd4 32. Ng4 Rxc1 33. Rxc1 h5 {Black is slowly but steadily converting the extra pawn.} 34. Nf2 Ba6 $6 {Unnecessary.} (34... Re8 35. Ne4 f5 36. Nd6 Re2 37. Rc8+ Kh7 {Black's d-pawn is now unstoppable and the King is very safe on h7.}) 35. Rc6 Qa1+ (35... Re8 {Was better.} 36. Rxa6 Re2 37. Ra8+ Bf8 $19) 36. Kh2 Bc3 37. Qe3 Bb5 $4 {A blunder which allows White an unexpected chance to escape.} (37... Bd4 {It was vital not to allow White eliminate the fantastic dark squared Bishop.} 38. Qd2 Qf1 39. Ne4 Qg1+ 40. Kg3 Rc8 {A nice way to trap White's King.} 41. Rxc8+ Bxc8 42. Qxd3 Qe1+ 43. Kh2 Bg1+ 44. Kh1 Bf2+ {With a mate to follow on g1.}) 38. Rd6 $4 {Missing the chance.} (38. Rxc3 $1 {Eliminating Black's best piece, even at the cost of being down an exchange. Thanks to the weak dark squares around Black's King, White has very good compensation.} Qxc3 (38... bxc3 $4 {Would be now losing for Black.} 39. Qd4 $1 Qe1 (39... d2 40. Bxd2) 40. Ne4 {41.Nf6 is now a big threat.} d2 41. Bh6 {Mate on g7 is coming.} f6 42. Qd6 Rf7 43. Nxf6+ $18 {White is winning.}) 39. Ne4 Qc6 (39... Qg7 40. Bh6) 40. Qd4 {It is now Black who has to be very precise not to lose the game.}) 38... Qxa2 $4 {Another blunder, perhaps the players were in big time-trouble, as they were yet to complete the 40th move to reach the time control.} 39. Rd5 $2 (39. Qc5 $1 a4 40. Ne4 $18 {Suddenly, all of White's pieces are very active, the d-pawn is not able to promote and Black's b5 Bishop is trapped. White is winning.}) 39... Ba6 $4 (39... Bc6 $1 {Would be the best, as it controls the e4-square, where White's Knight wants to land after retreating the Rook.} 40. Rxd3 (40. Rd6 $2 Re8 41. Qc5 Bxf3 42. gxf3 a4 $19 {White now doesn't have enough time to bring up the pieces towarrds the Black King, as her own King is weak.}) 40... Bg7 $17 {Black would be still better thanks to the extra pawn, but the advantage is definetely still a long way from being decisive.}) 40. Nxd3 $4 {The Knight is not on the right route.} (40. Ne4 $1 {It was vital to activate the Knight!} Qxb3 41. Be5 $1 Bxe5+ (41... Qxd5 $2 42. Nf6+ $18) 42. Rxe5 $18 {Now that the dark squared Bishops are off the board, Black's King is helpless.}) 40... Qxb3 $19 {Now that the 40th move is completed and the time trouble is behind, Black is back to the right track.} 41. Rxa5 Bxd3 42. Qxd3 Rc8 {With White's Knight off the board and Black's dark squared Bishop still alive, Galliamova didn't have to worry anymore about her King's safety and proceed to converting the extra pawn.} 43. Qe3 Qc4 44. Be5 b3 45. Bxc3 Qxc3 46. Qb6 (46. Qxc3 Rxc3 47. h4 Kf8 $19 {The Rook endgame is still lost, as Black's King will simply approach the b-pawn.}) 46... Qd2 47. Ra4 Rc2 48. Qb8+ Kh7 49. Qg3 b2 50. Ra7 b1=Q 51. Rxf7+ Kh6 {A very interesting game which promised to be a masterpiece by Galliamova, who managed to make all of the opening's ideas appear on the board if not the time-trouble blunders.  Conclusions:  1. Remember about the concept of a Bishop on top of a diagonal.  2. Don't relax too soon and try to be as precise as possible in converting the advantage, don't allow your opponent counterplay.  3. It is often that a player has the fixed idea that a pieces' value is higher by default (like the Rook vs the c3 Bishop here) and they don't even take into count the option of an 'uneven' trade. Keep you mind open!  4. Never give up and fight until the end, trying to get some practical chances; no one ever won by resigning.} 0-1

[Event "Gibraltar Masters 2017"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Gopal, Narayanan"]
[Black "Caruana, Fabiano"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "C76"]
[PlyCount "106"]
[EventDate "2022.10.08"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 a6 6. Ba4 d6 {Entering one of the mainlines.} 7. d4 Bd7 {Solving the pin issues.} 8. d5 {White closes up the centre, entering pawn structures which remind a lot about the King Indian's ones.} Nce7 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. c4 h6 {Taking the g5-square under control, so that White's Knight won't be able to jump thereafter our playing f5.} 11. Nc3 f5 {Fighting against White's central pawn constructure.} 12. Ne1 {White wants to consolidate the e4-pawn by playing f3, while the Knight from e1 heads to d3 in order to prepare c5. So far, the game follows the course, or does the course follow the game? Anyhow, we're in the book!} Nf6 13. f3 O-O 14. Nd3 g5 {This position is very well known and Black has tried almost all the possible moves. There is nothing wrong with this one, we can keep it as an alternative to the one suggested in the course.} (14... Rf7 {Is the move recommended in the course.} 15. Be3 Raf8 16. c5 g5 {The resulting positions are however quite similar to the one in the game.}) 15. exf5 $6 {Takes off the pressure too soon; perhaps White was trying to keep the matters as simple as possible.} (15. Bd2 {Is the main move as it keeps the tension in the centre.} Rf7 16. Nf2 f4 {Black's idea is simple: build up an attack on the Kingside.} 17. Rc1 {White has to organize counterplay on the Queenside.} h5 18. b4 g4 19. c5 Kh8 {Freeing the g8-square for the Rook. I believe Black's chances are better, as the Kingside attack is much more dangerous than White's one on the Queenside.}) 15... Qxf5 $5 {We need the Knight on e7 in order to put pressure on the d5-pawn. It can be increased by means of c6, b5.} 16. Nf2 b5 17. Qe2 c6 {Fabiano managed to challenge White's pawn chain in almost all the possible ways and White will now struggle to keep it together.} 18. Nfe4 (18. cxb5 cxd5 $5 {What a nice centre!} 19. bxa6 Qc8 {Black is better thanks to the evry pretty centre and the upcoming pressure via the a- and b-files.}) 18... Nxe4 19. Nxe4 bxc4 {Black finds a way to complicate things as much as possible; quite understandable when trying to win vs a lower-rated opponent.} 20. Nxd6 Qg6 21. Nxc4 cxd5 22. Nxe5 Qe6 23. Re1 Nf5 {Black wants to put even more pressure on the e5-Knight by playing 24...Rfe8.} 24. Nd3 {The best square for White's Knight.} (24. Ng4 $2 {Wouldn't be good as the Knight on g4 does fewer things than it would do from d3.} Qb6+ 25. Kh1 Rae8 26. Qf1 Qd4 $17 {With a better position for Black because White's Rook on a1 and the Bishop are stuck on their initial squares.}) 24... Qb6+ 25. Kh1 Rae8 26. Qf1 (26. Qxe8 $4 Rxe8 27. Rxe8+ Kf7 28. Re1 Qd4 $19 {Black is winning, as White's piece coordination is terrible.}) 26... Rxe1 27. Nxe1 $6 (27. Qxe1 Qb5 28. Qf1 {Would have been a better try; it seems to me that the Knight o d3 is the most important piece in White's position and it wasn't the right time to give up on that.}) 27... Qg6 {Preparing some mating nets. After 28...Bd4, there will be threats of 29...Ng3+, followed by a mate on h5.} 28. Qd3 Bd4 29. g4 {White is defending well so far.} Re8 30. Be3 $2 {Here comes the mistake.} (30. Qd1 $1 {The only move. It looks very unnatural to have all the pieces on the 1st rank, but the position would be within the equality margins.} Nh4 31. Ng2 $11) 30... Rxe3 $19 31. Qxf5 Qxf5 32. gxf5 Bxb2 {Black is now winning, thanks to the passed d-pawn and the much better pieces.} 33. Rd1 Bc3 34. Nc2 Re2 35. Nd4 Rxa2 36. Rd3 Bxd4 37. Rxd4 Ra5 38. Kg2 Kf7 39. Kg3 Kf6 40. Kg4 Rc5 41. f4 gxf4 42. Rd3 Ke5 43. Rd1 Rc4 44. Ra1 h5+ 45. Kg5 f3 46. Rf1 Rg4+ 47. Kxh5 Rf4 48. Kg5 Rxf5+ 49. Kg4 f2 50. h4 Ke4 51. h5 Rf7 52. h6 Ke3 53. Kg5 Ke2 {Conclusions:   1. In these structures with a closed centre, each side has pawn chains and the best plan is usually to attack them in order to weaken them.    2. Try to combine attacking the pawn chain with creating threats against White's King.   3. When playing vs a lower rated opponent and needing a win- trying to keep things as complicated as possible and giving them as many choices as you can is a good idea, as they might choose the wrong path at some point.} 0-1

[Event "Candidates Tournament 2018"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Karjakin, Sergey"]
[Black "Mamedyarov, Shakhriyar"]
[Result "0-1"]
[PlyCount "142"]
[EventDate "2022.10.08"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. c3 a6 {Shakhriyar Mamedyarov is one of the main ambassadors of the Smyslov System these days and his choice of opening in such an important tournament as the 2018 Candidates is I believe a proof that the line is very sound at the highest level.} 5. Bxc6 {One of the sidelines. White aims to get a pawn majority in the centre.} dxc6 6. d4 exd4 7. cxd4 Bg4 {Pressuring the d4-pawn.} 8. Qb3 {White gets rid of the pin on the h5-d1 diagonal and attacks the b7-pawn.} Bxf3 9. gxf3 Bg7 {As mentioned in the course, Black doesn't want to take on d4 before having the option to meet Qxb7 with short castle.} 10. Be3 (10. Qxb7 Ne7 {Black wants to castle short and claim compensation for the sacrificed pawn due to being ahead with the development.}) 10... Ne7 {Ready to castle now, thus we can consider taking the d4-pawn on our next move.} 11. Nc3 Bxd4 12. Bxd4 $2 {Is bad, as White's King will no longer be able to castle long, while castling short will also be dangerous, as the pawn structure on the Kingside is compromised.} (12. O-O-O $5 {Bringing the King to safety was better.} c5 13. Qxb7 O-O {Black has good compensation here; check out the corresponding line in the course for a more detailed analysis of this line.}) 12... Qxd4 13. Qxb7 O-O 14. Qxc7 {Missing a very interesting tactical possibility Black could come up with, which Shakh did not spot either.} (14. Rd1 {Was another option.} Qe5 15. Rd7 Rfc8 {Protecting the c7-pawn and arguing that White's King is very far from safe in the centre. Rab8 is now a threat to consider, as the b2-pawn is unprotected.} 16. O-O Qg5+ 17. Kh1 Qf6) 14... Rab8 {Another way of sacrificing the Knight; not such effective though, as White has time to castle.} (14... Nd5 $1 {Tempting White to win a piece but open up the e-file against his King.} 15. Nxd5 (15. Qxc6 $4 Nb4 $19 {Wins material.}) (15. exd5 $2 Qd3 {Now White's King is in big trouble; 16...Rae8 with a mate following shortly is the threat.} 16. Ne2 (16. Qf4 Rae8+ 17. Ne4 cxd5 {Wins back the piece, while White's issues with the King's safety are far from being solved.}) 16... Rae8 17. O-O {White returns back the Knight hoping for it to change the fate of the poor King.} Rxe2 {But the King is still open and Black can organize various threats against it.} 18. Qxc6 Qxf3 $17 {With a significant advantage for Black thanks to the issues White has with the King's safety. 19...Re4, 20...Rg4 is a threat.}) 15... cxd5 16. Qc3 {Hoping to save the day in a Rook endgame.} Qxc3+ 17. bxc3 Rae8 $15 {Winning back the pawn, which will leave White with a worse position because of the inferior pawn structure (4 islands of pawns vs 2 islands).}) 15. O-O (15. Qxe7 Rxb2 16. O-O Qxc3 {Would transpose to the game.}) 15... Rxb2 16. Qxe7 (16. Nd1 $5 Rb5 {White doesn't have time to take on e7, as the Rook on a1 is hanging.} 17. Ne3 {The Knight is much better here, close to White's King, as it can participate in its defense. The position remains complicated, with chances for both sides.}) 16... Qxc3 17. Kg2 {The only way to protect the f3-pawn. White now wants to continue with 18.Rac1, either forcing a pair of Rooks trade after 18...Rc2, or the c6-pawn will be captured.} Rc2 18. Rad1 {18.a4 was perhaps better, keeping the material balance.} Rxa2 19. Rc1 {Is still fine, but will inquire precise play from White's side.} Rc2 20. Rxc2 Qxc2 21. Ra1 Qc4 22. Qb7 Qb5 {A good practical try.} 23. Qxa6 ({The Queen swap is not an option for White, as after} 23. Qxb5 axb5 {Black's 2 connected passed pawns will be decisive.}) 23... Qg5+ 24. Kf1 Qf6 {Black still has better chances, once again thanks to White's issues about the King's safety, but also thanks to the passed c-pawn and better pawn structure on the Kingside.} 25. Kg2 Rb8 {Aiming for the b3-square, to put some extra pressure on the f3-pawn.} 26. Ra5 $2 {Isn't great. It was necessary to cover the b3-square so that Black's Rook wouldn't land it. It could be achieved by both 26.Ra3 and 26.Qa3.} Rb3 27. Qc8+ $2 {The Queen goes in the wrong direction.} (27. Qe2 {Was the best, as the Queen keeps an eye on the c-pawn and also protects the f3 one.} Kg7 28. Rc5 h6 {Black could still try to slowly improve the position and create small threats to White. Even though the engines hold the position for White, as a human being, the defence is much more unpleasant and less likely to be successful.}) 27... Kg7 28. Qg4 Rb5 {Forces the trade of Rooks, as otherwise, 29...Rg5 wins the Queen.} 29. Rxb5 cxb5 {This endgame is still defendable, as the material is even, but the task is not an easy one, as White's pawns are not likely to advance, while Black has a very nice passed pawn.} 30. Qd7 Qg5+ 31. Kf1 Qe5 32. h4 b4 33. Qb7 Qc3 34. e5 {White protects the f3-pawn and hopes to be able to organize some perpetual check if his Queen will be able to land on f6.} b3 35. Kg2 Qc4 36. Qb6 {White threatens to go for that perpetual by means of 37.Qf6+.} h6 {Freeing the h7-square for the King to hide.} 37. Kg3 Qd5 {The best place for Black's Queen, as it completes a lot of tasks: protects the b3 and f7 pawns, but also attacks the e5 one.} 38. f4 {However, it is still very complicated for Black to make progress because of the danger of a perpetual check.} Kh7 39. Qb8 Qc4 40. f3 Qc3 41. Qf8 Qc4 42. Qb8 Kg7 43. Qb6 Qd5 44. Qb8 Qd1 45. Qb7 {47.Qb6, covering the g1-square was perhaps more accurate.} (45. Kg2 $4 {Would be bad, as Black is in time to promote the b-pawn.} Qc2+ 46. Kg3 b2 47. Qd8 b1=Q 48. Qf6+ Kg8 49. Qd8+ Kh7 {Is a win for Black.}) 45... Qg1+ 46. Kh3 Qe3 47. Kg2 (47. Kg3 $4 {Losses now.} g5 $1 48. hxg5 hxg5 49. fxg5 Qxe5+ 50. Kf2 b2 {Black's pawn will promote.}) 47... Qe2+ (47... Qxf4 $2 48. e6 {Forces the trade of the b-pawn for the e-one.} Qf6 49. Qxb3 Qxe6 50. Qc3+ {With good chances for White to save the game.}) (47... g5 48. hxg5 hxg5 49. f5 {White holds the position, as compared to the line where White's King on g3, Black doesn't take now on e5 with a check.}) 48. Kg3 Qe1+ 49. Kg2 $4 (49. Kh3 {Was the only good move.} Qe3 50. Kg2 {Would very likely end with a draw, but the task proved too difficult even for the 'Minister of Defence'.}) 49... Qe3 $19 {Zugzwang. It was obligatory to get to this position with Black to move. White losses the game now.} 50. Qb4 {Doesn't help to keep the position together.} g5 $1 51. hxg5 hxg5 52. fxg5 Qe2+ 53. Kg3 Qxe5+ $4 (53... b2 $1 {The only winning move.} 54. e6 Qe5+ 55. Kg2 fxe6 $19 {And Black will be able to first take the g5-pawn with the King and then threaten to promote to a Queen, while the King will be able to run away from checks.}) 54. Kf2 $6 {Is also ok, but makes the defense trickier.} (54. f4 $1 {Black is not getting the g-pawn anymore.} Qe3+ 55. Kg4 Qe2+ 56. Kg3 Qc2 57. Qd4+ $11 {And there's no way for Black to hide from a perpetual with White's g-pawn alive, controlling the f6-square.}) 54... Qh2+ 55. Ke3 Qg1+ 56. Kf4 Qc1+ 57. Kg4 Qe3 58. Kg3 $4 {The fatal error, giving up the g5-pawn with a check.} (58. f4 {The only way to draw, keepiing the g5-pawn alive.} Qg1+ 59. Kf3 Qd1+ 60. Kg3 Qd3+ 61. Kg4 $11) 58... Qxg5+ 59. Kf2 Qd5 60. Ke3 Kg6 61. Ke2 Kf6 62. Ke3 Ke6 63. Qb6+ Kd7 64. Qa7+ Kc6 65. Qa6+ Kc5 66. Qa4 Qc4 67. Qa5+ Kc6 68. Qa1 Kb5 69. Qb2 Kb4 70. Kd2 Qf4+ 71. Ke1 Qh4+ {White resigned as he can't avoid the trade of Queens after a check on the 1st rank followed by another one on the 2nd rank.  Conclusions:   1. King's safety is very important, that's why when one doesn't follow one of the basic chess principles 'castle first, and then start active plans.' various tactical motifs may appear: stay alert for them!   2. In a game when one has to defend a long-term worse and passive position, try to avoid sacrificing material for activity unless you see a forced way to a draw.   3. On the other hand, when playing this type of position for the stronger side; be patient and slowly improve the position and try to make your opponent solve little problems all the time. Eventually, everyone gets tired and no one is blunder proof.} 0-1

[Event "Wolrd Blitz Championship, Warsaw 2021"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ter Sahakyan, S.."]
[Black "Tang, Andrew"]
[Result "0-1"]
[PlyCount "116"]
[EventDate "2022.10.08"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. c3 a6 5. Bc4 f5 {The aggressive line. 5...Bg7 is the alternative; check thecorresponding chapter in the course for more on it. Andrew is very well known in the online world for his fantastic skills in Blitz and Bullet. The Smyslov Ruy Lopez is a weapon he relies upon a lot.} 6. d3 Bg7 {Planning to close up White's Bishop on c1 by means of f4.} 7. Ng5 {A modern game played at the latest over the board World Blitz Championship. White tried some new ideas, but Black was able to neutralize them.} Nh6 {Covering the f7-square.} 8. a4 {White tries to take some space on the Queenside so that the c4-Bishop wouldn't be disturbed.} f4 $1 {Black closes up White's c1-Bishop. It is clear that he will then want to play on the Kingside.} 9. h4 Qe7 10. Nd2 d6 {Both sides continue their development.} 11. b4 Bf6 {Disturbing the Kinght on g5.} 12. Ndf3 $5 {Perhaps White overestimated a bit his position.} ({Was better, keeping things complicated, with chances for both sides.} 12. Ngf3 Bg4 13. Qb3 Nf7 {Preparing to castle short.} 14. Bb2 O-O 15. d4 {With interesting play.}) ({Interesting was} 12. Ba3 $5 {which still brings a very complicated game} Bxg5 13. hxg5 Nf7 14. Bxf7+ Qxf7 15. b5 $36) 12... Ng4 {It is now clear that the Knight from g5 will have to land to h3, from where it won't do much.} 13. g3 {White fights against Black's pawn chain, trying to compromise it.} h6 14. Nh3 g5 {It is now very difficult for White, as his Knights don't have enough space.} 15. Nhg1 (15. Bd2 {Was the better move. However, we have to remember that it was a Blitz game. From now on, mistakes were made by both sides.} Ne3 $1 16. fxe3 fxg3 {With very nice compensation, 17...g4 is coming!}) 15... Qg7 16. Qe2 Be7 17. Bb2 Bd7 18. Bd5 Nd8 19. d4 $2 c6 (19... fxg3 $1 20. fxg3 Rf8 $17 {White would be in big trouble.}) 20. Bb3 Ne6 21. O-O-O O-O-O 22. Kb1 Bf6 23. d5 cxd5 24. Bxd5 Nc7 {White hasn't managed to make any progress on the Kingside; the Rook on h1 and the Knight on g1 are very passive.} 25. Bb3 Be7 26. Ne1 {Making room for the g1-Knight.} Nf6 27. Ngf3 Kb8 28. Nd2 Rhf8 (28... fxg3 {Was better.} 29. fxg3 gxh4 30. gxh4 Qg6 $15 {Pressuring the e4-pawn.}) 29. hxg5 hxg5 30. gxf4 exf4 31. Nd3 Qg6 32. f3 Nh5 33. Rhe1 Ng3 34. Qf2 Bf6 $4 {Leaves the d6-pawn unprotected but also does nothing against White threatening to infiltrate with the Queen on b6.} (34... g4 {It was vital to organize some counterplay and fight against White's central pawn chain.} 35. Nc4 gxf3 36. Na5 Ne2 37. Qb6 Qxe4 $19 {Black is in time to protect b7.}) 35. Ka1 $2 (35. Nc4 $18 Bg7 36. Na5 {And Black's King is in big trouble, as 37.Qb6 is coming.}) 35... d5 {35...Qg7, attacking the c3-pawn would be better.} 36. e5 $2 (36. exd5 Qxd3 37. Ne4 Nxe4 38. Rxe4 {Trapping Black's Queen would be much better.}) 36... Be7 37. Nc5 Bc8 38. c4 d4 39. Nde4 (39. Bxd4 {Isn't too good either.} g4 40. Nde4 Nxe4 41. Rxe4 g3 {WIth the g3 pawn becoming very dangerous, Black's advantage also becomes significant.}) 39... Nf5 40. b5 axb5 41. cxb5 Qb6 42. Nd3 Ne3 43. Rc1 Ncd5 (43... Nxb5 $1 44. axb5 Qa5+ 45. Kb1 Qxb5 46. Ndc5 Bf5 $18 {Would be devastating for White.}) 44. Nec5 Bf5 45. Qd2 $2 (45. Bxd4 {was better, but still quite unpleasant for White.}) 45... Nc3 $1 {The triumph of Black's Knights!} 46. Bxc3 dxc3 47. Qxc3 Rc8 48. Qd4 Ka8 {Prophylaxy!} 49. Bd5 Rc7 50. a5 {Desperation.} Qxa5+ 51. Kb1 Qxb5+ 52. Nb3 Bxd3+ 53. Kb2 Rfc8 $4 {Big blunder.} (53... Rc2+ {Would be winning on the spot.} 54. Rxc2 Nxc2 $19) 54. Ra1+ Qa6 {Only move, as a mate comes on a7 after 54...Kb8.} 55. Rxa6+ Bxa6 {Black has still enough material for the Queen to be better.} 56. Be4 Kb8 57. Ra1 $4 {The last blunder.} (57. Rc1 {Was the only move.} Rxc1 58. Nxc1 Rd8 59. Qa4 Nc4+ {And the game might have continued for a long time.}) 57... Rd8 {White's Queen is trapped.} 58. Qb6 (58. Qa4 Rc4 59. Qa2 (59. Qa5 Rxe4 $19) 59... Rh8 $1 {An elegant way to finish, there is no way to stop 60...Rh2!}) 58... Nc4+ {Conclusions:  1. The 5...f5 idea is a very interesting one and provokes your opponent to try to punish you and take more risks than usual, as f5 looks like a move that goes against all the basic chess principles. However. it is not the case.  2. Remember about the principle of restriction. Whenever you can restrict one of your opponent's pieces, go for it; less space for a piece means more struggle (the c1 Bishop, the f3 and h3 Knights here).  3. Don't forget that even in positions that we play in a strategical key, the sacrifices are still in place (15.Bd2- Ne3).  4. Don't play Blitz. Just joking, we all know too well how it is to play on seconds with your pieces and heart jumping all over.} 0-1

